(21, NULL, 'CBC-complete blood count', 'EXP0021', '500', '299', 'Same Day', 'Fasting not Required', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Complete Blood Count (CBC) is a common blood test that measures red blood cells, white blood cells, hemoglobin, hematocrit, and platelets to evaluate overall health', 'Blood infection,Blood cancer , Anemia', '<p>A Complete Blood Count (CBC) is a comprehensive test that assesses levels of red blood cells, white blood cells, platelets, hemoglobin, and hematocrit in the blood, providing crucial information about overall health and detecting various medical conditions.</p>', '<p>A Complete Blood Count (CBC) is a comprehensive test that assesses various components of blood, including red and white blood cells, hemoglobin, hematocrit, and platelets. It helps diagnose conditions like anemia, infections, and blood disorders, providing vital information for medical diagnosis and treatment planning.</p>', '2024-07-09 17:50:36', '2024-07-09 18:04:31', NULL, 0),
(22, NULL, 'ESR- erythrocyte sedimentation rate', 'EXP0022', '180', '99', 'Same Day', 'Overnight Fasting for 9-12 hours', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'ESR (Erythrocyte Sedimentation Rate) measures how quickly red blood cells settle at the bottom of a test tube, indicating inflammation.', 'Infection & Inflammation', '<p>The Erythrocyte Sedimentation Rate (ESR) is a non-specific blood test that measures the rate at which red blood cells settle in a vertical tube over a specified period, usually one hour. It is an indirect measure of inflammation in the body.</p><p>During the test, anticoagulated blood is placed in a narrow tube, and the rate at which the red blood cells settle (sediment) is measured in millimeters per hour (mm/hr). The principle behind ESR is based on the fact that inflammatory proteins, such as fibrinogen and immunoglobulins, cause red blood cells to clump together and settle faster than normal. Higher levels of these proteins in the blood indicate increased inflammation.</p><p>ESR is influenced by various factors including age, sex, anemia, and certain medications. Normal ESR values differ by age and gender, with slightly higher rates in females. It is important to interpret ESR results in the context of a patient\'s overall clinical picture and other diagnostic tests</p>', '<p>Clinically, ESR is used as a screening tool for a wide range of conditions associated with inflammation, such as infections, autoimmune diseases (like rheumatoid arthritis and lupus), certain cancers, and chronic inflammatory conditions. Changes in ESR over time can also help monitor disease activity and response to treatment.</p><p>However, ESR is not specific to any particular disease and can be influenced by non-inflammatory conditions as well. Therefore, it is often used in conjunction with other tests to aid in diagnosis and monitoring of diseases. Despite its limitations, ESR remains a valuable and widely used tool in clinical practice for assessing inflammatory status and guiding further investigations.</p>', '2024-07-09 18:02:16', '2024-07-09 18:02:16', NULL, 0),
(23, 3, 'Lipid profile/cholesterol profile', 'EXP0023', '800', '449', 'Same day', 'Overnight fasting for 9-12 hours', 'Overnight fasting 9-12 hours', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'A lipid profile is a blood test measuring cholesterol and triglycerides, including total cholesterol, LDL (bad) cholesterol, HDL (good) cholesterol, and triglycerides, to assess cardiovascular health.', 'Arteries blockage', '<p>A lipid profile is a comprehensive blood test that measures the levels of specific fats and cholesterol in the bloodstream. This test includes several key components:</p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;1.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Total Cholesterol: This measures the overall amount of cholesterol in the blood. Cholesterol is a fatty substance essential for building cell membranes but can be harmful in excess.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;2.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Low-Density Lipoprotein (LDL) Cholesterol: Often referred to as bad cholesterol, high levels of LDL can lead to plaque buildup in the arteries, increasing the risk of heart disease and stroke.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;3.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;High-Density Lipoprotein (HDL) Cholesterol: Known as good cholesterol, HDL helps remove other forms of cholesterol from the bloodstream. Higher levels of HDL are associated with a lower risk of heart disease.</p><h3>&nbsp;</h3>', '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;4.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Triglycerides: These are a type of fat found in the blood. Elevated levels can increase the risk of heart disease, particularly when combined with high LDL or low HDL levels.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;5.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Very Low-Density Lipoprotein (VLDL) Cholesterol: VLDL is another type of lipoprotein that primarily carries triglycerides in the blood. Elevated levels of VLDL can contribute to plaque formation in the arteries.</p><p>A lipid profile is crucial for evaluating cardiovascular health and guiding treatment decisions. It can indicate the need for lifestyle changes or medication to manage cholesterol levels and reduce the risk of heart-related conditions. Regular monitoring through lipid profiles helps in maintaining optimal cardiovascular health.</p>', '2024-07-12 01:40:26', '2024-07-20 17:35:05', NULL, 0),
(24, NULL, 'panel 1', 'EXP0024', '123', '123', '1', 'Fasting not Required', 'Est ex nihil sint mi', 'Explicabo Inventore', 'admin/test/icon/icon.png', 'admin/test/banner/banner.png', 'Est ex nihil sint mi', NULL, '<p>Est ex nihil sint mi</p>', '<p>Est ex nihil sint mi</p>', '2024-07-12 14:16:09', '2024-07-12 17:00:15', '2024-07-12 17:00:15', 0),
(25, 1, 'Test', 'EXP0025', '124', '123', 'Cvc', 'Ccc', 'Ccc', 'Ccc', 'admin/test/icon/icon.png', 'admin/test/banner/banner.png', 'Cccc', NULL, '<p>Ccc</p>', '<p>Ccf</p>', '2024-07-12 14:17:32', '2024-07-12 17:00:02', '2024-07-12 17:00:02', 0),
(26, 6, 'Liver Function test - LFT  with GGT', 'EXP0026', '800', '449', 'Same day', 'Fasting not required', NULL, NULL, 'admin/test/icon/icon.png', 'admin/test/banner/banner.png', 'LFT, or liver function test, is a blood test that measures enzymes, proteins, and substances produced by the liver to assess its health and function. It helps diagnose liver diseases, monitor treatment efficacy, and check for liver damage due to medications or other factors.', NULL, '<p>Liver function tests (LFTs) are a group of blood tests that provide information about the state of a patients liver. These tests measure the levels of various enzymes, proteins, and substances the liver produces or processes, helping to assess its health and function. Key components of LFTs include:</p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;1.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Alanine aminotransferase (ALT) and Aspartate aminotransferase (AST): These enzymes are released into the blood when liver cells are damaged. Elevated levels often indicate liver damage or inflammation, possibly due to hepatitis, fatty liver disease, or alcohol abuse.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;2.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Alkaline phosphatase (ALP): This enzyme is linked to bile ducts; high levels may indicate blockages or issues with bile flow.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;3.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Gamma-glutamyl transferase (GGT): Elevated GGT can signal bile duct problems or alcohol-related liver disease.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;4.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Bilirubin: This waste product results from the breakdown of red blood cells. High bilirubin levels can cause jaundice and indicate liver or bile duct issues.</p>', '<p>Albumin and Total Protein: These measure the livers ability to produce proteins essential for various bodily functions. Low levels can signify liver dysfunction.</p><p>LFTs are crucial for diagnosing liver diseases, monitoring the progression of known liver conditions, and assessing the livers response to treatments. They can also help detect liver damage caused by medications, toxins, or other factors, guiding appropriate medical interventions.</p>', '2024-07-12 16:45:26', '2024-07-12 17:05:01', '2024-07-12 17:05:01', 0),
(27, NULL, 'CD3/CD4/CD8 Markers - Immune Deficiency Package', 'EXP0027', '3300', '2600', 'Within 3 Days', 'Fasting not required', NULL, NULL, 'admin/test/icon/icon.png', 'admin/test/banner/banner.png', 'CD3, CD4, and CD8 are markers on T cells, a type of white blood cell. CD3 is present on all T cells, CD4 on helper T cells, and CD8 on cytotoxic T cells. These markers help identify and classify T cells for immune function analysis and disease diagnosis.', NULL, '<p>CD3, CD4, and CD8 are important markers found on the surface of T cells, a critical component of the immune system. These markers are used to identify and differentiate various subsets of T cells, each playing a unique role in immune response.</p><p>CD3: This marker is present on all mature T cells. CD3 is a complex of proteins that associates with the T cell receptor (TCR) and is essential for TCR signaling. It plays a critical role in activating T cells in response to antigens.</p><p>CD4: Found on helper T cells (Th cells), CD4 molecules interact with major histocompatibility complex (MHC) class II molecules on antigen-presenting cells. Helper T cells are crucial for orchestrating the immune response, including the activation of other immune cells, production of cytokines, and aiding in B cell antibody production. They are pivotal in defending against infections and in immune regulation.<br>&nbsp;</p>', '<p>CD8: This marker is present on cytotoxic T cells (Tc cells), which interact with MHC class I molecules. Cytotoxic T cells are responsible for directly killing infected cells, cancer cells, and other damaged or dysfunctional cells. They are vital for controlling intracellular infections and maintaining cellular integrity.</p><p>The balance and ratio of CD4 to CD8 T cells are important indicators of immune health. For example, a decreased CD4/CD8 ratio can be seen in HIV infection, where CD4 cells are specifically targeted and destroyed. Measuring these markers is essential in diagnosing and monitoring various immune-related conditions and infections.</p>', '2024-07-12 16:53:18', '2024-07-12 17:04:57', '2024-07-12 17:04:57', 0);
