(119, NULL, 'Basic Vitamin profile', 'EXP0119', '2398', '1098', 'Same day', 'Overnight fasting is 9-12 hours', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'A Vitamin B12 and D3 test measures the levels of these essential nutrients in the blood. Vitamin B12 is crucial for nerve function, red blood cell production, and DNA synthesis, while Vitamin D3 supports bone health by aiding calcium absorption and maintaining immune function. Deficiency in Vitamin B12 can lead to anemia, fatigue, and neurological issues, whereas a lack of Vitamin D3 can cause bone disorders like osteoporosis and rickets. These tests help diagnose deficiencies, ensuring proper treatment through diet or supplements. Regular monitoring is especially important for individuals at risk, such as the elderly, vegetarians, vegans, and those with limited sun exposure.\r\n B12  D3              B12  ,    ,  DNA     ,   D3                  B12    , ,       ,   D3                       ,                        ,  , ,  ,        ', NULL, '<p>A Vitamin B12 and D3 test measures the levels of these essential nutrients in the blood. Vitamin B12, also known as cobalamin, is crucial for nerve function, red blood cell production, and DNA synthesis. It plays a vital role in maintaining the health of the nervous system and is necessary for the formation of red blood cells that carry oxygen throughout the body. Deficiency in Vitamin B12 can lead to symptoms such as fatigue, weakness, neurological issues like numbness or tingling, and in severe cases, megaloblastic anemia.</p><p>Vitamin D3, on the other hand, supports bone health by aiding calcium absorption and maintaining immune function. It is synthesized in the skin upon exposure to sunlight and can also be obtained through dietary sources or supplements. Vitamin D3 deficiency can result in conditions like osteoporosis, rickets (in children), and weakened immune function.</p><p>These tests are instrumental in diagnosing deficiencies of Vitamin B12 and D3, enabling appropriate treatment through dietary adjustments and supplementation. Regular monitoring of these nutrient levels is crucial, especially for individuals at risk such as older adults, vegetarians, vegans, and those with limited sun exposure, to maintain overall health and prevent associated complications.<br>&nbsp;</p>', '<p> B12  D3              B12,      ,  ,    ,  DNA                                 B12   , ,           ,    ,     </p><p> D3,  ,       ,                                              D3   ,  ( ),           </p><p>   B12  D3                                  ,            ,   , ,  ,        </p>', '2024-07-18 14:16:11', '2024-07-20 18:52:48', '2024-07-20 18:52:48', 0),
(120, NULL, 'Vitamin E-Tocopherol', 'EXP0120', '6999', '4499', 'Within 6 days', 'Overnight fasting is 9-12 hours', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Vitamin E is a fat-soluble nutrient known for its antioxidant properties, crucial for protecting cells from oxidative stress caused by free radicals. It exists in eight different forms, with alpha-tocopherol being the most biologically active in humans. Vitamin E plays a vital role in immune function, skin health, and cell signaling pathways. It helps maintain healthy skin, eyes, and strengthens the immune system. Dietary sources rich in Vitamin E include nuts, seeds, vegetable oils, and leafy green vegetables. Deficiency in Vitamin E is rare but can lead to neurological problems and muscle weakness. Regular intake of Vitamin E through a balanced diet supports overall health and well-being.', NULL, '<p> E   -             ,                                                ,  E          ,               </p><p> E      ,  -                  : - , , ,          E          ( )      ,        </p><p>    ,  E        ,                      ,                          ,          </p><p> E     ,                      ,             ,  ,    ,       </p><p>, ,  ,              E                    ,           ,                             </p>', '<p>Vitamin E is a crucial fat-soluble nutrient known for its powerful antioxidant properties, which play a vital role in protecting cells from damage caused by free radicals. Free radicals are unstable molecules that can harm cells and contribute to the development of various diseases, including heart disease and cancer. As an antioxidant, vitamin E helps neutralize these free radicals, thereby reducing oxidative stress and preserving cellular integrity.</p><p>There are eight naturally occurring forms of vitamin E, with alpha-tocopherol being the most biologically active and studied in humans. It is primarily found in plant-based oils, nuts, seeds, and leafy green vegetables. Vitamin E is absorbed in the small intestine and stored in adipose tissue (fat cells) and in the liver, where it can be utilized as needed.</p><p>Beyond its antioxidant function, vitamin E plays a critical role in immune function, supporting the body\'s defenses against infections and illnesses. It also contributes to skin health by protecting against UV radiation damage and promoting skin barrier function. This vitamin is involved in various cellular signaling pathways, influencing gene expression and cell proliferation.</p><p>A deficiency in vitamin E is relatively rare but can occur in individuals with certain medical conditions that affect fat absorption, such as cystic fibrosis or liver disease. Symptoms of deficiency may include muscle weakness, vision problems, impaired immune function, and nerve damage.</p><p>Maintaining adequate vitamin E levels through a balanced diet rich in nuts, seeds, vegetable oils, and green leafy vegetables is essential for overall health and well-being. While supplements are available, they should be used cautiously and under medical supervision, as excessive intake can potentially interfere with blood clotting and increase the risk of bleeding disorders. Regular monitoring of vitamin E status is important for individuals at risk of deficiency or those with specific health concerns to ensure optimal health outcomes.<br>&nbsp;</p>', '2024-07-18 14:22:43', '2024-07-18 14:22:43', NULL, 0);
