(123, NULL, 'CD3/CD4/CD8 Markers- Immune Deficiency Package', 'EXP0123', '2999', '2399', 'Within 3 days', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'A CD3/CD4/CD8 test measures the levels of different types of T lymphocytes (T cells) in the blood. These cells play critical roles in the immune system:\r\n\r\n1. **CD3+ T cells**: These are total T cells, as CD3 is a marker found on all T cells.\r\n2. **CD4+ T cells (Helper T cells)**: These cells assist other cells in the immune response by producing signaling molecules. They are crucial for orchestrating the immune response.\r\n3. **CD8+ T cells (Cytotoxic T cells)**: These cells directly kill virus-infected cells and tumor cells.\r\n\r\nThis test is commonly used to assess immune function, particularly in conditions such as HIV/AIDS, where CD4+ T cell counts are used to monitor disease progression and treatment efficacy. It can also be used to evaluate immune status in other conditions, such as autoimmune diseases or after organ transplantation.', NULL, '<p>The CD3/CD4/CD8 test measures levels of specific T lymphocytes in the blood, providing insight into the immune system\'s status. CD3 is a marker found on all T cells, representing the total T cell population. These cells are crucial for adaptive immunity, recognizing and responding to pathogens.</p><p>CD4+ T cells, also known as helper T cells, play a pivotal role by producing signaling molecules that help direct the immune response. They assist other immune cells in recognizing and responding to infections, and their count is a critical indicator of immune health. Low CD4+ counts, particularly below 200 cells/mm, can signal severe immunodeficiency, as seen in advanced HIV/AIDS.</p><p>CD8+ T cells, or cytotoxic T cells, are responsible for directly attacking and destroying infected or malignant cells. They play a key role in controlling viral infections and tumor surveillance.</p><p>Together, the CD3/CD4/CD8 test provides a comprehensive overview of the immune system\'s functionality. It\'s especially vital in diagnosing and monitoring diseases like HIV/AIDS, where CD4+ T cell counts are crucial for staging and treatment decisions. It also helps in assessing immune recovery post-transplant or in autoimmune diseases.</p>', '<p>CD3/CD4/CD8             ,             CD3           ,                 ,           </p><p>CD4+  ,        ,                              ,              200 /   CD4+   -,    /    ,     </p><p>CD8+  ,    ,                             </p><p> , CD3/CD4/CD8                /         ,  CD4+                                </p>', '2024-07-19 13:11:41', '2024-07-19 13:11:41', NULL, 0),
(124, NULL, 'HPLC HbA2- Beta Thalassemia Screening-HB Electrophoresis', 'EXP0124', '1299', '699', 'Within 2 days', 'Fasting is not Manda', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Hb electrophoresis-HPLC measures the different types of hemoglobin in the blood. Hemoglobin electrophoresis separates hemoglobin variants based on their electrical charge, while HPLC (High-Performance Liquid Chromatography) separates them based on their interaction with the column material. This combined test helps diagnose hemoglobin disorders such as sickle cell anemia, thalassemia, and other hemoglobinopathies by identifying abnormal hemoglobin variants. It provides a detailed profile of hemoglobin types and their relative amounts, aiding in the accurate diagnosis and management of these conditions.', NULL, '<p>Beta thalassemia screening using Hb electrophoresis and HPLC (High-Performance Liquid Chromatography) is a diagnostic procedure to detect and characterize beta thalassemia, a genetic blood disorder that reduces the production of hemoglobin. Hemoglobin is the protein in red blood cells that carries oxygen throughout the body. In beta thalassemia, mutations in the HBB gene lead to deficient or abnormal beta-globin chains, resulting in anemia and other complications.</p><p>**Hb electrophoresis** separates different types of hemoglobin based on their electrical charge. This method helps identify abnormal hemoglobin variants and quantify the proportions of normal and abnormal hemoglobin types.</p><p>**HPLC**, on the other hand, separates hemoglobin variants based on their interaction with the column material under high pressure. HPLC provides precise quantification and identification of hemoglobin fractions, allowing for detailed analysis.</p><p>Together, these tests provide a comprehensive profile of hemoglobin types and their relative amounts in the blood. This is crucial for diagnosing beta thalassemia and distinguishing it from other hemoglobinopathies. The screening identifies carriers (beta thalassemia trait) and individuals with the disease (beta thalassemia major or intermedia), enabling appropriate genetic counseling, management, and treatment options. Accurate diagnosis through this combined method ensures better patient care and informed family planning decisions.</p>', '<p>    (-  )                                                          ,       -       ,        </p><p>** **                                    </p><p>****,  ,                              ,       </p><p>                                    (  )      (    )    ,    ,                             </p>', '2024-07-19 13:18:36', '2024-07-19 13:18:36', NULL, 0),
(125, NULL, 'Urine R/M, Urine Analysis', 'EXP0125', '199', '99', 'Same day', 'Overnight fasting for 9-12 hours', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'A Urine R/M (Routine and Microscopic) test measures various components and properties of urine to assess overall health and detect potential disorders. The routine part involves analyzing the physical and chemical characteristics, such as color, clarity, pH, specific gravity, and the presence of substances like protein, glucose, ketones, and bilirubin. The microscopic part examines urine sediment for cells, crystals, bacteria, and casts. This test helps diagnose conditions like urinary tract infections, kidney disease, diabetes, and liver problems, providing a comprehensive overview of a patient\'s urinary and metabolic health.', NULL, '<p>Urine analysis, also known as urinalysis, is a diagnostic test that examines the content, concentration, and physical properties of urine. It is a common test used to screen for and diagnose a variety of conditions such as urinary tract infections (UTIs), kidney disease, diabetes, and liver disease.</p><p>**Physical Examination**: This involves evaluating the color, clarity, and odor of the urine. Normal urine is usually clear and light yellow. Changes in color or clarity can indicate different medical conditions or the presence of certain substances.</p><p>**Chemical Examination**: Chemical strips, or dipsticks, are used to test for various substances in the urine, including:<br>- **pH**: Indicates the acidity or alkalinity of urine.<br>- **Protein**: High levels can suggest kidney disease.<br>- **Glucose**: Presence may indicate diabetes.<br>- **Ketones**: High levels can be a sign of diabetic ketoacidosis.<br>- **Bilirubin**: May indicate liver disease.<br>- **Blood**: Presence can suggest infection, kidney stones, or other conditions.</p><p>**Microscopic Examination**: A sample of urine is examined under a microscope to look for cells, crystals, bacteria, and other substances. For example:<br>- **Red blood cells**: May indicate bleeding in the urinary tract.<br>- **White blood cells**: Suggest infection or inflammation.<br>- **Casts**: Tube-shaped proteins that can indicate kidney disease.<br>- **Crystals**: Can indicate kidney stones or metabolic issues.</p><p>Urine analysis provides a comprehensive overview of a patient\'s health, aiding in the diagnosis and monitoring of various medical conditions.</p>', '<p> ,      ,        ,                       (UTIs),   ,             </p><p>** **:    ,                                     </p><p>** **:  ,  ,             ,   :<br>- **pH**:        <br>- ****:          <br>- ****:       <br>- ****:         <br>- ****:       <br>- ****:  ,           </p><p>** **:            , ,           :<br>- **  **:         <br>- **  **:       <br>- ****:              <br>- ****:           </p><p>           ,            </p>', '2024-07-19 13:35:58', '2024-07-19 13:35:58', NULL, 0),
(126, NULL, 'Basic Vitamin panel 1', 'EXP0126', '2398', '799', 'Same day', 'Overnight fasting for 9-12 hours', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Vitamin D3 and B12 tests measure the levels of these essential vitamins in the blood. \r\n\r\n- **Vitamin D3** is crucial for calcium absorption, bone health, and immune function. Low levels can lead to bone disorders like osteoporosis and rickets.\r\n  \r\n- **Vitamin B12** is vital for red blood cell formation, neurological function, and DNA synthesis. Deficiency can result in anemia, neurological issues, and cognitive problems.\r\n\r\nThese tests help diagnose deficiencies or excesses, guiding appropriate supplementation or dietary adjustments to maintain optimal health. They are often used to evaluate conditions related to bone health, anemia, and neurological function.', NULL, '<p>Vitamin D3 and B12 are essential nutrients that play critical roles in maintaining overall health, and their levels can be assessed through blood tests.</p><p>**Vitamin D3** is a fat-soluble vitamin important for bone health, immune system function, and calcium absorption. It helps regulate calcium and phosphorus levels in the blood, which are crucial for maintaining healthy bones and teeth. Deficiency in Vitamin D3 can lead to bone disorders such as osteoporosis in adults and rickets in children. It can also contribute to immune system dysfunction and increased risk of chronic diseases. The test for Vitamin D3 measures the concentration of 25-hydroxyvitamin D in the blood, providing insight into the bodys vitamin D status.</p><p>**Vitamin B12** is a water-soluble vitamin essential for red blood cell formation, neurological function, and DNA synthesis. It is crucial for preventing megaloblastic anemia, which is characterized by the production of large, abnormal red blood cells. Vitamin B12 deficiency can lead to symptoms such as fatigue, weakness, numbness, and cognitive disturbances. The test for Vitamin B12 measures the concentration of this vitamin in the blood, helping diagnose deficiencies that can arise from dietary inadequacies, absorption issues, or certain medical conditions.</p><p>Both tests are important for diagnosing deficiencies and guiding appropriate treatment or dietary changes to ensure optimal health.</p>', '<p> D3  B12              ,             </p><p>** D3**  -      ,                       ,           D3        (  )   ( )       ,                   D3    25- D     ,     D      </p><p>** B12**  -       ,   ,  DNA             ,             B12   , , ,          B12          ,    ,  ,               </p><p>                  ,       </p>', '2024-07-19 13:52:44', '2024-07-19 18:30:35', NULL, 0),
(127, NULL, 'Urine Culture', 'EXP0127', '799', '399', 'Within 48-72 hours ( 3 Days )', 'Fasting required', '\"A urine sample should be hold for 3-4 hours in Urinary bladder', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'A urine culture measures the presence and type of bacteria or other microorganisms in the urine. It helps diagnose urinary tract infections (UTIs) by identifying the specific pathogen causing the infection and determining its sensitivity to antibiotics. The test involves growing a urine sample in a lab to see which organisms thrive. Results guide appropriate antibiotic treatment and help manage infections effectively. It can also detect rare pathogens that might not be identified with standard urine tests.', NULL, '<p>A urine culture is a diagnostic test used to detect and identify bacteria or other microorganisms in the urine, which can cause urinary tract infections (UTIs) or other urinary system issues. The test involves collecting a urine sample, which is then cultured in a laboratory to promote the growth of any bacteria present. The culture helps identify the specific type of microorganism responsible for the infection and determines its susceptibility to various antibiotics.</p><p>The process includes inoculating the urine sample onto a growth medium and incubating it under controlled conditions. After a specified period, the lab examines the culture for bacterial growth. If bacteria are present, the lab performs additional tests to identify the strain and assess its sensitivity to different antibiotics. This information is crucial for selecting the most effective treatment.</p><p>Urine cultures are essential for diagnosing infections that are not easily detected by other urine tests and for managing recurring or complicated UTIs. They help ensure appropriate antibiotic therapy, reduce the risk of resistance, and improve patient outcomes.</p>', '<p>                      ,     (UTIs)                    ,                                            </p><p>                       ,                   ,                                     </p><p>                       -     UTIs                 ,               </p>', '2024-07-19 14:04:38', '2024-07-19 14:04:38', NULL, 0),
(128, NULL, 'C ANCA -PR3 - Serin Proteinase 3 Antibodies', 'EXP0128', '2100', '1350', 'Next day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'The C-ANCA PR3 test measures the presence of anti-proteinase 3 (PR3) antibodies in the blood. These antibodies target PR3, an enzyme found in neutrophils, and are associated with certain autoimmune diseases, particularly vasculitis conditions like Wegener\'s granulomatosis and microscopic polyangiitis. The test helps diagnose these conditions by detecting these specific antibodies, indicating immune system activity against the bodys own tissues. It also aids in monitoring disease activity and treatment effectiveness.', NULL, '<p>The C-ANCA PR3 test is a diagnostic blood test that detects the presence of anti-proteinase 3 (PR3) antibodies. These antibodies target PR3, an enzyme found in neutrophils, and are specifically associated with certain autoimmune diseases, notably vasculitis conditions like Wegener\'s granulomatosis (now known as granulomatosis with polyangiitis) and microscopic polyangiitis.</p><p>In autoimmune vasculitis, the immune system erroneously attacks the bodys own blood vessels, leading to inflammation and damage. The presence of C-ANCA (cytoplasmic antineutrophil cytoplasmic antibodies) that target PR3 is a marker of this aberrant immune response.</p><p>The C-ANCA PR3 test is used to diagnose these diseases by confirming the presence of these specific antibodies. It also helps in monitoring disease activity and response to treatment. Elevated levels of C-ANCA PR3 can indicate active disease or a relapse, guiding therapeutic decisions. However, it is used alongside clinical evaluation and other diagnostic tests to provide a comprehensive view of the patient\'s condition.</p>', NULL, '2024-07-19 14:31:15', '2024-07-19 14:31:15', NULL, 0),
(129, NULL, 'Vitamin D-26 OH', 'EXP0129', '899', '599', 'Same day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'The Vitamin D 25-OH (25-hydroxyvitamin D) test measures the level of 25-hydroxyvitamin D in the blood, which is the main form of vitamin D circulating in the body. This test helps assess vitamin D status to ensure adequate levels for bone health, immune function, and overall health. Low levels can indicate deficiencies leading to conditions like osteoporosis and rickets, while high levels might indicate excess supplementation or other health issues. It is a key indicator of vitamin D sufficiency.', NULL, '<p>The Vitamin D 25-OH test, also known as the 25-hydroxyvitamin D test, measures the level of 25-hydroxyvitamin D in the blood. This form of vitamin D is the primary circulating form and a reliable indicator of overall vitamin D status in the body. Vitamin D is crucial for maintaining healthy bones and teeth by regulating calcium and phosphorus levels. It also plays a significant role in immune system function, muscle function, and overall cellular health.</p><p>Vitamin D can be obtained from sunlight exposure, certain foods, and supplements. Once in the body, it undergoes conversion in the liver to 25-hydroxyvitamin D, which is then converted in the kidneys to its active form, calcitriol. The 25-hydroxyvitamin D test is used to diagnose and monitor vitamin D deficiency or excess, which can impact bone health and contribute to conditions such as osteoporosis, rickets in children, and osteomalacia in adults.</p><p>Low levels of 25-hydroxyvitamin D can result from inadequate dietary intake, insufficient sunlight exposure, malabsorption disorders, or certain medical conditions. Conversely, high levels might indicate excessive supplementation. This test provides valuable information for managing and maintaining optimal health.</p>', '<p> D 25-OH ,  25- D        ,   25- D        D          D        D                     ,            </p><p> D     ,                 ,    25- D     ,       ,       25- D     D              ,           ,              </p><p>25- D      ,      ,             ,                         </p>', '2024-07-19 18:51:02', '2024-07-19 18:51:02', NULL, 0),
(130, NULL, 'Haemoglobin', 'EXP0130', '199', '99', 'Same day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Hemoglobin (Hb) is a protein in red blood cells responsible for transporting oxygen from the lungs to the rest of the body and returning carbon dioxide from the tissues to the lungs. An Hb test measures the amount of hemoglobin in the blood, which helps diagnose and monitor conditions like anemia, polycythemia, and other disorders affecting red blood cells. Normal Hb levels vary by age and sex, and deviations can indicate various health issues requiring further investigation.', NULL, '<p>Hemoglobin (Hb) is an iron-containing protein found in red blood cells that plays a critical role in transporting oxygen from the lungs to the tissues and organs throughout the body and carrying carbon dioxide back to the lungs for exhalation. Structurally, hemoglobin is composed of four subunits, each containing a heme group that binds to oxygen. This binding allows hemoglobin to efficiently pick up oxygen in the lungs and release it in the tissues where it is needed.</p><p>The concentration of hemoglobin in the blood is typically measured as part of a complete blood count (CBC) and is expressed in grams per deciliter (g/dL). Normal hemoglobin levels vary depending on age and sex, with typical ranges being 13.8-17.2 g/dL for men and 12.1-15.1 g/dL for women.</p><p>Low hemoglobin levels can indicate anemia, a condition where the body does not have enough red blood cells to adequately transport oxygen. This can be caused by various factors including nutritional deficiencies (like iron, vitamin B12, or folate), chronic diseases, bone marrow problems, or excessive blood loss. High hemoglobin levels may suggest conditions such as polycythemia vera, a bone marrow disorder, or can be a response to living at high altitudes or chronic smoking. Monitoring hemoglobin levels is crucial in diagnosing and managing various health conditions, making it an essential parameter in medical evaluations.</p>', '<p> (Hb)  -                                     ,   -    ,                       tissues        </p><p>           (CBC)              (g/dL)                  ,      13.8-17.2 g/dL     12.1-15.1 g/dL  </p><p>        ,                           ,     ( ,  B12,  ),  ,     ,              ,      ,                          ,           </p>', '2024-07-19 19:13:26', '2024-07-19 19:13:26', NULL, 0),
(131, NULL, 'Amylase', 'EXP0131', '699', '399', 'Same day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Amylase is an enzyme that measures the concentration of amylase in the blood or urine. It plays a crucial role in digesting carbohydrates by breaking down starches into simpler sugars. Elevated levels of amylase can indicate conditions such as pancreatitis, a pancreatic infection, or certain types of cancers. Low levels might suggest pancreatic insufficiency or other related disorders. The amylase test helps diagnose and monitor diseases affecting the pancreas and digestive system.', NULL, '<p>The amylase test measures the concentration of the enzyme amylase in the blood or urine. Amylase is crucial for digesting carbohydrates, as it breaks down starches into simpler sugars, which can then be absorbed by the body. It is primarily produced by the pancreas and salivary glands.</p><p>**In Blood Tests:** Elevated amylase levels can be indicative of conditions affecting the pancreas, such as acute or chronic pancreatitis, pancreatic cancer, or pancreatic duct obstruction. It can also be elevated in conditions like mumps or salivary gland infections.</p><p>**In Urine Tests:** Elevated urine amylase levels can help diagnose and monitor pancreatic disorders, as well as assess the severity of acute pancreatitis.</p><p>**Clinical Significance:**&nbsp;<br>- **Acute Pancreatitis:** A sudden rise in amylase levels is often associated with acute pancreatitis, a condition where the pancreas becomes inflamed.<br>- **Chronic Pancreatitis:** Long-term inflammation of the pancreas can also be reflected in elevated amylase levels.<br>- **Other Conditions:** Elevated levels can be seen in conditions such as kidney failure, gastrointestinal obstruction, or certain types of cancer.</p><p>**Limitations:** Amylase levels alone are not specific to pancreatic conditions and must be interpreted in conjunction with other diagnostic tests and clinical evaluations.</p>', '<p>                    ,         ,                    </p><p>**  :**            ,     ,  ,                 </p><p>**  :**                ,          </p><p>** :**<br>- ** :**             ,     <br>- ** :**             <br>- ** :**     ,  ,             </p><p>**:**                        </p>', '2024-07-19 19:18:14', '2024-07-19 19:18:14', NULL, 0),
(132, NULL, 'Accp Antibodies- ANTI CCP , Anti Cyclic Citrullinated Peptide Antibody', 'EXP0132', '1499', '799', 'Same day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'The Anti-CCP (Anti-Cyclic Citrullinated Peptide) test measures the presence of anti-CCP antibodies in the blood. These antibodies are highly specific for rheumatoid arthritis (RA) and are often present in the early stages of the disease. Elevated levels of anti-CCP antibodies help in diagnosing RA and predicting its severity and progression. This test is valuable for distinguishing RA from other types of arthritis and for guiding appropriate treatment strategies.', NULL, '<p>The Anti-Cyclic Citrullinated Peptide (Anti-CCP) test is a blood test used to detect the presence of anti-CCP antibodies, which are highly specific markers for rheumatoid arthritis (RA). RA is an autoimmune disorder characterized by chronic inflammation of the joints, leading to pain, swelling, and eventual joint damage. The anti-CCP test has become a crucial tool in diagnosing and managing this condition.</p><p>**Mechanism and Function:**<br>Anti-CCP antibodies target cyclic citrullinated peptides, which are proteins that undergo a process called citrullination. This process converts the amino acid arginine into citrulline, altering the protein\'s structure and triggering an autoimmune response in susceptible individuals. The presence of these antibodies indicates an immune system attack on the bodys own tissues, a hallmark of RA.</p><p>**Clinical Significance:**<br>1. **Early Diagnosis:** Anti-CCP antibodies can be detected in the blood early in the course of RA, often before the appearance of clinical symptoms. This early detection is crucial for initiating prompt treatment to slow disease progression and prevent joint damage.<br>2. **Specificity:** The anti-CCP test is highly specific for RA, meaning that a positive result strongly suggests the presence of RA. This helps distinguish RA from other types of arthritis and inflammatory conditions.<br>3. **Prognosis and Severity:** High levels of anti-CCP antibodies are associated with more severe disease and worse prognosis. Patients with positive anti-CCP results are more likely to experience aggressive joint damage and disability.</p><p>**Testing and Interpretation:**<br>The anti-CCP test involves drawing a blood sample, which is then analyzed for the presence of anti-CCP antibodies. Results are reported as positive or negative, with higher levels indicating a stronger likelihood of RA.</p><p>**Conclusion:**<br>The Anti-CCP test is a valuable diagnostic and prognostic tool in the management of rheumatoid arthritis. Its ability to detect RA early and predict disease severity helps healthcare providers tailor treatment plans, improving patient outcomes and quality of life.</p>', NULL, '2024-07-20 11:51:24', '2024-07-20 11:51:24', NULL, 0),
(133, NULL, 'Hepatitis C virus Total Antibodies by Elisa', 'EXP0133', '799', '399', 'Next day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'The Hepatitis C virus (HCV) total antibodies test measures the presence of antibodies against the hepatitis C virus in the blood. These antibodies are produced by the immune system in response to an HCV infection, indicating that a person has been exposed to the virus at some point. This test does not distinguish between a current active infection and a past resolved infection. A positive result usually requires further testing, such as an HCV RNA test, to determine if the virus is still present and if the infection is active.', NULL, '<p>The Hepatitis C virus (HCV) total antibodies test is a blood test that detects the presence of antibodies produced in response to an infection with the hepatitis C virus. This test is used primarily for screening and diagnosing HCV infection. Heres an overview of its clinical applications and significance:</p><p>**Screening and Diagnosis:**<br>The HCV total antibodies test is often the first step in diagnosing hepatitis C. It is recommended for individuals at high risk of HCV infection, such as those with a history of intravenous drug use, recipients of blood transfusions before 1992, healthcare workers exposed to needlestick injuries, and people with certain medical conditions like HIV. The test can also be used for routine screening in populations with higher prevalence rates of HCV infection.</p><p>**Interpreting Results:**<br>- **Positive Result:** Indicates that the person has been exposed to HCV and has developed antibodies. However, a positive result does not distinguish between a past resolved infection and a current active infection. Further testing with an HCV RNA test is necessary to determine if the virus is still present in the blood and if the infection is active.<br>- **Negative Result:** Suggests that the person has never been exposed to HCV, or it is too early after exposure for antibodies to be detectable (the window period).</p><p>**Clinical Significance:**<br>Identifying HCV infection early allows for timely medical intervention, reducing the risk of liver damage, cirrhosis, liver cancer, and preventing the spread of the virus to others. Effective antiviral treatments are available that can cure most cases of hepatitis C, underscoring the importance of early detection through antibody testing.</p>', NULL, '2024-07-20 11:54:40', '2024-07-20 11:54:40', NULL, 0),
(134, NULL, 'Hepatitis A virus -IgM Antibodies, Anti HAV IgM Qualitative', 'EXP0134', '1399', '680', 'Within 3 days', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'The Anti-HAV IgM test measures the presence of immunoglobulin M (IgM) antibodies specific to the hepatitis A virus (HAV) in the blood. These antibodies are produced by the immune system shortly after HAV infection and are indicative of an acute or recent hepatitis A infection. A positive result confirms a current or recent infection, whereas a negative result suggests the absence of a recent infection. This test is crucial for diagnosing hepatitis A, particularly in individuals presenting with symptoms such as jaundice, fatigue, abdominal pain, and elevated liver enzymes.', NULL, '<p>The Anti-HAV IgM test is a diagnostic blood test used to detect immunoglobulin M (IgM) antibodies specific to the hepatitis A virus (HAV). These antibodies are produced by the immune system in response to an HAV infection and are typically present during the acute phase of the illness. The presence of Anti-HAV IgM antibodies indicates a recent or ongoing infection with hepatitis A, a contagious liver disease caused by the hepatitis A virus.</p><p>Hepatitis A is usually transmitted through ingestion of contaminated food or water, or through close contact with an infected person. Symptoms of hepatitis A can include jaundice (yellowing of the skin and eyes), fatigue, abdominal pain, nausea, vomiting, and elevated liver enzymes. Because these symptoms are not specific to hepatitis A, the Anti-HAV IgM test is essential for accurate diagnosis.</p><p>A positive Anti-HAV IgM test result confirms an acute or recent HAV infection, indicating that the individual is in the early stages of the disease or has been recently infected. This information is crucial for implementing appropriate public health measures to prevent the spread of the virus and for managing the patient\'s care.</p><p>Conversely, a negative result suggests that the person has not recently been infected with HAV and is not in the acute phase of hepatitis A. This test, therefore, plays a vital role in diagnosing hepatitis A, particularly in patients with compatible symptoms and in outbreak situations.</p>', NULL, '2024-07-20 11:59:39', '2024-07-20 11:59:39', NULL, 0),
(135, NULL, 'A4- ANDROSTENEDIONE', 'EXP0135', '2590', '1450', 'Within 3 days', 'Overnight Fasting for 9-12 hours', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'An androstenedione test measures the level of androstenedione, a steroid hormone produced by the adrenal glands, ovaries, and testes. It is a precursor to testosterone and estrogen. This test is used to evaluate the function of these glands and can help diagnose conditions such as polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS), adrenal hyperplasia, and androgen-secreting tumors. Elevated or decreased levels of androstenedione can indicate hormonal imbalances and guide the diagnosis and management of disorders related to abnormal androgen production.', NULL, '<p>The androstenedione test measures the concentration of androstenedione, a steroid hormone produced primarily by the adrenal glands, ovaries, and testes. Androstenedione is a precursor to both testosterone and estrogen, making this test important for assessing hormone levels and diagnosing related disorders.</p><p>**Clinical Indications for the Test:**</p><p>1. **Polycystic Ovary Syndrome (PCOS):** Elevated androstenedione levels can indicate PCOS, a condition characterized by hormonal imbalances that can cause irregular menstrual cycles, excessive hair growth, and infertility.</p><p>2. **Adrenal Disorders:** Conditions such as congenital adrenal hyperplasia (CAH) or adrenal tumors can lead to increased androstenedione production. The test helps evaluate adrenal function and diagnose such disorders.</p><p>3. **Hirsutism:** In women with excessive hair growth, an androstenedione test may be used to determine if high levels of androgens are contributing to this symptom.</p><p>4. **Menstrual Irregularities:** Abnormal androstenedione levels can be associated with menstrual irregularities and other reproductive issues.</p><p>5. **Diagnosis of Tumors:** Elevated androstenedione levels may indicate tumors of the adrenal glands or ovaries that secrete androgens.</p><p>**Procedure and Interpretation:**</p><p>The test involves a blood sample, usually taken in the morning when hormone levels are highest. Results are interpreted in the context of other diagnostic tests and clinical symptoms. High levels may suggest conditions like PCOS or adrenal disorders, while low levels could indicate issues with adrenal or ovarian function. This test helps guide appropriate treatment strategies and manage hormonal imbalances effectively.</p>', '<p>       ,           ,                ,               </p><p>**    :**</p><p>1. **   (PCOS):**     PCOS     ,             ,          </p><p>2. ** :**    (CAH)                               </p><p>3. **:**        ,                      </p><p>4. **  :**                </p><p>5. **  :**                    </p><p>**  :**</p><p>       ,                                PCOS          ,                                   </p>', '2024-07-20 12:17:07', '2024-07-20 12:17:07', NULL, 0),
(136, NULL, 'Hepatitis E Virus-IgM Antibodies,  ( HAV IgM )', 'EXP0136', '1299', '790', 'Within 3 days', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'The HEV IgM test measures the presence of Immunoglobulin M (IgM) antibodies against the Hepatitis E virus (HEV) in the blood. This test is used to diagnose a recent or acute Hepatitis E infection. IgM antibodies are typically the first antibodies produced by the immune system in response to an infection, indicating a recent or ongoing infection with HEV. The presence of HEV IgM helps confirm a Hepatitis E infection and can aid in distinguishing it from other types of hepatitis.', NULL, '<p>The HEV IgM test measures the presence of Immunoglobulin M (IgM) antibodies against the Hepatitis E virus (HEV) in the blood. This test is primarily used to diagnose acute Hepatitis E infection, as IgM antibodies are the first antibodies produced in response to the virus and indicate recent or current infection.</p><p>**Clinical Indications for the Test:**</p><p>1. **Acute Hepatitis E Diagnosis:** The HEV IgM test helps confirm a Hepatitis E infection in individuals with symptoms such as jaundice, abdominal pain, nausea, and elevated liver enzymes. It is especially useful in areas with high Hepatitis E prevalence or during outbreaks.</p><p>2. **Differentiation from Other Hepatitis Types:** The test helps distinguish Hepatitis E from other types of hepatitis, such as Hepatitis A, B, and C, which may have similar symptoms but require different management strategies.</p><p>3. **Monitoring High-Risk Populations:** It is useful for monitoring individuals who have been exposed to potential sources of Hepatitis E, such as contaminated water or undercooked pork.</p><p>**Procedure and Interpretation:**</p><p>A blood sample is collected, typically from a vein in the arm. Positive HEV IgM results confirm an acute infection, while negative results may suggest that Hepatitis E is not the cause of the symptoms or that the infection is past the acute phase. This test is crucial for timely diagnosis and appropriate treatment of Hepatitis E.</p>', NULL, '2024-07-20 12:24:06', '2024-07-20 12:24:06', NULL, 0);
