(137, NULL, 'Iron Profile Basic', 'EXP0137', '499', '350', 'Same day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'An iron profile measures various aspects of iron metabolism in the body. It typically includes tests for serum iron (the amount of iron in the blood), ferritin (iron storage levels), transferrin (the protein that carries iron in the blood), and total iron-binding capacity (TIBC, the bloods ability to bind and transport iron). This profile helps diagnose and monitor conditions like iron deficiency anemia, anemia of chronic disease, and iron overload disorders. It provides insights into how well iron is being absorbed and utilized.', 'Hair,Skin & Anxiety', '<p>The iron profile test is a comprehensive diagnostic tool used to assess various aspects of iron metabolism in the body. It is crucial for diagnosing and managing conditions related to iron balance, such as anemia, iron deficiency, and iron overload. The test typically comprises several key components:</p><p>1. **Serum Iron:** Measures the amount of free iron circulating in the blood. It provides insight into the current iron level but can fluctuate based on diet and other factors.</p><p>2.**Transferrin:** Evaluates the concentration of transferrin, a protein that transports iron in the bloodstream. Elevated transferrin levels are commonly seen in iron deficiency, whereas low levels may be indicative of chronic disease or malnutrition.</p><p>3. **Total Iron-Binding Capacity (TIBC):** Measures the maximum amount of iron that can be bound by transferrin. Increased TIBC is often associated with iron deficiency, while decreased TIBC may occur in chronic diseases or conditions affecting transferrin production.</p><p>4. **Transferrin Saturation:** This ratio, calculated from serum iron and TIBC, indicates the percentage of transferrin that is bound with iron. Low transferrin saturation suggests iron deficiency.</p><p>Together, these components provide a detailed overview of iron status, helping healthcare providers diagnose and manage conditions related to iron metabolism effectively.</p>', NULL, '2024-07-20 12:43:12', '2024-07-20 18:17:23', NULL, 0),
(138, NULL, 'Serum Iron', 'EXP0138', '290', '190', 'Same day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Serum iron measures the concentration of free iron in the blood that is available for use by the body. This iron is bound to transferrin, a protein that transports iron to various tissues. The test helps assess iron levels and diagnose conditions such as iron deficiency anemia, chronic diseases, or iron overload disorders. Serum iron levels can fluctuate based on factors like diet, time of day, and recent iron intake, making it a part of a broader assessment of iron status.', NULL, '<p>Serum iron refers to the amount of free iron present in the liquid component of the blood, known as serum. Iron is a vital mineral that is crucial for various physiological functions, primarily for the formation of hemoglobin in red blood cells, which is essential for oxygen transport throughout the body. Serum iron is an important component of an iron profile, used to evaluate overall iron status and diagnose related disorders.</p><p>**Function and Measurement:**<br>Iron in the blood is primarily bound to a protein called transferrin, which transports iron to various tissues where it is needed for cellular functions, including the production of hemoglobin. The serum iron test measures the concentration of this iron in the blood. The measurement is typically expressed in micrograms per deciliter (g/dL) or micromoles per liter (mol/L).</p><p>**Clinical Significance:**<br>1. **Iron Deficiency Anemia:** Low serum iron levels can indicate iron deficiency anemia, a condition where there is insufficient iron to produce adequate amounts of hemoglobin, leading to symptoms like fatigue, weakness, and pallor.<br>2. **Iron Overload Disorders:** High serum iron levels may suggest conditions such as hemochromatosis or iron overload from repeated blood transfusions, where excessive iron accumulation can damage organs.<br>3. **Chronic Diseases:** Fluctuations in serum iron levels can be associated with chronic inflammatory diseases or infections that affect iron metabolism.</p><p>**Testing and Interpretation:**<br>The serum iron test is often performed alongside other tests, such as ferritin, transferrin, and total iron-binding capacity (TIBC), to provide a comprehensive assessment of iron status. Results are interpreted in the context of clinical symptoms and other diagnostic findings to accurately diagnose and manage iron-related conditions.</p>', NULL, '2024-07-20 13:07:38', '2024-07-20 13:07:38', NULL, 0),
(139, NULL, 'TIBC- Total Iron Binding Capacity', 'EXP0139', '290', '190', 'Same day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Total Iron-Binding Capacity (TIBC) measures the maximum amount of iron that can be bound by proteins in the blood, primarily transferrin. It reflects the body\'s ability to transport iron. A high TIBC usually indicates iron deficiency, as the body produces more transferrin to capture available iron. Conversely, low TIBC can be associated with conditions like iron overload or chronic diseases, where transferrin production is reduced. TIBC is often measured alongside serum iron and ferritin to assess overall iron status.', NULL, '<p>Total Iron-Binding Capacity (TIBC) is a blood test that measures the maximum amount of iron that can be bound by proteins in the bloodstream, primarily transferrin. Transferrin is a protein produced by the liver that transports iron throughout the body. TIBC reflects the ability of transferrin to bind and transport iron, providing insights into the bodys iron status.</p><p>The TIBC test is used to evaluate iron metabolism and diagnose iron-related disorders. It is often performed in conjunction with serum iron and ferritin tests to assess overall iron levels and determine the underlying cause of anemia or iron deficiency. A high TIBC typically indicates iron deficiency anemia, as the body produces more transferrin in response to low iron levels. Conversely, a low TIBC can suggest conditions such as iron overload (hemochromatosis), chronic inflammation, or liver disease, where transferrin production is reduced.</p><p>The TIBC test involves drawing a blood sample, which is then analyzed in a laboratory. Results are reported in micrograms per deciliter (g/dL) and are interpreted alongside other iron studies to provide a comprehensive view of an individual\'s iron status and guide appropriate treatment strategies.</p>', NULL, '2024-07-20 13:11:37', '2024-07-20 13:11:37', NULL, 0),
(140, NULL, 'Helicobacter Pylori-H.Pylori IgA Antibodies', 'EXP0140', '2899', '1670', 'Fasting is not mandatory', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'The H. pylori IgA antibody test measures the presence of IgA antibodies specific to *Helicobacter pylori* in the blood. This test helps diagnose an active or recent infection by detecting the immune response to the bacterium. Elevated IgA levels can indicate an ongoing H. pylori infection, which may be associated with conditions like peptic ulcers or chronic gastritis. It is used to assess infection status and guide appropriate treatment.', NULL, '<p>The H. pylori IgA antibody test is a diagnostic tool used to detect the presence of Immunoglobulin A (IgA) antibodies against *Helicobacter pylori* in the blood. *H. pylori* is a bacterium that infects the stomach lining and is linked to various gastrointestinal conditions, including peptic ulcers, chronic gastritis, and an increased risk of gastric cancer.</p><p>**Purpose and Function:**<br>The test measures the immune response to an active or recent *H. pylori* infection. IgA is one of the first antibodies produced by the immune system upon encountering the bacterium, making it a useful marker for detecting early infection. Elevated levels of IgA antibodies suggest the body\'s ongoing immune response to *H. pylori*, indicating a current or recent infection.</p><p>**Clinical Significance:**<br>1. **Diagnosis of Infection:** The H. pylori IgA antibody test helps diagnose an active *H. pylori* infection, especially in symptomatic individuals presenting with signs of peptic ulcers, dyspepsia, or gastritis.<br>2. **Monitoring Treatment:** Post-treatment, a decrease in IgA antibody levels can indicate successful eradication of the bacterium, although it may not be as commonly used for monitoring compared to other methods like the urea breath test or stool antigen test.<br>3. **Complementary Use:** This test is often used alongside other diagnostic methods, such as endoscopy, biopsy, or stool antigen tests, to confirm an *H. pylori* infection and guide appropriate treatment.</p><p>**Limitations:**<br>While the IgA antibody test is helpful in diagnosing active *H. pylori* infection, it may not distinguish between past and current infections due to the persistence of antibodies in the blood even after the infection has been treated. Therefore, it is usually interpreted in conjunction with clinical symptoms and other diagnostic tests.</p>', NULL, '2024-07-20 13:21:24', '2024-07-20 13:21:24', NULL, 0),
(141, NULL, 'Lipase', 'EXP0141', '780', '430', 'Same day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'A lipase test measures the level of lipase, an enzyme produced by the pancreas, in the blood. Lipase helps break down fats into fatty acids and glycerol. Elevated lipase levels can indicate pancreatic disorders such as acute or chronic pancreatitis, pancreatic cancer, or other conditions affecting the pancreas. The test is useful for diagnosing and monitoring these conditions, as well as assessing abdominal pain and digestive issues.', NULL, '<p>The lipase test measures the concentration of lipase, an enzyme primarily produced by the pancreas, in the blood. Lipase plays a crucial role in the digestion of dietary fats by breaking them down into fatty acids and glycerol, which can be easily absorbed by the intestines. In addition to the pancreas, smaller amounts of lipase are produced by the stomach and salivary glands.</p><p>Clinically, the lipase test is used to diagnose and monitor pancreatic disorders. Elevated levels of lipase in the blood can indicate acute or chronic pancreatitis, conditions characterized by inflammation of the pancreas. It can also suggest other pancreatic issues, such as pancreatic cancer or blockages in the pancreatic duct. High lipase levels may also be seen in cases of gastrointestinal diseases, kidney failure, or severe abdominal pain of unknown origin.</p><p>The test is typically performed by drawing a blood sample, which is then analyzed for lipase activity. Normal lipase levels can vary slightly between different laboratories, but significantly elevated levels generally warrant further investigation to identify the underlying cause. Monitoring lipase levels helps healthcare providers diagnose, manage, and treat conditions related to the pancreas, improving patient outcomes.</p>', '<p>         ,                        ,        ,             ,             </p><p>,                              ,             ,                   ,   ,               </p><p>          ,                      ,                  warrant                ,        ,        </p>', '2024-07-20 13:37:20', '2024-07-20 13:37:20', NULL, 0),
(142, NULL, 'Lipoprotein A-LPA', 'EXP0142', '1470', '790', 'Next day', 'Overnight fasting for 9-12 hours', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'A lipoprotein test measures the levels of lipoproteins in the blood. Lipoproteins are molecules that transport cholesterol and triglycerides through the bloodstream. This test typically includes measurements of low-density lipoprotein (LDL), high-density lipoprotein (HDL), and sometimes very low-density lipoprotein (VLDL). It helps assess the risk of cardiovascular diseases, such as heart disease and stroke, by evaluating cholesterol levels and their distribution within different types of lipoproteins.', NULL, '<p>A lipoprotein test, also known as a lipid panel or lipid profile, measures the levels of specific lipoproteins in the blood. Lipoproteins are complex particles composed of lipids (fats) and proteins that transport cholesterol and triglycerides through the bloodstream. The test typically includes measurements of:</p><p>1. **Low-Density Lipoprotein (LDL)**: Often referred to as \"bad\" cholesterol, high levels of LDL can lead to plaque buildup in arteries, increasing the risk of heart disease and stroke.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;<br>2. **High-Density Lipoprotein (HDL)**: Known as \"good\" cholesterol, HDL helps remove cholesterol from the bloodstream, reducing the risk of cardiovascular diseases.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;<br>3. **Total Cholesterol**: The sum of LDL, HDL, and VLDL (very low-density lipoprotein) levels.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;<br>4. **Triglycerides**: A type of fat found in the blood; high levels can increase the risk of heart disease.</p><p>The lipoprotein test is used to assess the risk of cardiovascular diseases by evaluating cholesterol levels and their distribution among different types of lipoproteins. It helps guide dietary, lifestyle, and medication interventions to manage cholesterol levels and reduce the risk of heart disease and related conditions. The test is typically performed through a blood sample, often after fasting for 9-12 hours.</p>', '<p>       ()              &nbsp;<br>                ,                  , ,                                          ,   9-12        </p>', '2024-07-20 13:43:28', '2024-07-20 13:43:28', NULL, 0),
(143, NULL, 'Lithium', 'EXP0143', '850', '499', 'Next day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'A lithium test measures the concentration of lithium in the blood. Lithium is a medication used primarily to treat bipolar disorder. This test helps ensure that lithium levels stay within the therapeutic range, as both low and high levels can lead to ineffective treatment or adverse effects. Regular monitoring helps manage dosing and prevent toxicity, ensuring the medication\'s efficacy while minimizing side effects. The test is crucial for maintaining proper lithium balance in patients undergoing lithium therapy.', NULL, '<p>The lithium test measures the concentration of lithium in the blood, specifically for patients undergoing lithium therapy. Lithium is a mood-stabilizing medication primarily used to treat bipolar disorder, a mental health condition characterized by extreme mood swings. It helps stabilize mood and prevent both manic and depressive episodes.</p><p>Lithium levels need to be carefully monitored because the difference between a therapeutic dose and a toxic dose is narrow. Too little lithium may not effectively control symptoms, while too much can lead to toxicity. Symptoms of lithium toxicity include nausea, tremors, confusion, and in severe cases, kidney damage or seizures.</p><p>The test is typically conducted by analyzing a blood sample, usually taken 12 hours after the last dose, to ensure accurate measurement of peak lithium levels. Monitoring is essential for adjusting dosages and ensuring the medication\'s effectiveness while avoiding adverse effects. Regular testing helps manage and adjust treatment plans to maintain therapeutic levels and prevent complications associated with improper lithium dosing.</p>', NULL, '2024-07-20 13:52:23', '2024-07-20 13:52:23', NULL, 0),
(144, NULL, 'Magnesium', 'EXP0144', '880', '390', 'Next day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'The magnesium test measures the concentration of magnesium in the blood. Magnesium is an essential mineral involved in various bodily functions, including nerve and muscle function, blood sugar control, and bone health. It plays a crucial role in enzyme reactions and energy production. Abnormal levels of magnesium can indicate conditions such as kidney disease, diabetes, or gastrointestinal disorders. Low magnesium levels may cause muscle cramps, weakness, or irregular heartbeats, while high levels can lead to symptoms like nausea, confusion, and cardiac issues.', NULL, '<p>The magnesium test measures the concentration of magnesium in the blood, an essential mineral critical for numerous physiological functions. Magnesium is involved in over 300 enzymatic reactions in the body, contributing to energy production, protein synthesis, muscle and nerve function, and bone health. It helps regulate heart rhythm, blood sugar levels, and blood pressure. Magnesium is also vital for maintaining a healthy immune system.</p><p>The test is commonly used to diagnose and monitor conditions related to magnesium imbalance. Low magnesium levels (hypomagnesemia) can result from conditions such as gastrointestinal diseases, kidney disorders, or prolonged use of diuretics. Symptoms of low magnesium may include muscle cramps, weakness, and irregular heartbeats. Conversely, high magnesium levels (hypermagnesemia) can occur due to excessive supplementation or kidney dysfunction and may present with symptoms like nausea, confusion, or cardiac disturbances.</p><p>A blood sample is typically analyzed to measure serum magnesium levels. The test is useful in evaluating overall health, particularly in patients with conditions that affect magnesium balance. Regular monitoring helps guide appropriate treatment and dietary adjustments to manage magnesium levels and prevent complications.</p>', '<p>   300        ,   ,  ,    ,            ,   ,                    </p><p>                      ()   ,   ,  uretics                  , ,          ,    ()                , ,        </p>', '2024-07-20 13:57:00', '2024-07-20 13:58:49', NULL, 0),
(145, NULL, 'Phosphorus Calcium & Uric acid', 'EXP0145', '799', '399', 'Same day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Phosphorus, calcium, and uric acid are vital substances measured in blood tests to assess various health conditions. \r\n\r\n- **Phosphorus:** Important for bone health and energy production.\r\n- **Calcium:** Crucial for bone strength, muscle function, and nerve signaling.\r\n- **Uric Acid:** A waste product from purine metabolism; high levels can indicate gout or kidney stones.\r\n\r\nThese tests help diagnose and manage conditions like bone disorders, kidney disease, and metabolic issues.', 'Teeth,healthy Bones & joint pain', NULL, NULL, '2024-07-20 17:53:33', '2024-07-20 17:53:33', NULL, 0),
(146, NULL, 'Alkaline phosphotase & protein', 'EXP0146', '580', '330', 'Same day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '**Alkaline Phosphatase (ALP):** ALP is an enzyme found in various tissues, especially the liver, bones, and bile ducts. Elevated ALP levels can indicate liver disease, bone disorders, or bile duct obstruction. Low levels might suggest malnutrition or certain genetic conditions.\r\n\r\n**Protein:** Total protein test measures the amount of protein in the blood, including albumin and globulin. It helps assess nutritional status, liver and kidney function, and various medical conditions. Abnormal protein levels can indicate liver disease, kidney disease, or inflammatory conditions. \r\n\r\nThese tests are crucial for diagnosing and monitoring various health conditions.', 'Bone development', NULL, NULL, '2024-07-20 18:00:36', '2024-07-20 18:00:36', NULL, 0),
(147, NULL, 'Urine R/M - UTI detailed', 'EXP0147', '199', '99', 'Same day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'A Urine Routine Examination (Urine RM) is a common diagnostic test that evaluates various components of a urine sample. It typically includes:\r\n\r\n1. **Physical Examination:** Analyzes color, clarity, and specific gravity.\r\n2. **Chemical Examination:** Tests for pH, protein, glucose, ketones, bilirubin, urobilinogen, nitrites, and leukocyte esterase.\r\n3. **Microscopic Examination:** Detects cells, bacteria, crystals, and casts.\r\n\r\nThis test helps diagnose urinary tract infections, kidney disease, diabetes, liver conditions, and other medical issues.', 'Pus cells & bacteria', NULL, NULL, '2024-07-20 18:02:42', '2024-07-20 18:02:42', NULL, 0),
