(151, NULL, 'RMA - Rapid Malaria Antigen PV & PF', 'EXP0151', '580', '299', 'Same day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'A rapid malaria antigen test detects specific proteins produced by malaria parasites in a patient\'s blood. It\'s a quick and simple diagnostic tool that provides results in 15-30 minutes. The test uses a small blood sample, typically obtained via finger prick, which is applied to a test strip or cassette. This method is particularly useful in areas with limited laboratory infrastructure, enabling timely diagnosis and treatment, thus reducing the burden of malaria, especially in resource-limited settings.', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2024-07-22 18:06:24', '2024-07-22 18:06:24', NULL, 0),
(152, NULL, 'Malaria Parasite Slide ( MP slide )', 'EXP0152', '299', '130', 'Same day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'The malaria parasite slide test, or microscopic examination, is a traditional method for diagnosing malaria. It involves collecting a blood sample, usually via finger prick, and spreading it on a glass slide to create a blood smear. The smear is stained using Giemsa or other specific stains, which highlight the malaria parasites within red blood cells. A trained laboratory technician then examines the stained smear under a microscope to identify and quantify the presence of malaria parasites. This method is considered the gold standard for malaria diagnosis due to its high sensitivity and specificity. It allows for the identification of the malaria species and the determination of parasite density, which are crucial for appropriate treatment and monitoring. However, it requires skilled personnel and proper laboratory facilities.', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2024-07-22 18:08:51', '2024-07-22 18:08:51', NULL, 0),
(153, NULL, 'Phosphorus', 'EXP0153', '350', '199', 'Same day', 'Overnight fasting for 9-12 hours', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'A phosphorus test measures the amount of phosphorus in the blood, an essential mineral involved in various bodily functions. Phosphorus works in tandem with calcium to build and maintain strong bones and teeth. It is also crucial for energy production, as it forms part of ATP (adenosine triphosphate), the molecule that stores and releases energy in cells. Additionally, phosphorus plays a role in the synthesis of DNA and RNA, the regulation of acid-base balance, and the proper functioning of muscles and nerves.\r\n\r\nThe test is often ordered to evaluate kidney function since the kidneys regulate phosphorus levels in the blood. It can help diagnose conditions like kidney disease, bone disorders, malnutrition, and issues with calcium metabolism. Monitoring phosphorus levels is particularly important for patients with chronic kidney disease or those undergoing dialysis.', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2024-07-22 18:20:29', '2024-07-22 18:20:29', NULL, 0),
(154, NULL, 'MPO- ANCA ( P-ANCA )', 'EXP0154', '2480', '1299', 'Next day', 'Overnight fasting for 9-12 hours', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'A P-ANCA (Perinuclear Anti-Neutrophil Cytoplasmic Antibodies) test measures the presence of specific autoantibodies that target proteins in the cytoplasm of neutrophils, a type of white blood cell. These autoantibodies are often associated with autoimmune vasculitis, particularly microscopic polyangiitis and ulcerative colitis. The test helps in diagnosing and monitoring these autoimmune conditions by detecting the characteristic antibodies that indicate inflammation of blood vessels. It aids in distinguishing between different types of vasculitis and related disorders.', NULL, '<p>The P-ANCA (Perinuclear Anti-Neutrophil Cytoplasmic Antibodies) test is a blood test used to detect the presence of specific autoantibodies that target antigens in the perinuclear region of neutrophils, a type of white blood cell. These autoantibodies are often found in individuals with certain autoimmune diseases, particularly those affecting small blood vessels.</p><p>The P-ANCA test is commonly used in the diagnosis and monitoring of autoimmune vasculitis, such as microscopic polyangiitis, and other conditions like ulcerative colitis. In these diseases, the body\'s immune system mistakenly attacks its own blood vessels, leading to inflammation and damage. The presence of P-ANCA helps differentiate these conditions from other types of vasculitis and related disorders.</p><p>The test involves taking a blood sample and analyzing it in a laboratory for the characteristic antibodies. Positive results, along with clinical symptoms and other diagnostic tests, assist healthcare providers in confirming the diagnosis and guiding treatment decisions.</p>', '<p>P-ANCA (Perinuclear Anti-Neutrophil Cytoplasmic Antibodies)       ,      ,                                     ,            </p><p>P-ANCA       ,   ,                 ,             ,       P-ANCA                   </p><p>                     ,         ,                 </p>', '2024-07-22 18:27:20', '2024-07-22 18:27:20', NULL, 0),
(155, NULL, 'DHEA - dehydroepiandrosterone', 'EXP0155', '3990', '2230', 'Next day', 'Overnight fasting for 9-12 hours', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'A DHEA (Dehydroepiandrosterone) test measures the level of DHEA sulfate (DHEA-S) in the blood. DHEA is a hormone produced by the adrenal glands, playing a key role in the production of male and female sex hormones, including testosterone and estrogen. The test helps evaluate adrenal gland function and diagnose conditions related to hormone imbalances, such as adrenal tumors, adrenal insufficiency, and polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS). It is also used to monitor patients with these conditions.', NULL, '<p>DHEA (Dehydroepiandrosterone) is a steroid hormone produced primarily by the adrenal glands, with smaller amounts secreted by the ovaries and testes. It serves as a precursor to male and female sex hormones, including testosterone and estrogen. The DHEA test, specifically measuring DHEA sulfate (DHEA-S), evaluates the level of this hormone in the blood.</p><p>DHEA levels peak in early adulthood and gradually decline with age. Measuring DHEA-S is useful in assessing adrenal gland function and diagnosing various conditions related to hormone imbalances. Elevated DHEA-S levels may indicate adrenal tumors, congenital adrenal hyperplasia, or polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS). Conversely, low levels can suggest adrenal insufficiency, Addison\'s disease, or hypopituitarism.</p><p>The DHEA test is particularly valuable in evaluating symptoms such as hirsutism, infertility, amenorrhea, and early puberty. It helps healthcare providers determine the underlying cause of these symptoms and guide appropriate treatment strategies. The test involves a simple blood draw and is often used alongside other hormonal tests for a comprehensive assessment.</p>', '<p>DHEA (Dehydroepiandrosterone)              ,                 ,    ,         DHEA ,    DHEA  (DHEA-S)   ,           </p><p>DHEA            -     DHEA-S                        DHEA-S   ,   ,     (PCOS)       ,    ,  ,       &nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p>DHEA  , , ,                                                                </p>', '2024-07-22 18:34:56', '2024-07-22 18:36:14', NULL, 0),
(156, NULL, 'TPHA with Titee - Treponema Pallidum Hemagglutination', 'EXP0156', '990', '590', 'Next day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'A TPHA (Treponema pallidum hemagglutination assay) with titer measures the concentration of antibodies against Treponema pallidum, the bacterium that causes syphilis. The test detects and quantifies the presence of these antibodies in the blood, indicating a past or current syphilis infection. The titer represents the dilution at which antibodies are still detectable, helping assess the severity and progression of the infection. High titers can suggest active infection or a recent infection, while declining titers may indicate successful treatment.', NULL, '<p>The TPHA (Treponema pallidum hemagglutination assay) with titer is a blood test used to detect and measure antibodies against Treponema pallidum, the bacterium responsible for syphilis. This assay is highly sensitive and specific for syphilis detection. During the test, red blood cells coated with antigens are mixed with the patient\'s serum. If antibodies against Treponema pallidum are present, they will cause agglutination (clumping) of the red blood cells.</p><p>The titer represents the highest dilution of the patient\'s serum at which agglutination is still observable. It quantifies the concentration of these antibodies, providing information about the extent of the infection. High titers generally indicate an active or recent syphilis infection, while lower or declining titers may suggest resolution of the infection or a previous, treated infection. This test is often used to confirm syphilis diagnosis and monitor treatment efficacy over time.</p>', NULL, '2024-07-22 18:48:56', '2024-07-22 18:48:56', NULL, 0),
(157, NULL, 'Hepatitis C Virus- HCV Genotyping', 'EXP0157', '7000', '3350', 'Within 4 Days', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'HCV genotyping measures the specific strain or type of Hepatitis C virus (HCV) present in a patients blood. This test identifies the viral genotype, which is crucial for determining the appropriate treatment regimen and predicting the likelihood of treatment success. HCV has several genotypes, each with multiple subtypes, and knowing the genotype helps tailor antiviral therapy and manage the disease effectively. This test is typically used to guide treatment decisions and monitor the response to therapy.', NULL, '<p>HCV genotype refers to the specific strain or type of Hepatitis C virus (HCV) identified in a patient. Hepatitis C is caused by the HCV, which has several distinct genotypes, each with multiple subtypes. Genotypes are classified based on genetic variations in the virus, and the most common genotypes are 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, and 6, with each having its own variations.</p><p>Determining the HCV genotype is crucial for guiding treatment decisions because different genotypes respond differently to antiviral therapies. For example, some genotypes may be more resistant to certain drugs, while others may respond better. Genotyping helps in selecting the most effective treatment regimen, predicting the likelihood of achieving a sustained viral response, and tailoring the duration of therapy. The test involves analyzing a blood sample to identify the specific HCV genotype and is an essential component of personalized treatment planning for Hepatitis C.</p>', '<p>HCV               (HCV)         HCV   ,      ,                  ,     1, 2, 3, 4, 5,  6 ,   -   </p><p>HCV           ,        -      ,           ,              ,          ,                     HCV                    </p>', '2024-07-22 19:01:02', '2024-07-22 19:01:02', NULL, 0),
(158, NULL, 'Cardiolipin Antibody- ACL IgG', 'EXP0158', '1190', '690', 'Next Day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Cardiolipin antibodies measure the presence of autoantibodies against cardiolipin, a phospholipid component of cell membranes. These antibodies are often tested to diagnose antiphospholipid syndrome, an autoimmune disorder that increases the risk of blood clots, miscarriages, and other complications. Elevated levels of cardiolipin antibodies can indicate an increased risk of clotting disorders and help in evaluating the presence and severity of antiphospholipid syndrome. The test is used to guide treatment and monitor patients with suspected or confirmed autoimmune conditions.', NULL, '<p>Cardiolipin antibodies are autoantibodies that target cardiolipin, a phospholipid found in the inner mitochondrial membrane and in cell membranes. These antibodies are commonly associated with antiphospholipid syndrome (APS), an autoimmune condition that can lead to an increased risk of abnormal blood clotting, recurrent miscarriages, and other complications. In APS, the immune system mistakenly produces antibodies against cardiolipin, interfering with normal blood clotting processes.</p><p>The presence of cardiolipin antibodies in the blood is measured through a specific blood test. Elevated levels can help diagnose APS and assess the risk of thrombotic events. The test results are used in conjunction with clinical symptoms and other diagnostic criteria to guide treatment strategies and manage the risk of complications associated with APS.</p>', NULL, '2024-07-22 19:09:46', '2024-07-22 19:09:46', NULL, 0),
(159, NULL, 'Reticulocyte Count', 'EXP0159', '580', '290', 'Next day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'A reticulocyte count measures the number of reticulocytes, which are immature red blood cells, in the blood. This test helps evaluate bone marrow function and red blood cell production. It is used to diagnose and monitor conditions such as anemia, bone marrow disorders, and the body\'s response to treatments like chemotherapy or erythropoietin therapy. High reticulocyte counts can indicate increased red blood cell production, while low counts may suggest bone marrow failure or insufficient production.', NULL, '<p>A reticulocyte count is a blood test that measures the number of reticulocytes, which are immature red blood cells newly released from the bone marrow into the bloodstream. This count is a crucial indicator of bone marrow function and the bodys ability to produce red blood cells.</p><p>Reticulocytes typically comprise about 0.5% to 2.5% of the total red blood cells in healthy individuals. The test is particularly useful in diagnosing and monitoring various conditions, such as anemia, bone marrow disorders, and the effectiveness of treatments like chemotherapy or erythropoietin therapy. Elevated reticulocyte counts can indicate increased red blood cell production in response to conditions like hemolytic anemia or blood loss, reflecting the bone marrows compensatory effort. Conversely, low reticulocyte counts may suggest bone marrow failure, aplastic anemia, or insufficient erythropoiesis.</p><p>By providing insights into red blood cell production and bone marrow health, the reticulocyte count helps healthcare providers diagnose underlying conditions, monitor treatment responses, and adjust therapeutic strategies accordingly.</p>', '<p>            ,                                       </p><p>            0.5%  2.5%          ,   ,                                    ,                   ,      ,  ,        </p><p>           ,           ,     ,          </p>', '2024-07-23 01:37:39', '2024-07-23 01:37:39', NULL, 0),
(160, NULL, 'Chikungunya Virus IgMAntibody Rapid', 'EXP0160', '880', '495', 'Same day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'A Chikungunya virus IgM rapid antibody test measures the presence of IgM antibodies against the Chikungunya virus in the blood. IgM antibodies are produced by the immune system shortly after infection, indicating a recent or acute infection. This rapid test helps diagnose Chikungunya fever, a mosquito-borne viral disease, in its early stages. By detecting IgM antibodies, healthcare providers can confirm an active Chikungunya infection and differentiate it from other similar illnesses, facilitating timely and appropriate treatment.', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2024-07-23 07:18:23', '2024-07-23 07:18:23', NULL, 0),
(161, NULL, 'Cortisol-Morning', 'EXP0161', '999', '490', 'Same Day', 'Overnight fasting for 9-12 hours', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'A cortisol morning test measures the level of cortisol, a hormone produced by the adrenal glands, in the blood. Cortisol levels naturally peak in the early morning and decrease throughout the day. This test is typically performed in the morning to evaluate adrenal gland function and diagnose conditions such as Cushing\'s syndrome (high cortisol) or Addison\'s disease (low cortisol). By assessing morning cortisol levels, healthcare providers can better understand the body\'s stress response and hormonal balance.', NULL, '<p>Morning cortisol refers to the measurement of cortisol levels in the blood taken early in the morning, typically between 6:00 AM and 8:00 AM. Cortisol is a hormone produced by the adrenal glands that plays a crucial role in regulating metabolism, immune response, and the body\'s stress response. Cortisol levels follow a diurnal rhythm, peaking in the early morning and gradually decreasing throughout the day.</p><p>The morning cortisol test is used to assess adrenal gland function and diagnose disorders related to cortisol imbalance. Elevated morning cortisol levels can indicate conditions such as Cushing\'s syndrome, characterized by excessive cortisol production. Conversely, low morning cortisol levels may suggest adrenal insufficiency, as seen in Addison\'s disease. This test is essential for identifying and managing these conditions, helping healthcare providers tailor appropriate treatment plans based on the patient\'s hormonal profile and overall health status.</p>', '<p>            ,   6:00 AM  8:00 AM  ,                      ,  ,                    ,        -   </p><p>                                       ,          ,            ,                    ,                      </p>', '2024-07-23 07:24:42', '2024-07-23 07:24:42', NULL, 0),
(162, NULL, 'Torch IgG', 'EXP0162', '1780', '799', 'Same Day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'A TORCH IgG test measures the presence of IgG antibodies against a group of infectious agents: Toxoplasma, Rubella, Cytomegalovirus (CMV), and Herpes simplex virus (HSV). This test helps determine if a person has had a past infection or immunity to these pathogens, which can be particularly important for pregnant women. Detecting IgG antibodies indicates prior exposure and potential immunity, aiding in assessing the risk of congenital infections that could affect the fetus.', NULL, '<p>A TORCH IgG test is a blood test that measures the presence of IgG antibodies against a specific group of infections: Toxoplasma gondii (T), Rubella virus (R), Cytomegalovirus (C), and Herpes simplex virus (H). The acronym TORCH represents these pathogens, which can cause congenital infections if transmitted from a pregnant woman to her developing fetus. The presence of IgG antibodies indicates past exposure or immunity to these infections.</p><p>This test is particularly crucial for pregnant women, as it helps assess the risk of transmitting these infections to the fetus. A positive IgG result suggests that the individual has had a prior infection and may have developed immunity, reducing the risk of active infection during pregnancy. Conversely, a negative result indicates no prior exposure, and the person may be susceptible to these infections.</p><p>Understanding a patients IgG antibody status allows healthcare providers to take necessary precautions and provide appropriate care to prevent potential complications, such as birth defects or developmental issues, in the newborn.</p>', '<p>TORCH IgG             IgG      : Toxoplasma gondii (T), Rubella virus (R), Cytomegalovirus (C),  Herpes simplex virus (H) TORCH       ,                   IgG               </p><p>          ,                   IgG                    ,              ,            ,          </p><p>  IgG                                      </p>', '2024-07-23 07:32:16', '2024-07-23 07:32:16', NULL, 0);
