(163, NULL, 'SGPT-Alanine Transaminase ( ALT )', 'EXP0163', '250', '150', 'Same Day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'SGPT (Serum Glutamate Pyruvate Transaminase), also known as ALT (Alanine Aminotransferase), measures the level of the enzyme ALT in the blood. This enzyme is primarily found in the liver and is released into the bloodstream when liver cells are damaged. The SGPT test is used to assess liver function and diagnose liver conditions such as hepatitis, cirrhosis, and liver inflammation. Elevated SGPT levels indicate liver damage or disease, guiding further diagnostic and treatment decisions.', NULL, '<p>SGPT (Serum Glutamate Pyruvate Transaminase), also known as ALT (Alanine Aminotransferase), is an enzyme primarily found in the liver, with smaller amounts present in the kidneys, heart, and muscles. This enzyme plays a crucial role in amino acid metabolism by catalyzing the conversion of alanine and alpha-ketoglutarate to pyruvate and glutamate.</p><p>The SGPT test measures the level of ALT in the blood, which helps assess liver function. Elevated levels of SGPT can indicate liver damage or disease, as the enzyme is released into the bloodstream when liver cells are injured. Conditions that may cause elevated SGPT levels include hepatitis, cirrhosis, fatty liver disease, liver inflammation, and drug-induced liver damage.</p><p>Monitoring SGPT levels is essential for diagnosing and managing liver conditions. It is also used to evaluate the effectiveness of treatments and monitor potential liver damage in patients taking medications that may affect the liver. By providing insight into liver health, the SGPT test guides healthcare providers in diagnosing liver disorders and planning appropriate treatment strategies.</p>', '<p>SGPT (   ),  ALT ( )       ,            ,      ,                  ,   -         </p><p>SGPT    ALT     ,            SGPT             ,                   SGPT         , ,   ,            </p><p>SGPT                                                      , SGPT                    </p>', '2024-07-23 12:49:08', '2024-07-23 12:49:08', NULL, 0),
(164, NULL, 'Torch IgM', 'EXP0164', '1780', '799', 'Next Day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'A TORCH IgM test measures the presence of IgM antibodies against a group of infections: Toxoplasma, Rubella, Cytomegalovirus (CMV), and Herpes simplex virus (HSV). IgM antibodies indicate a recent or acute infection. This test is particularly important for pregnant women, as these infections can cause serious birth defects or complications if transmitted to the fetus. Detecting IgM antibodies helps diagnose recent infections, allowing healthcare providers to take timely steps to manage and reduce the risk to the mother and baby.', NULL, '<p>A TORCH IgM test is a blood test that measures the presence of IgM antibodies against a group of infectious agents: Toxoplasma gondii (T), Rubella virus (R), Cytomegalovirus (C), and Herpes simplex virus (H). The presence of IgM antibodies indicates a recent or acute infection, as IgM is the first antibody produced by the immune system in response to an infection.</p><p>This test is particularly important for pregnant women, as these infections can cause serious complications, including congenital abnormalities, miscarriage, or stillbirth, if transmitted to the fetus. The TORCH IgM test helps diagnose these recent infections, enabling timely intervention and management. A positive IgM result suggests an active or recent infection, requiring further evaluation and potentially additional testing or treatment.</p><p>By identifying recent infections, the TORCH IgM test aids healthcare providers in protecting both the mother and the developing fetus from the potential adverse effects of these infectious agents, ensuring better prenatal care and outcomes.</p>', '<p>TORCH IgM       IgM                : Toxoplasma gondii (T), Rubella virus (R), Cytomegalovirus (C),  Herpes simplex virus (H) IgM             ,  IgM              </p><p>          ,               ,   ,      TORCH IgM            ,           IgM            ,               </p><p>     , TORCH IgM                        ,         </p>', '2024-07-23 12:55:20', '2024-07-23 12:55:20', NULL, 0),
(165, NULL, 'C- Peptide Serum Fasting', 'EXP0165', '1350', '630', 'Next day', 'Overnight fasting for 9-12 hours', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'A C-peptide fasting serum test measures the level of C-peptide in the blood after fasting. C-peptide is a byproduct of insulin production, and its measurement helps assess how much insulin the body is producing. This test is useful in differentiating between type 1 and type 2 diabetes, evaluating insulinoma (a tumor of the pancreas), and monitoring the function of pancreatic beta cells in diabetic patients. It provides insights into the body\'s insulin production capacity.\r\nTranslation Hindi', NULL, '<p>A C-peptide fasting test measures the level of C-peptide in the blood after fasting. C-peptide is a byproduct of insulin production, released in equal amounts to insulin when proinsulin is split into insulin and C-peptide by the pancreas. Measuring C-peptide helps assess the body\'s insulin production since C-peptide remains in the blood longer than insulin, providing a more stable indicator of insulin secretion.</p><p>This test is particularly useful in differentiating between type 1 and type 2 diabetes, as well as in diagnosing conditions like insulinoma, a tumor of the pancreas that causes excessive insulin production. Additionally, it helps evaluate residual beta-cell function in diabetic patients, guiding treatment decisions. Elevated C-peptide levels can indicate insulin resistance or excessive insulin production, while low levels may suggest reduced insulin production, typical of type 1 diabetes. The C-peptide fasting test thus provides critical insights into pancreatic function and insulin dynamics.</p>', '<p>C-        C-      C-     ,        C-           C-               C-           ,         </p><p>   1   2     ,            ,                ,      -        ,          C-            ,     1               , C-              </p>', '2024-07-23 13:03:26', '2024-07-23 13:03:26', NULL, 0),
(166, NULL, 'CPK- NAC- Creatinine Phospho Kinase -', 'EXP0166', '399', '245', 'Same Day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'A CPK-NAC (Creatine Phosphokinase-N-acetylcysteine) test measures the level of creatine phosphokinase (CPK) in the blood after the addition of N-acetylcysteine (NAC), which helps stabilize and preserve the enzyme. CPK is an enzyme found in the heart, brain, and muscles, and its levels can indicate muscle damage or stress. This test is used to assess and monitor conditions like myocardial infarction, muscular dystrophy, and other muscle-related disorders by evaluating changes in CPK levels.', NULL, '<p>The CPK-NAC (Creatine Phosphokinase-N-acetylcysteine) test measures the level of creatine phosphokinase (CPK) in the blood after the addition of N-acetylcysteine (NAC). CPK is an enzyme present in the heart, brain, and skeletal muscles, and its measurement helps assess muscle and heart tissue damage. NAC is used to stabilize and preserve CPK during testing, ensuring accurate results. Elevated CPK levels can indicate muscle damage, such as from myocardial infarction (heart attack), muscular dystrophy, or other muscle injuries. By providing a clearer picture of muscle enzyme activity, the CPK-NAC test aids in diagnosing and monitoring various muscle and heart conditions, helping guide treatment decisions and evaluate the extent of muscle damage.</p>', '<p>CPK-NAC ( --)      (CPK)     ,  N- (NAC)    CPK     ,         ,                 NAC   CPK             ,        CPK         ,     (  ),    (  ),             , CPK-NAC                ,                </p>', '2024-07-23 13:16:49', '2024-07-30 18:33:38', NULL, 0),
(167, NULL, 'Dual Marker-Double Marker ( Maternal Screen First Trimester )', 'EXP0167', '2699', '1350', 'Within 2 Days', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'A dual marker test measures the levels of two specific biomarkers in the blood to assess the risk of certain conditions. Commonly used in prenatal screening, it typically measures markers like alpha-fetoprotein (AFP) and human chorionic gonadotropin (hCG) to evaluate the risk of chromosomal abnormalities such as Down syndrome. By comparing these markers with established reference ranges, the test helps in assessing the likelihood of such conditions and guides further diagnostic or monitoring steps.', NULL, '<p>The dual marker test is a prenatal screening tool used to assess the risk of chromosomal abnormalities, such as Down syndrome, in a developing fetus. This test measures two specific biomarkers in the maternal blood: alpha-fetoprotein (AFP) and human chorionic gonadotropin (hCG). AFP is a protein produced by the fetal liver, while hCG is a hormone produced by the placenta.</p><p>By analyzing the levels of these markers, the dual marker test helps estimate the risk of the fetus having certain genetic disorders. Abnormal levels of AFP and hCG can indicate an increased risk of conditions like Down syndrome or, in some cases, neural tube defects. The test is typically performed between the 15th and 20th week of pregnancy and provides valuable information to guide further diagnostic testing, such as amniocentesis or chorionic villus sampling, if needed.</p>', '<p>              ,   ,                       : - (AFP)     (hCG) AFP           ,  hCG         </p><p>      ,                     AFP  hCG                           15  20                              </p>', '2024-07-23 13:29:08', '2024-07-23 13:29:08', NULL, 0),
(168, NULL, 'Quadruple marker - Matennal screen 4', 'EXP0168', '3500', '1850', 'Within 3 Days', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'The quadruple marker test is a prenatal screening test that measures four specific biomarkers in the maternal blood to assess the risk of fetal chromosomal abnormalities and neural tube defects. These biomarkers typically include alpha-fetoprotein (AFP), human chorionic gonadotropin (hCG), estriol (uE3), and inhibin A. By evaluating the levels of these markers, the test helps estimate the risk of conditions such as Down syndrome, trisomy 18, and neural tube defects, providing information to guide further diagnostic testing.', NULL, '<p>The quadruple marker test is a prenatal screening tool used to assess the risk of certain fetal abnormalities. It measures four specific biomarkers in the maternal blood: alpha-fetoprotein (AFP), human chorionic gonadotropin (hCG), estriol (uE3), and inhibin A. AFP is a protein produced by the fetal liver, hCG is a hormone produced by the placenta, estriol is an estrogen produced by both the placenta and fetal liver, and inhibin A is a hormone produced by the placenta and ovaries.</p><p>The test is typically performed between the 15th and 20th weeks of pregnancy. Abnormal levels of these markers can indicate an increased risk of chromosomal abnormalities like Down syndrome (trisomy 21) and trisomy 18, as well as neural tube defects. The quadruple marker test helps guide further diagnostic testing, such as amniocentesis, if needed, to confirm or rule out these conditions.</p>', '<p>                                 : - (AFP),    (hCG),  (uE3),   A AFP           , hCG         ,              ,   A           </p><p>     15  20              ( 21)   18   ,                   ,    ,      ,   ,         </p>', '2024-07-23 13:58:11', '2024-07-23 13:58:11', NULL, 0),
(169, NULL, 'Serum Uric Acid', 'EXP0169', '290', '159', 'Same Day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'A uric acid test measures the level of uric acid in the blood. Uric acid is a waste product formed from the breakdown of purines, which are substances found in certain foods and produced naturally in the body. The test helps assess how well the body is clearing uric acid and can indicate conditions such as gout, kidney stones, or kidney dysfunction. Elevated levels may suggest impaired excretion or increased production, while low levels could be due to conditions like chronic kidney disease.', NULL, '<p>Uric acid is a waste product formed from the breakdown of purines, which are substances found in certain foods and produced naturally within the body. It is normally dissolved in the blood and excreted through the kidneys in urine. A uric acid test measures the concentration of uric acid in the blood or urine. High levels of uric acid, known as hyperuricemia, can lead to conditions such as gout, characterized by painful joint inflammation, or kidney stones. Conversely, low uric acid levels might be associated with conditions like chronic kidney disease or certain metabolic disorders. The test helps diagnose these conditions, monitor treatment efficacy, and manage associated symptoms.</p>', '<p>            ,                                                    ,     ,        ,         ,      ,                      ,     ,          </p>', '2024-07-23 14:03:24', '2024-07-23 14:03:24', NULL, 0),
(170, NULL, 'ANA ( IFA )-Anti Nuclear Antibodies-Immunofluorescence-IFA Method', 'EXP0170', '1899', '990', 'Within 4 Days', 'Overnight Fasting for 9-12 hours', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'The ANA IFA (Antinuclear Antibody Indirect Immunofluorescence Assay) test measures the presence of antinuclear antibodies (ANAs) in the blood. ANAs are antibodies that target the bodys own nuclear components, and their presence can indicate autoimmune disorders. The test involves mixing a blood sample with cells that have been treated to bind ANAs, and then using a fluorescent dye to visualize any binding. A positive result can help diagnose conditions like lupus, rheumatoid arthritis, or scleroderma.', NULL, '<p>The ANA IFA (Antinuclear Antibody Indirect Immunofluorescence Assay) test is a laboratory procedure used to detect the presence of antinuclear antibodies (ANAs) in the blood. ANAs are antibodies that mistakenly target and attack the bodys own nuclear components, such as DNA and proteins within the cell nucleus. The test involves mixing a blood sample with cells that have been treated to capture ANAs. A fluorescent dye is then applied, and a microscope is used to detect any fluorescence, indicating the presence of ANAs.</p><p>A positive ANA IFA test can suggest autoimmune disorders, such as systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE), rheumatoid arthritis, or scleroderma. It is not a definitive diagnostic tool but helps in identifying potential autoimmune conditions and guiding further diagnostic testing and treatment.</p>', '<p>ANA IFA (-    )         -  (ANAs)            ANAs           ,  DNA       ,      ,              ANAs                             ,  ANAs      </p><p>  ANA IFA   ,     (SLE),  ,              ,                    </p>', '2024-07-23 14:09:53', '2024-07-23 14:14:09', NULL, 0),
(171, NULL, 'ANA ( ELISA ) - Anti Nuclear Antibodies', 'EXP0171', '699', '430', 'Within 3 Days', 'Overnight fasting for 9-12 hours', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'The ANA ELISA (Antinuclear Antibody Enzyme-Linked Immunosorbent Assay) test measures the level of antinuclear antibodies (ANAs) in the blood. ANAs are antibodies that target the body\'s own nuclear components. The test uses an enzyme-linked reaction to detect and quantify these antibodies. Elevated ANA levels can suggest autoimmune disorders such as systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE) or rheumatoid arthritis. The ANA ELISA test provides a quantitative measure of these antibodies, helping to assess the presence and extent of autoimmune activity.', NULL, '<p>The ANA ELISA (Antinuclear Antibody Enzyme-Linked Immunosorbent Assay) test is a diagnostic tool used to detect and quantify antinuclear antibodies (ANAs) in the blood. ANAs are antibodies that target components within the cell nucleus, and their presence can indicate autoimmune disorders. The test employs an enzyme-linked immunosorbent assay to bind ANAs to a specific antigen coated on a plate. After binding, a substrate is added that produces a detectable color change, proportional to the amount of ANAs present.</p><p>A positive ANA ELISA result can suggest autoimmune conditions like systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE), rheumatoid arthritis, or scleroderma. Unlike the ANA IFA test, which provides qualitative results, the ELISA method offers quantitative data, which helps in assessing the extent of autoimmune activity and guiding further diagnostic and treatment decisions.</p>', NULL, '2024-07-23 14:13:40', '2024-07-23 14:13:40', NULL, 0),
(172, NULL, 'Ceruloplasmin', 'EXP0172', '1599', '830', 'Next Day', 'Overnight Fasting for 9-12 hours', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'A ceruloplasmin test measures the level of ceruloplasmin, a protein that binds and transports copper in the blood. Ceruloplasmin is produced by the liver and is essential for iron metabolism and antioxidant activity. Measuring ceruloplasmin levels helps diagnose and monitor conditions related to copper metabolism, such as Wilson\'s disease, where copper accumulates in tissues due to a deficiency of ceruloplasmin. Abnormal levels can also indicate liver disease, malnutrition, or other disorders affecting copper and iron metabolism.', NULL, '<p>Ceruloplasmin is a copper-binding glycoprotein produced by the liver, playing a crucial role in the transport and regulation of copper within the body. This protein is also involved in iron metabolism and has antioxidant properties, helping to protect cells from damage caused by free radicals. Measuring ceruloplasmin levels in the blood is important for diagnosing and monitoring disorders related to copper metabolism, such as Wilson\'s disease, a genetic disorder where copper accumulates in tissues due to defective ceruloplasmin function. Low levels of ceruloplasmin can indicate Wilson\'s disease, liver disease, or malnutrition, while high levels might be seen in conditions like inflammation or infection. Thus, ceruloplasmin is vital for maintaining metal homeostasis and overall metabolic health.</p>', '<p>  -        ,                            ,                                      ,    ,                        ,  ,       ,               ,              </p>', '2024-07-23 17:48:32', '2024-07-23 17:48:32', NULL, 0),
(173, NULL, 'Karyotyping ( CHROMOSOME ANALYSIS )', 'EXP0173', '5200', '2870', 'Within 18 Days', 'Overnight fasting for 9-12 hours', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'A karyotyping test analyzes the number and structure of chromosomes in cells to detect genetic abnormalities. It involves arranging and photographing chromosomes from a cell sample, typically blood, bone marrow, or amniotic fluid. Karyotyping helps diagnose genetic disorders, congenital anomalies, and certain cancers by identifying chromosomal changes like deletions, duplications, translocations, or extra chromosomes, such as in Down syndrome. The test provides valuable information for genetic counseling, guiding treatment decisions, and understanding hereditary conditions.', NULL, '<p>Karyotyping is a laboratory technique used to visualize and examine the number and structure of chromosomes in a cell. This process involves staining and arranging chromosomes from a sample of cells, typically from blood, bone marrow, amniotic fluid, or placental tissue, into a standardized format called a karyogram or karyotype. The chromosomes are then analyzed under a microscope to identify any abnormalities in size, shape, or number.</p><p>Karyotyping is essential for diagnosing genetic disorders and congenital anomalies, such as Down syndrome, Turner syndrome, and Klinefelter syndrome. It can also detect structural changes like deletions, duplications, inversions, and translocations, which may contribute to developmental issues or cancer. This test provides critical information for genetic counseling, guiding clinical management, and understanding the genetic basis of various conditions. By identifying chromosomal abnormalities, karyotyping aids in making informed medical and reproductive decisions.</p>', '<p>                                     ,       ,                   ,            </p><p>     ,   ,             , , ,           ,              ,                      ,           </p>', '2024-07-23 17:53:12', '2024-07-27 17:59:02', NULL, 0),
(174, NULL, 'Sodium -NA', 'EXP0174', '250', '140', 'Same Day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'A sodium test measures the concentration of sodium in the blood. Sodium is an essential electrolyte that helps regulate water balance, nerve function, and muscle contraction. Abnormal sodium levels can indicate various health issues: hyponatremia (low sodium) can result from conditions like dehydration, kidney disease, or heart failure, while hypernatremia (high sodium) may be due to excessive fluid loss, certain medications, or endocrine disorders. Monitoring sodium levels is crucial for diagnosing and managing these and other related conditions.', NULL, '<p>                      ,                                             ,           ,        ,             </p><p>           ,    ,    ,   ,         ,  , , ,           ,    , ,   ,        ,   ,                   </p>', '<p>Sodium is an essential electrolyte and mineral found in the blood and various bodily fluids. It plays a critical role in maintaining fluid balance, transmitting nerve impulses, and supporting muscle function. Sodium helps regulate blood pressure and volume by controlling the movement of water between cells and the bloodstream. The body obtains sodium primarily through dietary sources, especially salt, and it is regulated by the kidneys, which adjust sodium excretion to maintain proper balance.</p><p>Abnormal sodium levels can lead to various health issues. Hyponatremia, or low sodium levels, can result from excessive water intake, kidney disease, heart failure, or hormonal imbalances, causing symptoms like headache, nausea, confusion, and in severe cases, seizures. Hypernatremia, or high sodium levels, can occur due to dehydration, excessive salt intake, or endocrine disorders, leading to symptoms such as thirst, weakness, and confusion. Proper sodium balance is crucial for overall health and bodily function.<br>&nbsp;</p>', '2024-07-23 18:26:34', '2024-07-23 18:27:04', NULL, 0),
(175, NULL, 'Potassium-K', 'EXP0175', '250', '140', 'Same day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'A potassium test measures the level of potassium in the blood. Potassium is a crucial electrolyte that helps regulate heart function, muscle contractions, and nerve signals. It plays a key role in maintaining fluid balance and acid-base equilibrium in the body. Potassium levels are primarily controlled by the kidneys, which excrete excess potassium through urine. \r\n\r\nAbnormal potassium levels can lead to various health issues: hypokalemia (low potassium) may cause symptoms like muscle weakness, fatigue, and arrhythmias, while hyperkalemia (high potassium) can lead to serious conditions such as cardiac arrhythmias or kidney dysfunction. Monitoring potassium levels is essential for diagnosing and managing conditions related to electrolyte imbalances, kidney function, and overall cardiovascular health.', NULL, '<p>Potassium is an essential electrolyte and mineral vital for numerous physiological functions in the body. It is predominantly found inside cells and plays a crucial role in maintaining fluid balance, regulating nerve and muscle cell function, and ensuring proper heart rhythm. Potassium helps control muscle contractions, nerve impulses, and acid-base balance, which are all necessary for normal cell function.</p><p>The body regulates potassium levels through the kidneys, which adjust potassium excretion based on dietary intake and bodily needs. Normal potassium levels are essential for cardiovascular health, as imbalances can lead to serious conditions. Hypokalemia (low potassium) may cause symptoms such as muscle weakness, fatigue, and irregular heartbeats, while hyperkalemia (high potassium) can result in dangerous cardiac arrhythmias and potential kidney dysfunction. Monitoring and managing potassium levels is crucial for treating and preventing various health issues, particularly those related to heart and kidney function.</p>', '<p>                              ,          ,                ,  ,  -     ,        </p><p>          ,                        ,           ( )   , ,          ,   ( )                                     </p>', '2024-07-23 18:31:02', '2024-07-23 18:42:50', NULL, 0),
(176, NULL, 'Chloride- Cl', 'EXP0176', '250', '140', 'Same Day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'A chloride test measures the concentration of chloride, an essential electrolyte, in the blood or urine. Chloride plays a crucial role in maintaining fluid balance, regulating acid-base levels, and supporting nerve and muscle function. It works with sodium and potassium to manage blood volume, pressure, and pH balance. Abnormal chloride levels can indicate health issues such as dehydration, kidney disease, metabolic acidosis (high levels), or prolonged vomiting and metabolic alkalosis (low levels).', NULL, '<p>A chloride test measures the concentration of chloride in the blood or urine. Chloride is an essential electrolyte that helps maintain fluid balance, acid-base balance, and proper muscle and nerve function. It works with sodium and potassium to regulate blood volume and pressure. Abnormal chloride levels can indicate various health conditions, such as dehydration, kidney disease, or imbalances in acid-base levels. The test provides valuable information for diagnosing and managing these conditions.</p>', '<p>           , -    ,                                   , ,             ,     ( )              </p><p>                         () ,   ,        ,     ()    ,  ,                          </p>', '2024-07-23 18:41:43', '2024-07-23 18:43:14', NULL, 0),
(177, NULL, 'Electrolytes Panel- Na k Cl', 'EXP0177', '499', '330', 'Same Day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'An electrolyte panel measures the levels of key electrolytes in the blood, including sodium, potassium, chloride, and bicarbonate. These electrolytes are crucial for maintaining fluid balance, nerve function, and muscle contractions. The panel helps assess overall health, diagnose conditions related to imbalances, such as dehydration, kidney disease, or acid-base disorders, and monitor the effects of treatments. Abnormal results can indicate issues with fluid and electrolyte balance, requiring further evaluation and management.', NULL, '<p>Electrolytes are electrically charged minerals in the body that are essential for various physiological functions. They include sodium, potassium, chloride, bicarbonate, calcium, and magnesium. Electrolytes help regulate fluid balance, maintain acid-base balance, and ensure proper nerve and muscle function. They are involved in critical processes such as transmitting nerve impulses, muscle contractions, and maintaining hydration levels. Electrolyte levels are tightly regulated by the kidneys and other organs. Imbalances can lead to health issues such as dehydration, heart arrhythmias, and muscle weakness. Measuring electrolytes through blood tests helps diagnose and manage these conditions effectively.</p>', '<p>                  , , , , ,          , -   ,                   ,   ,                              ,    ,                              </p>', '2024-07-23 18:48:12', '2024-07-23 18:48:12', NULL, 0),
(178, NULL, 'CMV-IgG - Cytomegalo Virus', 'EXP0178', '699', '395', 'Next Day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'A CMV IgG test measures the presence of IgG antibodies against cytomegalovirus (CMV) in the blood. IgG antibodies indicate a past infection and provide long-term immunity against CMV. This test helps determine whether a person has been previously exposed to CMV, which is important for pregnant women, organ transplant recipients, and immunocompromised individuals. A positive CMV IgG result suggests prior exposure and potential immunity, while a negative result indicates no previous infection and susceptibility to CMV.', NULL, '<p>CMV IgG (Cytomegalovirus Immunoglobulin G) is a blood test that detects the presence of IgG antibodies specific to cytomegalovirus (CMV). CMV is a common virus that can infect people of all ages, often causing mild or no symptoms in healthy individuals. The presence of IgG antibodies indicates past exposure to CMV and suggests that the individual has developed long-term immunity against the virus.</p><p>This test is particularly important for certain populations, such as pregnant women, organ transplant recipients, and immunocompromised individuals. For pregnant women, determining CMV status is crucial because a primary CMV infection during pregnancy can lead to congenital CMV, potentially causing serious birth defects or developmental issues in the newborn. For transplant recipients and immunocompromised patients, knowing CMV status helps in managing and preventing potential CMV-related complications.</p><p>A positive CMV IgG test result indicates previous exposure and potential immunity, while a negative result means no prior infection and susceptibility to CMV.</p>', '<p>CMV IgG (  G)       (CMV)    IgG        &nbsp;IgG    CMV                        </p><p>      ,   ,              , CMV          CMV     CMV     ,                        , CMV    CMV-         </p><p>  CMV IgG           ,             CMV   </p>', '2024-07-24 17:24:56', '2024-07-24 17:24:56', NULL, 0),
(179, NULL, 'CMV-IgM - Cytomegalo Virus', 'EXP0179', '699', '395', 'Next Day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'A CMV IgM (Cytomegalovirus Immunoglobulin M) test measures the presence of IgM antibodies specific to cytomegalovirus (CMV) in the blood. The presence of IgM antibodies indicates a recent or current CMV infection. This test is particularly useful for diagnosing acute CMV infections, especially in pregnant women, organ transplant recipients, and immunocompromised individuals, as a recent CMV infection can lead to serious health complications in these populations.', NULL, '<p>CMV IgM (Cytomegalovirus Immunoglobulin M) is a blood test that detects the presence of IgM antibodies specific to cytomegalovirus (CMV). CMV is a common virus that usually causes mild or no symptoms in healthy individuals but can lead to serious health issues in certain populations. The presence of IgM antibodies indicates a recent or active CMV infection, as IgM is the first antibody produced by the immune system in response to an infection.</p><p>This test is especially important for pregnant women, organ transplant recipients, and immunocompromised individuals. For pregnant women, a recent CMV infection can pose significant risks to the fetus, potentially causing congenital CMV, which can lead to birth defects or developmental problems. In transplant recipients and immunocompromised patients, active CMV infection can result in severe complications due to their weakened immune systems.</p><p>A positive CMV IgM test result suggests a recent or ongoing CMV infection, necessitating further evaluation and appropriate management to mitigate potential health risks.<br>&nbsp;</p>', '<p>CMV IgM (  M)       (CMV)    IgM        CMV                  ,             IgM       CMV     ,  IgM          </p><p>      ,              ,  CMV          ,   CMV   ,                 ,  CMV              </p><p>  CMV IgM       CMV     ,                   </p>', '2024-07-24 17:30:03', '2024-07-24 17:30:03', NULL, 0),
(180, NULL, 'Dengue IgG', 'EXP0180', '850', '450', 'Same Day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'A Dengue IgG test measures the presence of IgG antibodies in the blood, which indicates a past infection with the dengue virus. IgG antibodies typically appear several weeks after the initial infection and remain in the body for years, providing long-term immunity. This test helps determine if a person has been previously exposed to the dengue virus, which is important for understanding immunity status and potential risk of future dengue infections. It is particularly useful in endemic areas for epidemiological studies and patient history assessment.', NULL, '<p> IgG         G (IgG)          -                   IgG                       <br>           IgG                   ,</p><p>  IgG             ,                                 ,                             ,     IgG            </p><p> IgG             ,                </p>', NULL, '2024-07-24 17:35:34', '2024-07-24 17:35:34', NULL, 0),
(181, NULL, 'Dengue IgM', 'EXP0181', '850', '450', 'Same Day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'The Dengue IgM test measures the presence of Immunoglobulin M (IgM) antibodies specific to the dengue virus in the blood. IgM antibodies are produced by the immune system shortly after a dengue infection, typically appearing within a few days. A positive Dengue IgM test indicates a recent or current dengue infection, helping in the early diagnosis and management of the disease.', NULL, '<p> IgM         M (IgM)                    ,                     IgM             ,                                                       IgM           ,         IgG     ,  IgM           </p>', NULL, '2024-07-24 17:40:42', '2024-07-24 17:40:42', NULL, 0),
(182, NULL, 'Dengue NS1 Antigen Elisa', 'EXP0182', '850', '450', 'Same Day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'The Dengue NS1 Antigen test measures the presence of the NS1 protein, a non-structural protein produced by the dengue virus during the early phase of infection. This protein can be detected in the blood of individuals infected with dengue virus, usually within the first few days of symptoms. The test helps in the early diagnosis of dengue fever, distinguishing it from other febrile illnesses and enabling prompt treatment to manage the disease effectively.', NULL, '<p> 1   (-  )                1               1            -        1    ,           ,        </p><p>       ,          ,        ,              1    ,                                              </p>', NULL, '2024-07-24 17:46:28', '2024-07-24 17:46:28', NULL, 0);
INSERT INTO `tests` (`id`, `category_id`, `test_name`, `test_code`, `mrp_price`, `price`, `report_date`, `fasting`, `customer_instructions`, `phlebo_instructions`, `icon`, `banner`, `short_desc`, `short_desc_1`, `desc_1`, `desc_2`, `created_at`, `updated_at`, `deleted_at`, `parameter_count`) VALUES
(183, NULL, 'HIV (1&2) Antibody 4th Generation Quantitative-ELISA', 'EXP0183', '550', '320', 'Next Day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'HIV (Human Immunodeficiency Virus) is a virus that attacks and weakens the immune system by targeting and destroying CD4 cells, which are critical to the body\'s defense against infections. Without adequate treatment, HIV can lead to acquired immunodeficiency syndrome (AIDS), a stage where the immune system is severely compromised, making individuals vulnerable to opportunistic infections and certain cancers. HIV is transmitted through blood, sexual contact, and from mother to child during childbirth or breastfeeding.\r\n\r\nDiagnosis typically involves blood tests to detect HIV antibodies or viral RNA. Early diagnosis and antiretroviral therapy (ART) can significantly manage the virus, reduce viral load, and prevent progression to AIDS. ART helps maintain immune function and reduces the risk of transmitting the virus to others. Regular monitoring and adherence to treatment are essential for long-term health and quality of life for those living with HIV.', NULL, '<p>HIV (  )          ,  CD4                 , HIV AIDS (  )     ,                         HIV ,  ,             </p><p>            HIV    RNA  detect        (ART)        ,        ,  AIDS        ART                            HIV          </p>', NULL, '2024-07-24 18:19:17', '2024-07-24 18:19:17', NULL, 0),
(184, NULL, 'Direct Coombs Test - DCT', 'EXP0184', '699', '395', 'Within 2 Days', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'A DCT (Direct Coombs Test) measures the presence of antibodies bound to red blood cells. This test, also known as the direct antiglobulin test, involves adding anti-human globulin (Coombs reagent) to a blood sample to detect if antibodies or complement proteins are attached to the red blood cells. It is used to diagnose conditions such as hemolytic anemia, autoimmune disorders, and transfusion reactions, helping identify causes of red blood cell destruction.', NULL, '<p>The Direct Coombs Test (DCT), also known as the direct antiglobulin test, is a diagnostic blood test used to detect antibodies or complement proteins that are bound to the surface of red blood cells. In this test, a blood sample is mixed with anti-human globulin (Coombs reagent). If antibodies or complement proteins are present on the red blood cells, the reagent will cause agglutination (clumping) of the cells, indicating a positive result.</p><p>The DCT is crucial for diagnosing conditions where the immune system attacks red blood cells, such as autoimmune hemolytic anemia, where the body\'s immune system destroys its own red blood cells, and hemolytic disease of the newborn (HDN), which occurs when maternal antibodies target fetal red blood cells. It is also used to investigate transfusion reactions and other situations involving red blood cell destruction. Accurate detection through the DCT helps guide appropriate treatment and management.</p>', '<p>   (DCT),        ,                            ,     -  ( )                ,      ()   ,        </p><p>DCT                ,     ,                ,       (HDN),                                        DCT             </p>', '2024-07-24 18:23:18', '2024-07-24 18:23:18', NULL, 0),
(185, NULL, '5 Alpha- DIHYDROTESTOSTERONE or 5 Alpha DHT', 'EXP0185', '3500', '1999', 'Within 4 Days', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'The 5-alpha-DHT (5-alpha-dihydrotestosterone) test measures the level of 5-alpha-DHT, a potent androgen hormone derived from testosterone. 5-alpha-DHT plays a crucial role in the development of male characteristics and is involved in conditions such as benign prostatic hyperplasia (BPH) and androgenetic alopecia (hair loss). Elevated levels of 5-alpha-DHT can indicate issues like prostate disorders or excessive androgen activity, while low levels may suggest hormonal imbalances. This test helps diagnose and manage related conditions.', NULL, '<p>5-alpha-DHT (5-alpha-dihydrotestosterone) is a potent androgen hormone synthesized from testosterone by the enzyme 5-alpha reductase. It plays a critical role in the development of male physical characteristics, such as facial and body hair, and is involved in the growth and function of the prostate gland. 5-alpha-DHT binds more strongly to androgen receptors than testosterone, making it a more active form of the hormone in certain tissues.</p><p>The 5-alpha-DHT test measures the level of this hormone in the blood to help diagnose and manage conditions related to androgen excess or deficiency. Elevated levels of 5-alpha-DHT can be associated with benign prostatic hyperplasia (BPH), prostate cancer, and androgenetic alopecia (pattern baldness). Low levels may indicate hormonal imbalances or deficiencies. By assessing 5-alpha-DHT levels, healthcare providers can better understand and address related health issues and tailor appropriate treatments.</p>', '<p>5-alpha-DHT (5-alpha-dihydrotestosterone)          5-alpha reductase          ,       ,                    5-alpha-DHT            ,             </p><p>5-alpha-DHT          ,                          (BPH),      ( )                5-alpha-DHT    ,                 </p>', '2024-07-24 18:30:19', '2024-07-24 18:30:19', NULL, 0),
(186, NULL, 'Indirect COOMBS Test- IDCT', 'EXP0186', '699', '390', 'Within 2 Days', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'An IDCT (Indirect Coombs Test), also known as the indirect antiglobulin test, measures the presence of antibodies against red blood cells in the blood serum. This test involves mixing a patient\'s serum with red blood cells of known antigenic profiles and then adding anti-human globulin (Coombs reagent). Agglutination indicates that antibodies in the serum are binding to the red blood cells. The IDCT is used to screen for antibodies in blood transfusion compatibility testing and in diagnosing conditions like hemolytic disease of the newborn.', NULL, '<p>IDCT (Indirect Coombs Test), also known as the indirect antiglobulin test, is a diagnostic blood test used to detect antibodies in the serum that may bind to red blood cells. This test is performed by mixing a patient\'s serum with red blood cells of known antigenic profiles. Then, anti-human globulin (Coombs reagent) is added to the mixture. If antibodies are present, they will bind to the red blood cells and cause agglutination (clumping) when the Coombs reagent is added.</p><p>The IDCT is crucial for several clinical applications, including blood transfusion compatibility testing, where it helps identify potential antibodies that could cause a transfusion reaction. It is also used to diagnose and investigate hemolytic disease of the newborn (HDN) and autoimmune hemolytic anemia, where the immune system destroys its own red blood cells. By detecting harmful antibodies, the IDCT aids in ensuring safe transfusions and effective treatment for related conditions.</p>', '<p>IDCT (  ),        ,                           ,                  , -  ( )          ,               ()   </p><p>IDCT       ,       ,                          (HDN)            ,                  , IDCT               </p>', '2024-07-24 18:34:57', '2024-07-24 18:34:57', NULL, 0),
(187, NULL, '17 HydroxyProgesterone -17 OHP', 'EXP0187', '1850', '990', 'Next  Days', 'Overnight fasting for 9-12 hours', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '17-OH progesterone (17-hydroxyprogesterone) is a hormone measured to assess adrenal gland function and diagnose congenital adrenal hyperplasia (CAH). This test evaluates levels of 17-OH progesterone, which is a precursor in cortisol production. High levels may indicate CAH, a condition where the adrenal glands produce inadequate cortisol and aldosterone. Its also used to investigate hormonal imbalances in conditions like polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS) and to monitor treatment in CAH.', NULL, '<p>The 17-OH progesterone (17-hydroxyprogesterone) test measures the level of this hormone in the blood. It is primarily used to evaluate adrenal gland function and diagnose congenital adrenal hyperplasia (CAH), a genetic disorder that affects cortisol and aldosterone production. 17-OH progesterone is a precursor in the synthesis of these hormones. Elevated levels can indicate CAH, while normal levels help rule out this condition. The test is also used to assess hormone imbalances related to conditions such as polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS) and to monitor CAH treatment. By analyzing 17-OH progesterone levels, healthcare providers can better understand adrenal function and manage related disorders effectively.</p>', '<p>17-OH  (17-)                          (CAH)         ,                17-OH            CAH     ,                        ,      (PCOS),  CAH           17-OH     ,                       </p>', '2024-07-24 18:43:11', '2024-07-24 18:43:11', NULL, 0),
(188, NULL, 'Hepatitis C Virus - Total Antibodies by ELISA', 'EXP0188', '750', '390', 'Next Day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'The Hepatitis C Virus (HCV) Total Antibody by ELISA (Enzyme-Linked Immunosorbent Assay) test measures the presence of antibodies against the hepatitis C virus in the blood. This test indicates whether a person has been exposed to HCV, regardless of whether the infection is current or has occurred in the past. A positive result suggests that the individual has been infected with HCV at some point, necessitating further testing to determine the current infection status and appropriate medical management.', NULL, '<p>The Hepatitis C Virus (HCV) Total Antibody by ELISA (Enzyme-Linked Immunosorbent Assay) test is a diagnostic tool used to detect the presence of antibodies against the hepatitis C virus in a persons blood. These antibodies are produced by the immune system in response to an HCV infection. The ELISA method involves binding HCV antigens to a microplate, adding the patients serum, and then applying an enzyme-linked antibody that reacts with any HCV antibodies present, producing a measurable color change.</p><p>This test is crucial for identifying individuals who have been exposed to HCV, whether the infection is current or occurred in the past. A positive result indicates prior exposure to the virus and warrants further testing, such as HCV RNA testing, to determine if the virus is still present and active in the body. The test helps guide clinical decisions, including the need for antiviral therapy and monitoring for liver-related complications.</p>', '<p>   (HCV)    ELISA (-  )                                  HCV        ELISA   HCV      ,         -         HCV       ,         </p><p>           HCV     ,                         ,  HCV RNA     ,                           ,              </p>', '2024-07-25 16:15:26', '2024-07-25 16:15:26', NULL, 0),
(189, NULL, 'Toxoplasma Gondii IgG Antibodies', 'EXP0189', '750', '390', 'Same Day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'A Toxoplasma gondii IgG antibodies test measures the presence of IgG antibodies against Toxoplasma gondii in the blood. These antibodies indicate past exposure or infection with the parasite, which causes toxoplasmosis. A positive result suggests that the individual has been infected at some point and has developed immunity. This test helps in diagnosing toxoplasmosis, especially in pregnant women, immunocompromised patients, and individuals with unexplained symptoms, to determine the risk of reactivation or potential complications.', NULL, '<p>Toxoplasma gondii IgG antibodies are immune proteins produced by the body in response to infection with the Toxoplasma gondii parasite, which causes toxoplasmosis. The presence of these antibodies in the blood indicates that a person has been exposed to the parasite at some point in their life. IgG antibodies typically develop several weeks after initial infection and persist for life, providing long-term immunity against reinfection.</p><p>The Toxoplasma gondii IgG antibody test is primarily used to determine past exposure to the parasite, particularly in pregnant women, immunocompromised individuals, and patients with unexplained symptoms that may suggest toxoplasmosis. In pregnant women, identifying previous exposure is crucial because a primary infection during pregnancy can lead to severe congenital infections in the fetus. For immunocompromised patients, knowing IgG status helps assess the risk of reactivation of latent infection.</p><p>A positive IgG result indicates past infection and immunity, while a negative result suggests no prior exposure, making the individual susceptible to infection.</p>', '<p>                     ,                                                 ,  :        </p><p>                      ,     ,                     ,                           ,                 </p><p>           ,                 ,         </p>', '2024-07-25 16:27:59', '2024-07-25 16:27:59', NULL, 0),
(190, NULL, 'Toxoplasma Gondii IgM Antibodies', 'EXP0190', '750', '390', 'Same Day', 'Fasting is not Mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'The Toxoplasma IgM antibodies test measures the presence of IgM antibodies in the blood, which are produced in response to a recent or acute infection with the Toxoplasma gondii parasite. The presence of IgM antibodies indicates a current or recent infection, as these antibodies typically appear soon after exposure and decrease over time. This test is crucial for diagnosing acute toxoplasmosis, especially in pregnant women and immunocompromised individuals, to prevent potential severe complications from a recent infection.', NULL, '<p>Toxoplasma IgM antibodies are immune proteins produced by the body in response to an acute or recent infection with the Toxoplasma gondii parasite, which causes toxoplasmosis. The presence of these IgM antibodies in the blood indicates an active or recent infection, as they typically appear soon after exposure to the parasite and decline over several months.</p><p>The Toxoplasma IgM antibody test is essential for diagnosing acute toxoplasmosis, particularly in high-risk groups such as pregnant women, newborns, and immunocompromised individuals. In pregnant women, detecting an acute infection is crucial because Toxoplasma gondii can cross the placenta and potentially cause severe congenital infections, leading to birth defects or developmental problems in the fetus. In immunocompromised patients, an acute infection can lead to serious health complications due to their weakened immune systems.</p><p>A positive IgM test result suggests a recent or ongoing infection, prompting further evaluation and treatment to prevent or manage potential complications. This test, often used alongside the Toxoplasma IgG test, helps provide a comprehensive assessment of toxoplasmosis status.</p>', '<p> IgM                     ,          IgM            ,                      </p><p> IgM       ,                      ,                         ,               ,              </p><p>  IgM            ,                        IgG       ,            </p>', '2024-07-25 16:33:05', '2024-07-25 16:33:05', NULL, 0),
(191, NULL, 'Toxoplasma Gondii IgG & IgM Antibodies', 'EXP0191', '1500', '650', 'Same Day', 'Fasting is not Mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'The Toxoplasma IgG and IgM antibodies test measures the body\'s immune response to the Toxoplasma gondii parasite. IgG antibodies indicate past exposure and long-term immunity, while IgM antibodies suggest a recent or acute infection. This dual test helps diagnose both current and past toxoplasmosis infections. It\'s particularly crucial for pregnant women, newborns, and immunocompromised individuals, as it helps determine the timing of the infection and guide appropriate treatment and management to prevent complications.', NULL, '<p>The Toxoplasma IgG and IgM antibodies test measures the presence of immune proteins produced in response to infection with the Toxoplasma gondii parasite. IgG antibodies indicate past exposure and long-term immunity, developing several weeks after initial infection and persisting for life. IgM antibodies appear soon after infection and indicate an acute or recent infection, typically declining within a few months.</p><p>This test is crucial for diagnosing both current and past toxoplasmosis infections. It is especially important for high-risk groups such as pregnant women, newborns, and immunocompromised individuals. In pregnant women, detecting IgM antibodies indicates a recent infection, which poses a risk of congenital toxoplasmosis, potentially leading to severe fetal complications. Identifying IgG antibodies helps determine if there is existing immunity.</p><p>By assessing both IgG and IgM antibodies, healthcare providers can better understand the timing of the infection, guide appropriate treatment, and manage potential complications, ensuring better outcomes for affected individuals.</p>', '<p>** IgG  IgM  **                     IgG          ,                 IgM                    ,         </p><p>                         ,            , IgM              ,        ,           IgG               </p><p>IgG  IgM     ,             ,               ,           </p>', '2024-07-25 17:06:22', '2024-07-25 17:06:22', NULL, 0),
(192, NULL, 'Toxoplasma Gondii IgG Avidity', 'EXP0192', '890', '640', 'Same Day', 'Fasting is not Mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Toxoplasma gondii IgG avidity refers to the strength with which IgG antibodies bind to the Toxoplasma gondii antigens. It is an important diagnostic tool used to distinguish between recent and past infections with the Toxoplasma gondii parasite. \r\n\r\nWhen the body first responds to an infection, it produces IgG antibodies with low avidity (weaker binding). Over time, as the immune response matures, the avidity of these antibodies increases (stronger binding). Therefore, measuring the avidity of IgG antibodies can help determine the timing of the infection.\r\n\r\n- **High IgG avidity** suggests that the infection occurred in the distant past.\r\n- **Low IgG avidity** indicates a more recent infection.\r\n\r\nThis information is particularly crucial for pregnant women, as a recent infection with Toxoplasma gondii can pose significant risks to the fetus, potentially leading to congenital toxoplasmosis. By assessing IgG avidity, healthcare providers can make more informed decisions about the management and treatment of the infection.', NULL, '<p>Toxoplasma gondii IgG avidity refers to the strength with which IgG antibodies, produced in response to Toxoplasma gondii infection, bind to the parasite\'s antigens. This test helps distinguish between recent and past infections. Initially, the immune system produces low-avidity (weaker binding) IgG antibodies following an acute infection. Over time, these antibodies mature and their avidity increases (stronger binding).</p><p>The IgG avidity test measures this maturation process. High avidity indicates that the infection occurred in the distant past, while low avidity suggests a recent infection. This distinction is particularly important for pregnant women, as a recent Toxoplasma gondii infection can lead to severe congenital infections in the fetus, causing birth defects or developmental issues.</p><p>By evaluating IgG avidity, healthcare providers can accurately determine the timing of the infection. This aids in making informed clinical decisions, guiding appropriate treatment, and managing potential risks, especially in high-risk populations like pregnant women and immunocompromised individuals.</p>', '<p>  IgG          IgG ,          ,                       ,         ( ) IgG       ,             ( )</p><p>IgG                    ,                      ,               ,         </p><p>IgG    ,                 ,              ,             </p>', '2024-07-25 17:09:32', '2024-07-25 17:13:06', NULL, 0),
(193, NULL, 'Herpes Simplex Virus I -IgG', 'EXP0193', '960', '450', 'Within 3  Days', 'Overnight Fasting for 9-12 hours', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'The HSV (Herpes Simplex Virus) I & II IgG test measures the presence of IgG antibodies against HSV types 1 and 2 in the blood. These antibodies indicate past exposure or infection with the virus, as IgG antibodies typically develop several weeks after initial infection and persist for life. This test helps determine whether a person has been infected with HSV-1 (commonly causing oral herpes) or HSV-2 (commonly causing genital herpes) in the past.', NULL, NULL, '<p>Herpes Simplex Virus type 1 (HSV-1) is a common virus that typically causes oral herpes, which manifests as cold sores or fever blisters around the mouth and lips. It is highly contagious and primarily transmitted through direct contact with infected saliva, mucous membranes, or skin. After the initial infection, HSV-1 remains dormant in nerve cells and can reactivate later, leading to recurrent outbreaks.</p><p>While HSV-1 is most commonly associated with oral infections, it can also cause genital herpes through oral-genital contact. Symptoms of an HSV-1 infection include painful blisters or ulcers at the infection site, itching, and flu-like symptoms during the initial outbreak. Although there is no cure for HSV-1, antiviral medications can help manage symptoms and reduce the frequency of outbreaks, improving the quality of life for those affected.</p>', '2024-07-25 18:21:51', '2024-07-25 18:21:51', NULL, 0),
(194, NULL, 'Herpes Simplex Virus -HSV I-IgM', 'EXP0194', '780', '425', 'Same Day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'A herpes simplex virus 1 (HSV-1) IgM test measures the presence of IgM antibodies against HSV-1 in the blood. Heres what this means:\r\n\r\n- **HSV-1:** This is a common virus that typically causes oral herpes, which leads to cold sores or fever blisters around the mouth. It can also cause genital herpes, though HSV-2 is more commonly associated with genital infections.\r\n  \r\n- **IgM Antibodies:** Immunoglobulin M (IgM) is one of the first antibodies produced by the immune system in response to an infection. The presence of IgM antibodies typically indicates a recent or current infection. Over time, IgM levels decrease and IgG antibodies, which provide longer-term immunity, increase.\r\n\r\n- **Test Interpretation:** A positive HSV-1 IgM test result suggests a recent or active HSV-1 infection. However, the IgM test can sometimes produce false positives and does not distinguish between primary (initial) and recurrent infections. For this reason, it is often used in conjunction with other tests, such as HSV-1 IgG antibody tests, which measure longer-term immunity.\r\n\r\nOverall, the HSV-1 IgM test helps in the diagnosis of a recent or ongoing HSV-1 infection, providing information that can guide treatment and management.', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2024-07-26 12:07:36', '2024-07-30 14:39:14', NULL, 0),
(195, NULL, 'Herpes Simplex Virus II -IgG', 'EXP0195', '960', '450', 'Same Day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'A Herpes simplex virus II (HSV-2) IgG test measures the presence of IgG antibodies against HSV-2 in the blood. Heres what this entails:\r\n\r\n- **HSV-2:** This virus primarily causes genital herpes, which results in sores and blisters in the genital and anal areas. It can also cause infections in other parts of the body, though less commonly.\r\n\r\n- **IgG Antibodies:** Immunoglobulin G (IgG) is a type of antibody produced by the immune system several weeks after an initial infection and provides long-term immunity. The presence of IgG antibodies typically indicates past exposure to the virus.\r\n\r\n- **Test Interpretation:**\r\n  - **Positive HSV-2 IgG:** Indicates that the person has been infected with HSV-2 at some point in the past. This does not necessarily mean the infection is active; it simply means that the immune system has responded to the virus at some point.\r\n  - **Negative HSV-2 IgG:** Suggests that the person has not been exposed to HSV-2 or that it is too early in the infection for IgG antibodies to be detectable.\r\n\r\nOverall, the HSV-2 IgG test is used to determine if someone has been previously infected with HSV-2, providing valuable information for diagnosis, management, and understanding the risk of transmission.', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2024-07-26 12:11:15', '2024-07-26 12:11:15', NULL, 0),
(196, NULL, 'Herpes Simplex Virus -HSV II-IgM', 'EXP0196', '780', '425', 'Same Day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'A Herpes simplex virus II (HSV-2) IgM test measures the presence of IgM antibodies against HSV-2 in the blood. Heres what this entails:\r\n\r\n- **HSV-2:** This virus primarily causes genital herpes, characterized by sores and blisters in the genital and anal areas. It can also cause infections in other parts of the body.\r\n\r\n- **IgM Antibodies:** Immunoglobulin M (IgM) is one of the first types of antibodies produced by the immune system in response to an infection. The presence of IgM antibodies generally indicates a recent or active infection.\r\n\r\n- **Test Interpretation:**\r\n  - **Positive HSV-2 IgM:** Suggests a recent or current HSV-2 infection. However, IgM tests can sometimes produce false positives and do not distinguish well between primary (initial) and recurrent infections.\r\n  - **Negative HSV-2 IgM:** Suggests that there is no recent or current HSV-2 infection, although it does not rule out past infection.\r\n\r\n- **Limitations:** The HSV-2 IgM test can have limitations, including cross-reactivity with HSV-1, leading to potential false positives. Additionally, because IgM levels can decline quickly after the initial infection, they may not be present during later stages or recurrent infections.\r\n\r\nOverall, the HSV-2 IgM test is used to detect recent or active HSV-2 infections and is often part of a broader diagnostic approach, which may include IgG antibody tests and clinical evaluation.', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2024-07-26 12:13:23', '2024-07-30 14:40:59', NULL, 0),
(197, NULL, 'TORCH panel IgG & IgM -10 Parameters', 'EXP0197', '4500', '1950', 'Next Day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'A TORCH panel is a group of blood tests that screen for several infections that can cause congenital infections (infections passed from a pregnant person to their fetus). The acronym TORCH stands for Toxoplasmosis, Other (including syphilis, varicella-zoster, parvovirus B19), Rubella, Cytomegalovirus (CMV), and Herpes simplex virus (HSV). When referring to a TORCH panel with 10 parameters, it typically means that the panel includes tests for specific antibodies (IgM and IgG) for each of these infections, as well as possibly other related tests.\r\n\r\nHere\'s a breakdown of the 10 parameters commonly measured:\r\n\r\n1. **Toxoplasmosis IgM**\r\n2. **Toxoplasmosis IgG**\r\n3. **Rubella IgM**\r\n4. **Rubella IgG**\r\n5. **Cytomegalovirus (CMV) IgM**\r\n6. **Cytomegalovirus (CMV) IgG**\r\n7. **Herpes simplex virus (HSV) IgM**\r\n8. **Herpes simplex virus (HSV) IgG**\r\n\r\nAdditionally, the \"Other\" category can include tests for infections like:\r\n\r\n9. **Syphilis (Treponema pallidum) antibodies**\r\n10. **Varicella-zoster virus (VZV) antibodies** or **Parvovirus B19 antibodies**\r\n\r\n**Test Interpretation:**\r\n\r\n- **IgM Antibodies:** Presence of IgM antibodies typically indicates a recent or active infection.\r\n- **IgG Antibodies:** Presence of IgG antibodies indicates past exposure and immunity to the infection.\r\n\r\nThe TORCH panel helps in identifying infections that could potentially harm the developing fetus, allowing for timely intervention and management.', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2024-07-26 12:23:28', '2024-07-26 12:23:28', NULL, 0),
(198, NULL, 'APOLIPOPROTEIN A1-APO A1', 'EXP0198', '1450', '790', 'Next Day', 'Overnight Fasting for 9-12 hours', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'An Apolipoprotein A1 (Apo A1) test measures the level of Apo A1 protein in the blood. Apo A1 is the main protein component of high-density lipoprotein (HDL), known as \"good cholesterol.\" It helps transport cholesterol from the arteries to the liver for removal. This test assesses cardiovascular disease risk, with low Apo A1 levels indicating a higher risk and higher levels being protective. It\'s used alongside other lipid tests to evaluate heart health.', NULL, '<p>Apolipoprotein A1 (Apo A1) is a protein that plays a crucial role in lipid metabolism and cardiovascular health. It is the primary protein component of high-density lipoprotein (HDL), often referred to as \"good cholesterol.\" Apo A1 helps transport cholesterol from the arteries to the liver, where it can be processed and excreted from the body. This process, known as reverse cholesterol transport, is vital for maintaining healthy cholesterol levels and preventing the buildup of plaque in the arteries, which can lead to atherosclerosis and cardiovascular disease.</p><p>Apo A1 also has antioxidant and anti-inflammatory properties, contributing further to its protective effects on the cardiovascular system. Measuring Apo A1 levels in the blood can provide valuable information about an individual\'s risk for heart disease. Low levels of Apo A1 are associated with an increased risk of developing cardiovascular conditions, while higher levels are generally indicative of a lower risk. This test is often used in conjunction with other lipid profile tests to give a comprehensive assessment of heart health and guide treatment strategies.</p>', '<p>Apolipoprotein A1 (Apo A1)                    (HDL)     ,   \" \"    Apo A1      ()      ,                       ,                   ,          </p><p>Apo A1    -    ,               Apo A1                    Apo A1              ,                                        </p>', '2024-07-26 12:29:29', '2024-07-26 12:29:29', NULL, 0),
(199, NULL, 'APOLIPOPROTEIN B - APO B', 'EXP0199', '1380', '750', 'Next Day', 'Overnight fasting for 9-12 hours', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Apo B (Apolipoprotein B) measures the level of this protein in the blood, which is a key component of low-density lipoprotein (LDL) and other atherogenic lipoproteins. Apo B is crucial for assessing cardiovascular risk, as it reflects the number of potentially harmful lipoprotein particles that can contribute to plaque buildup in the arteries. High levels of Apo B are associated with an increased risk of heart disease. This test helps evaluate overall heart health and guide treatment strategies.', NULL, '<p>Apolipoprotein B (Apo B) is a protein essential for lipid metabolism and cardiovascular health. It is the primary protein component of low-density lipoprotein (LDL) and other atherogenic lipoproteins, including very-low-density lipoprotein (VLDL). Apo B plays a critical role in transporting cholesterol and other lipids through the bloodstream. Each LDL particle contains one Apo B molecule, making it a useful marker for the number of potentially harmful lipoprotein particles.</p><p>Measuring Apo B levels helps assess cardiovascular risk because high levels indicate a higher number of atherogenic particles, which can contribute to plaque formation in the arteries and lead to atherosclerosis and heart disease. Elevated Apo B levels are associated with an increased risk of cardiovascular events. This test is often used alongside other lipid profile tests to provide a comprehensive evaluation of heart health and guide appropriate treatment strategies.</p>', '<p>Apolipoprotein B (Apo B)               -  (LDL)    ,   --  (VLDL)       Apo B               LDL    Apo B   ,               </p><p>Apo B              ,           ,                       Apo B                                        </p>', '2024-07-26 12:35:06', '2024-07-26 12:35:06', NULL, 0),
(200, NULL, 'Apolipoprotein B/A1 Ratio  Apolipoprotein B and A1', 'EXP0200', '1670', '750', 'Next Day', 'Overnight fasting for 9-12 hours', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'The Apolipoprotein B/A1 ratio measures the balance between two key proteins in lipid metabolism: Apolipoprotein B (Apo B) and Apolipoprotein A1 (Apo A1). Apo B is the primary protein component of low-density lipoprotein (LDL) and other atherogenic particles, while Apo A1 is the main protein component of high-density lipoprotein (HDL), which helps remove cholesterol from the bloodstream.\r\n\r\nThis ratio provides insight into cardiovascular risk by comparing the levels of these two proteins. A high Apo B/A1 ratio indicates a higher number of potentially harmful lipoprotein particles (associated with LDL) relative to the protective HDL particles (associated with Apo A1). A higher ratio is linked to an increased risk of developing cardiovascular diseases, as it reflects an imbalance between pro-atherogenic and anti-atherogenic lipoproteins. This ratio is used alongside other lipid profile measurements to evaluate overall heart health and guide treatment decisions.', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2024-07-26 12:42:11', '2024-07-26 12:42:11', NULL, 0),
(201, NULL, 'Urine Protein Electrophoresis', 'EXP0201', '1800', '890', 'Within 5 Days', 'Overnight fasting for 9-12 hours', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Urine protein electrophoresis is a laboratory test that measures and identifies the different types of proteins present in urine. This test helps detect and evaluate abnormalities in protein levels, which can indicate various kidney and systemic diseases. \r\n\r\nDuring the test, a urine sample is subjected to an electric field, causing proteins to separate based on their size and charge. The resulting pattern of protein bands is then analyzed to identify the presence of specific proteins, such as albumin, immunoglobulins, and Bence Jones proteins.\r\n\r\nUrine protein electrophoresis is particularly useful in diagnosing and monitoring conditions like multiple myeloma, amyloidosis, and other plasma cell disorders. It can also help assess kidney function and detect proteinuria, which is a sign of kidney damage or disease. By identifying abnormal protein patterns, this test provides valuable information for diagnosis, prognosis, and treatment planning.', NULL, '<p>                                    ,           </p><p>  ,          ,                            ,   , ,    </p><p>       , ,                                ,              ,   ,             </p>', NULL, '2024-07-26 17:50:01', '2024-07-26 17:50:01', NULL, 0),
(202, NULL, 'ANTI STREPTOLYSIN O-ASO', 'EXP0202', '790', '430', 'Same Day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'The Anti-Streptolysin O (ASO) test measures the level of antibodies against streptolysin O, a toxin produced by group A Streptococcus bacteria. Here\'s what it indicates:\r\n\r\n- **Streptolysin O:** A toxin produced by Streptococcus pyogenes (group A strep) that can cause cell damage.\r\n- **ASO Antibodies:** The immune system produces antibodies against streptolysin O when infected by group A strep.\r\n\r\n**Test Purpose:**\r\n- **Diagnosis of Recent Strep Infection:** Elevated ASO levels suggest a recent or past infection with group A strep.\r\n- **Rheumatic Fever and Glomerulonephritis:** Helps diagnose complications like rheumatic fever or post-streptococcal glomerulonephritis, which can develop after a strep infection.\r\n  \r\n**Interpretation:**\r\n- **High ASO Levels:** Indicate a recent streptococcal infection.\r\n- **Normal ASO Levels:** Do not rule out strep infection, especially if the test is performed too early or if the individual has a different immune response.\r\n\r\nThe ASO test aids in diagnosing and managing complications arising from streptococcal infections.', NULL, '<p>Anti-Streptolysin O (ASO) is a blood test that detects antibodies produced by the immune system in response to an infection with group A Streptococcus bacteria, specifically targeting the toxin streptolysin O. Streptolysin O is an enzyme that can damage tissues and red blood cells. When the body is infected by Streptococcus pyogenes, it produces ASO antibodies to neutralize this toxin.</p><p>The ASO test is primarily used to determine if a recent streptococcal infection has occurred, which can help diagnose complications such as rheumatic fever and post-streptococcal glomerulonephritis. Elevated ASO levels indicate a recent or past infection with group A Streptococcus. However, normal ASO levels do not necessarily rule out an infection, as antibody production varies among individuals and may not always be detectable in the early stages of infection. The ASO test is a valuable tool in diagnosing and managing complications resulting from streptococcal infections.</p>', '<p>Anti-Streptolysin O (ASO)       A Streptococcus              ,     O       O                 Streptococcus pyogenes    ,         ASO     </p><p>ASO                       ,     -             ASO   A Streptococcus          ,  ASO          ,                       ASO               </p>', '2024-07-26 17:55:49', '2024-07-26 17:55:49', NULL, 0);
