(203, NULL, 'Helicobacter Pylori-H.Pylori-Antigen stool', 'EXP0203', '2500', '1999', 'Next Day', 'Overnight fasting for 9-12 hours', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'The Helicobacter pylori (H. pylori) antigen stool test detects the presence of H. pylori antigens in a stool sample. H. pylori is a type of bacteria that can infect the stomach lining and is a common cause of peptic ulcers, chronic gastritis, and can contribute to the development of stomach cancer.\r\n\r\n**Test Purpose:**\r\n- **Detection of Infection:** Identifies current H. pylori infection by detecting bacterial antigens in the stool.\r\n- **Monitoring Treatment:** Evaluates the effectiveness of treatment for H. pylori infection, as the absence of antigens post-treatment indicates successful eradication of the bacteria.\r\n\r\n**Test Interpretation:**\r\n- **Positive Result:** Indicates an active H. pylori infection.\r\n- **Negative Result:** Suggests the absence of an active infection, although it does not rule out a past infection that has been cleared.\r\n\r\nThis non-invasive test is commonly used due to its simplicity and accuracy, helping in diagnosing H. pylori-related gastrointestinal conditions and monitoring treatment outcomes.', NULL, '<p>Helicobacter pylori (H. pylori) is a spiral-shaped bacterium that infects the lining of the stomach and is one of the most common bacterial infections worldwide. It is typically acquired during childhood and can persist throughout life if not treated. H. pylori is a major cause of peptic ulcers, chronic gastritis, and has been linked to the development of gastric cancer and mucosa-associated lymphoid tissue (MALT) lymphoma.</p><p>The bacterium is adapted to survive in the harsh acidic environment of the stomach by producing urease, an enzyme that neutralizes stomach acid. H. pylori infection is often asymptomatic but can lead to symptoms such as abdominal pain, bloating, nausea, and in severe cases, bleeding ulcers.</p><p>Diagnosis of H. pylori infection can be done through various methods, including breath tests, blood tests, stool antigen tests, and endoscopic biopsies. Treatment typically involves a combination of antibiotics and proton pump inhibitors to eradicate the infection and reduce stomach acid.</p>', '<p>Helicobacter pylori (H. pylori)                                               H. pylori  ,            -   (MALT)       </p><p>             ,         ,         H. pylori       ,    , ,             </p><p>H. pylori          ,   ,  ,                                   </p>', '2024-07-26 18:02:34', '2024-07-26 18:02:34', NULL, 0),
(204, NULL, 'Serum Ferritin', 'EXP0204', '599', '330', 'Same Day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Ferritin measures the amount of ferritin protein in the blood, which reflects the body\'s iron stores. Ferritin is an iron-binding protein found in cells, particularly in the liver, spleen, and bone marrow. High ferritin levels may indicate excess iron or inflammation, while low levels can suggest iron deficiency or anemia. This test helps assess overall iron levels in the body, diagnose conditions like iron deficiency anemia, and monitor iron therapy effectiveness.', NULL, '<p>Ferritin is a protein that stores and regulates iron within the body. It serves as the primary intracellular iron reservoir, found mainly in the liver, spleen, bone marrow, and muscles. Ferritin\'s main function is to store iron in a non-toxic, readily available form, releasing it as needed for various bodily functions, including the production of hemoglobin and red blood cells.</p><p>The ferritin level in the blood is a key indicator of the bodys iron stores. Low ferritin levels typically signify iron deficiency, which can lead to anemia and other health issues, while elevated levels can indicate excess iron or conditions such as inflammation, liver disease, or certain cancers. Measuring ferritin levels is crucial for diagnosing and managing iron-related disorders, evaluating the effectiveness of iron supplementation or treatment, and monitoring chronic diseases. It is often used alongside other tests to get a comprehensive view of a persons iron status and overall health.</p>', '<p>                         ,     , ,  ,              - ,        ,        ,         ,     </p><p>                       ,           ,       ,  ,                       ,         ,                                  </p>', '2024-07-26 18:06:22', '2024-07-26 18:06:22', NULL, 0),
(205, NULL, 'HCV Viral Load-Hepatitis C Virus RNA PCR Quantitative', 'EXP0205', '4700', '2570', 'Within 4 Days', 'Overnight Fasting for 9-12 hours', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'The HCV Viral Load RNA PCR Quantitative test measures the amount of hepatitis C virus (HCV) RNA in the blood using polymerase chain reaction (PCR) technology. This test quantifies the viral load, or the number of HCV RNA copies per milliliter of blood, providing a precise measurement of the viral replication level. \r\n\r\nThe quantitative result is crucial for diagnosing the severity of an HCV infection, assessing how well the virus is responding to antiviral treatment, and monitoring the effectiveness of therapy. It helps guide clinical decisions regarding treatment duration and adjustments. \r\n\r\nHigh viral loads indicate a higher level of viral replication and can be associated with more severe liver damage or a higher risk of transmission. Conversely, a decrease in viral load during treatment suggests a positive response to therapy. Regular monitoring through this test is essential for managing chronic hepatitis C effectively.', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2024-07-26 18:13:12', '2024-07-26 18:13:12', NULL, 0),
(206, NULL, 'Helicobacter Pylori- H.Pylori IgG Antibodies', 'EXP0206', '1600', '850', 'Within 2 Days', 'Overnight Fasting for 9-12 hours', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'The H. pylori IgG antibodies test measures the presence of immunoglobulin G (IgG) antibodies against Helicobacter pylori bacteria in the blood. This test helps determine if a person has been exposed to H. pylori, indicating a current or past infection. Elevated IgG levels suggest that the individual has been infected with H. pylori, which can lead to conditions such as peptic ulcers or chronic gastritis. However, it does not differentiate between an active or past infection.', NULL, '<p>The H. pylori IgG antibodies test detects the presence of immunoglobulin G (IgG) antibodies specific to Helicobacter pylori, a bacterium that infects the stomach lining. IgG antibodies are produced by the immune system in response to an H. pylori infection. This blood test helps determine if a person has been exposed to the bacterium, suggesting either a current or past infection.</p><p>A positive result indicates that the person has been infected with H. pylori at some point, which is often associated with conditions like peptic ulcers, chronic gastritis, and in some cases, gastric cancer. However, the IgG test does not distinguish between an active infection and a past infection that has been cleared. For determining active infection or evaluating treatment response, other tests like the stool antigen test or urea breath test are used in conjunction. The IgG antibody test is useful for initial diagnosis and screening but should be interpreted with other clinical information.</p>', '<p>H. pylori IgG         G (IgG)       ,            IgG        H. pylori                          ,           </p><p>            H. pylori    ,     ,  ,             , IgG            ,                   ,                 IgG          ,           </p>', '2024-07-26 18:19:02', '2024-07-26 18:19:02', NULL, 0),
(207, NULL, 'Helicobacter  Pylori- H. Pylori IgM Antibodies', 'EXP0207', '1600', '850', 'Within 2 Days', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'The H. pylori IgM antibodies test measures the presence of immunoglobulin M (IgM) antibodies specific to Helicobacter pylori in the blood. IgM is the first antibody produced in response to a new infection. This test helps detect a recent or active H. pylori infection. Elevated IgM levels suggest a current infection with H. pylori, which can cause conditions such as peptic ulcers or chronic gastritis. However, the IgM test is less commonly used than the IgG test for diagnosing H. pylori infections.', NULL, '<p>The H. pylori IgM antibodies test detects the presence of immunoglobulin M (IgM) antibodies specific to Helicobacter pylori, a bacterium that infects the stomach lining. IgM antibodies are the first type of antibodies produced by the immune system in response to a new or recent infection. This test is used to identify if a person has a recent or active H. pylori infection.</p><p>A positive result indicates that the individual has been recently infected with H. pylori, which can contribute to conditions such as peptic ulcers, chronic gastritis, and sometimes gastric cancer. While the IgM test can be useful for detecting recent infections, it is less commonly used compared to the IgG antibody test. The IgG test is typically preferred for diagnosing H. pylori infections because it indicates past exposure and is more reliable for determining long-term infection status. The IgM test, however, can help identify the timing of an infection.</p>', '<p>H. pylori IgM         M (IgM)       ,            IgM                                     H. pylori   </p><p>            H. pylori    ,   ,  ,  -           IgM            ,  IgG            IgG    H. pylori                              , IgM           </p>', '2024-07-26 18:24:44', '2024-07-26 18:24:44', NULL, 0),
(208, NULL, 'Hepatitis B envelope Antigen- HBeAg', 'EXP0208', '1400', '780', 'Next Day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'The HBeAg (Hepatitis B e-antigen) test measures the presence of the e-antigen from the hepatitis B virus (HBV in the blood. HBeAg indicates active viral replication and high infectivity, suggesting a more severe or acute stage of hepatitis B. A positive HBeAg result generally means the virus is actively reproducing and the patient is highly contagious. Monitoring HBeAg levels helps assess the progression of hepatitis B, evaluate the effectiveness of treatment, and guide management decisions.', NULL, '<p>HBeAg (Hepatitis B e-antigen) is a protein produced by the hepatitis B virus (HBV) and is found in the blood of individuals infected with HBV. It is a marker of active viral replication and high infectivity. The presence of HBeAg indicates that the virus is actively multiplying and that the individual is highly contagious.</p><p>HBeAg is often used to assess the severity and stage of hepatitis B infection, as well as to monitor the effectiveness of antiviral treatment. A positive HBeAg result suggests that the patient has a high viral load and may be at higher risk for liver damage and transmission of the virus. Conversely, a negative HBeAg result may indicate that the viral replication is under control, either due to the natural course of the disease or as a result of treatment. Monitoring HBeAg levels helps guide treatment decisions and evaluate disease progression.</p>', '<p>HBeAg (  -)        (HBV)      HBV                    HBeAg                   </p><p>HBeAg                  ,             HBeAg                            ,  HBeAg            ,              HBeAg                   </p>', '2024-07-26 18:30:42', '2024-07-26 18:30:42', NULL, 0),
(209, NULL, 'HLA-B27 By PCR', 'EXP0209', '3150', '1670', 'Within 4 Days', 'Fasting is not Mandatory', NULL, 'If is there other test of EDTA , 2 vials will be collected', NULL, NULL, 'The HLA-B27 by PCR test detects the presence of the HLA-B27 antigen on white blood cells. HLA-B27 is a specific genetic marker associated with certain autoimmune conditions, such as ankylosing spondylitis, reactive arthritis, and other spondyloarthropathies. The PCR (polymerase chain reaction) method amplifies and identifies the HLA-B27 gene to determine if it is present. A positive result indicates that the HLA-B27 antigen is present, which may suggest an increased risk for these conditions, although it is not a definitive diagnostic tool on its own.', NULL, '<p>The HLA-B27 by PCR (polymerase chain reaction) test is a genetic test that detects the presence of the HLA-B27 antigen, a specific protein found on the surface of white blood cells. This antigen is part of the human leukocyte antigen (HLA) system, which plays a crucial role in the immune response.</p><p>The PCR technique is used to amplify and identify the HLA-B27 gene, providing a highly sensitive and accurate measurement of its presence. HLA-B27 is associated with an increased risk of developing certain autoimmune conditions, particularly spondyloarthropathies like ankylosing spondylitis, reactive arthritis, and psoriatic arthritis. However, having the HLA-B27 antigen does not confirm the presence of these diseases but indicates a higher susceptibility.</p><p>The test is valuable in diagnosing and managing autoimmune disorders, guiding treatment decisions, and assessing familial risk. It should be interpreted in the context of clinical symptoms and other diagnostic findings.</p>', '<p>HLA-B27  PCR (  )       HLA-B27       ,                  (HLA)    ,        </p><p>PCR    HLA-B27          ,             HLA-B27   ,       ,  ,              , HLA-B27         ,        </p><p>          ,      ,                      </p>', '2024-07-26 18:47:43', '2024-07-26 18:47:43', NULL, 0),
(210, NULL, 'Homocysteine', 'EXP0210', '1370', '690', 'Next Day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'The homocysteine test measures the level of homocysteine, an amino acid, in the blood. Elevated levels of homocysteine can be an indicator of various health issues, including a higher risk of cardiovascular diseases such as heart attack and stroke, as well as other conditions like blood clots and cognitive decline.\r\n\r\nHomocysteine is produced during the metabolism of methionine, another amino acid. Typically, the body breaks down homocysteine with the help of vitamins B6, B12, and folate. Low levels of these vitamins can lead to increased homocysteine levels.\r\n\r\nThe test is often used to assess cardiovascular risk, particularly in individuals with a family history of heart disease or those with other risk factors. It can also help diagnose vitamin deficiencies and monitor conditions that affect homocysteine metabolism.', NULL, '<p>Homocysteine is an amino acid produced in the body as a byproduct of the metabolism of methionine, another amino acid. Normally, homocysteine is converted into other substances with the help of vitamins B6, B12, and folate. Elevated levels of homocysteine in the blood can be a risk factor for various health issues, including cardiovascular diseases such as heart disease, stroke, and blood clots. High homocysteine levels are also associated with cognitive decline and other health conditions.</p><p>An abnormal increase in homocysteine can result from deficiencies in B vitamins, genetic factors, or certain medical conditions. Monitoring homocysteine levels can help assess cardiovascular risk, diagnose vitamin deficiencies, and guide treatment strategies. Reducing elevated homocysteine levels typically involves dietary adjustments, such as increasing intake of B vitamins, and addressing any underlying health conditions. The homocysteine test provides valuable insights for managing and preventing cardiovascular and other related health issues.</p>', '<p>        ,    ,           ,    B6, B12,                           ,   , ,                  </p><p>     B  ,  ,                    ,      ,                         ,   B   ,                               </p>', '2024-07-26 18:51:07', '2024-07-26 18:51:07', NULL, 0),
(211, NULL, 'IMMUNOGLOBULIN-IgM', 'EXP0211', '960', '490', 'Next Da', 'Fasting is not Mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Immunoglobulin IgM is a blood test that measures the level of immunoglobulin M (IgM) antibodies, which are produced by the immune system in response to infection or foreign substances. IgM is the first type of antibody produced when the body encounters a new pathogen or antigen.\r\n\r\n**Key Points:**\r\n\r\n- **Early Response:** IgM antibodies are the earliest antibodies produced in response to an infection and indicate a recent or acute infection.\r\n- **Diagnosis:** Elevated levels of IgM can indicate recent infections with various pathogens, such as viruses or bacteria.\r\n- **Assessment:** The test helps diagnose and monitor infections and assess immune system function.\r\n\r\nIgM levels are useful for diagnosing recent or ongoing infections, distinguishing between acute and chronic stages of an illness, and evaluating the immune response to infections or vaccines.', NULL, '<p>Immunoglobulin IgM is a type of antibody, or immunoglobulin, produced by the immune system. It is the largest antibody in terms of molecular size and is the first antibody produced in response to an infection. IgM plays a critical role in the early stages of the immune response by identifying and neutralizing pathogens such as bacteria and viruses.</p><p>**Key Functions:**</p><p>- **Early Detection:** IgM is the initial antibody produced when the body encounters a new pathogen, indicating a recent or acute infection.<br>- **Immune Response:** It helps initiate the immune response by binding to antigens and activating other immune mechanisms, such as the complement system, to eliminate pathogens.<br>- **Diagnostic Value:** Elevated levels of IgM in the blood can indicate recent infections, autoimmune disorders, or certain other conditions.</p><p>Measuring IgM levels is essential for diagnosing and monitoring infections, determining the stage of an illness, and assessing the effectiveness of treatments or vaccinations.</p>', '<p> IgM    ,   ,                         IgM          ,            </p><p>** :**</p><p>- ** :** IgM                 ,        <br>- ** :**           ,    ,        <br>- ** :**   IgM     ,  ,        </p><p>IgM        ,      ,             </p>', '2024-07-26 19:00:38', '2024-07-26 19:00:38', NULL, 0),
(212, NULL, 'PHENYTOIN /DILANTIN / EPTOIN Level', 'EXP0212', '1470', '730', 'Next Day', 'Fasting is not Mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'A phenytoin (Dilantin/Eptoin) level measures the concentration of phenytoin in the blood. Phenytoin is an antiepileptic drug used to control seizures. Monitoring its levels ensures therapeutic efficacy while avoiding toxicity. Therapeutic ranges are crucial as low levels may lead to uncontrolled seizures, while high levels can cause side effects like dizziness, ataxia, and even severe toxicity. Regular monitoring helps maintain appropriate dosing, ensuring patient safety and effective seizure management.', NULL, '<p>A phenytoin (Dilantin/Eptoin) level measures the concentration of phenytoin, an antiepileptic medication, in the blood. Phenytoin is commonly prescribed to control seizures in patients with epilepsy and to prevent seizures following neurosurgery or traumatic brain injury. Monitoring the blood levels of phenytoin is critical due to its narrow therapeutic range.</p><p>Therapeutic drug monitoring helps ensure that the drug concentration stays within a range that is effective for seizure control without causing adverse effects. The therapeutic range for phenytoin is typically 10-20 micrograms per milliliter (mcg/mL). Levels below this range may not effectively prevent seizures, while levels above it can lead to toxicity. Symptoms of phenytoin toxicity include nystagmus, ataxia, slurred speech, confusion, and in severe cases, coma.</p><p>Phenytoin levels can be influenced by various factors, including patient adherence, drug interactions, liver function, and individual metabolism rates. Regular blood tests are essential to adjust the dosage as needed, especially when starting treatment, changing doses, or when there are changes in the patient\'s medical condition or medication regimen. Accurate dosing ensures the medications efficacy while minimizing the risk of side effects and toxicity.</p>', NULL, '2024-07-27 18:27:44', '2024-07-27 18:27:44', NULL, 0),
(213, NULL, 'Peripheral Blood Smear- PBS / PS', 'EXP0213', '199', '99', 'Same Day', 'Fasting is not Mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'A peripheral blood smear (PBS) measures and evaluates the characteristics of blood cells under a microscope. It provides detailed information about the size, shape, and appearance of red blood cells, white blood cells, and platelets. This test helps diagnose and monitor various conditions, including anemia, infections, and blood disorders like leukemia. By identifying abnormalities in blood cell morphology, a PBS can guide further diagnostic testing and inform treatment decisions, contributing to accurate and effective medical care.', NULL, '<p>A peripheral blood smear (PBS) is a laboratory test that involves spreading a drop of blood thinly onto a microscope slide for examination. This test provides a detailed visual assessment of blood cells, including red blood cells (RBCs), white blood cells (WBCs), and platelets. By examining the morphology and quantity of these cells, healthcare providers can diagnose and monitor various hematological conditions.</p><p>For red blood cells, a PBS can reveal size and shape abnormalities, such as those seen in anemia, sickle cell disease, or thalassemia. It can also identify variations in color and the presence of abnormal inclusions. For white blood cells, a PBS helps in detecting infections, inflammatory conditions, and blood cancers like leukemia. Abnormalities in the number, size, shape, and maturity of WBCs provide crucial diagnostic information. Platelet evaluation can reveal disorders affecting clotting and bleeding, such as thrombocytopenia or thrombocytosis.</p><p>A PBS is particularly useful in diagnosing conditions that automated blood analyzers might miss or misinterpret. It is a critical tool for hematologists and other healthcare providers, aiding in the accurate diagnosis, monitoring, and treatment of a wide range of blood-related disorders and systemic diseases.</p>', '<p>   ()                       ,     (),    (),                  ,              </p><p>    ,  ,                                      ,  ,                  , ,                        ,    ,     </p><p>                                     ,           , ,      </p>', '2024-07-27 18:32:19', '2024-07-27 18:32:19', NULL, 0),
(214, NULL, 'Sputum AFB', 'EXP0214', '495', '270', 'Fasting is not Mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'A sputum AFB (Acid-Fast Bacillus) test measures the presence of acid-fast bacteria, primarily Mycobacterium tuberculosis, in the sputum. This test is crucial for diagnosing tuberculosis (TB) and monitoring the effectiveness of TB treatment. Sputum samples are stained and examined under a microscope for AFB. Positive results indicate TB infection or other mycobacterial infections, necessitating further medical evaluation and treatment to prevent spread and ensure proper patient care.', NULL, '<p>A sputum AFB (Acid-Fast Bacillus) test is a laboratory diagnostic procedure used to detect the presence of acid-fast bacteria, particularly Mycobacterium tuberculosis, the causative agent of tuberculosis (TB), in a patient\'s sputum. This test is essential for diagnosing pulmonary TB, which primarily affects the lungs, and for monitoring the effectiveness of TB treatment.</p><p>The procedure involves collecting a sputum sample, which is mucus coughed up from the lower airways. The sample is then stained using a special technique, such as the Ziehl-Neelsen stain, which highlights acid-fast bacilli due to their unique cell wall composition that retains the stain even after being washed with an acid-alcohol solution. The stained sample is examined under a microscope to identify the characteristic rod-shaped bacteria.</p><p>A positive sputum AFB test indicates the presence of TB or other mycobacterial infections, prompting further confirmatory tests, such as culture or molecular assays, to establish a definitive diagnosis. Early detection through sputum AFB testing is critical for initiating appropriate treatment, preventing transmission, and controlling the spread of TB, particularly in high-risk populations. Accurate diagnosis and timely intervention are vital for effective TB management and improving patient outcomes.</p>', '<p>  (- )             - ,     ,   ()    ,                                   </p><p>          ,                        ,   - ,  -               -                               </p><p>               ,     ,      ,                       ,   ,                                      </p>', '2024-07-27 18:40:18', '2024-07-27 18:40:18', NULL, 0),
(215, NULL, 'Sputum Culture Aerobic', 'EXP0215', '1370', '599', 'Within 3 Days', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'A sputum culture aerobics test measures the presence of aerobic bacteria in the sputum, which is mucus coughed up from the lower airways. This test is crucial for diagnosing bacterial respiratory infections, such as pneumonia, bronchitis, or tuberculosis, caused by aerobic bacteria. \r\n\r\nThe procedure involves collecting a sputum sample and placing it on a culture medium that promotes the growth of aerobic bacteria. The sample is then incubated under conditions that allow aerobic bacteria to grow, typically in the presence of oxygen. After incubation, the bacteria are identified based on their colony characteristics and further biochemical tests.\r\n\r\nA positive sputum culture indicates a bacterial infection, identifying the specific pathogen responsible. This information guides healthcare providers in selecting the most appropriate antibiotic treatment, ensuring effective management of the infection and improving patient outcomes.', NULL, '<p>            ,                 ,   , ,  ,       ,      </p><p>                                             ,         ,                  </p><p>         ,                       ,       ,        </p>', NULL, '2024-07-27 18:45:31', '2024-07-27 18:45:31', NULL, 0),
(216, NULL, 'Quantiferon TB Gold - Interferon for Kochs', 'EXP0216', '2900', '1475', 'Next Day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'The QuantiFERON-TB Gold test measures the immune response to Mycobacterium tuberculosis, the bacteria causing tuberculosis (TB). It detects the release of interferon-gamma (IFN-) from white blood cells in response to TB-specific antigens. This blood test helps diagnose latent or active TB infections by indicating if a person has been exposed to TB bacteria. It is highly specific and used as an alternative to the traditional tuberculin skin test (TST).', NULL, '<p>The QuantiFERON-TB Gold test is a blood test used to detect latent or active tuberculosis (TB) infections by measuring the immune system\'s response to Mycobacterium tuberculosis, the bacterium responsible for TB. The test specifically measures the release of interferon-gamma (IFN-) from T-cells in the blood after they have been exposed to TB-specific antigens, which are proteins found in the TB bacteria but not in most non-tuberculosis mycobacteria or the BCG vaccine.</p><p>The procedure involves drawing a blood sample from the patient, which is then incubated with these TB-specific antigens. If the patient has been infected with TB bacteria, their white blood cells will recognize the antigens and release IFN-, which is measured by the test. A positive result indicates TB infection, but it does not distinguish between latent and active TB. Further clinical evaluation and additional tests, such as chest X-rays and sputum cultures, are needed to determine if the infection is active.</p><p>The QuantiFERON-TB Gold test is preferred for its accuracy, specificity, and convenience, providing a reliable alternative to the traditional tuberculin skin test (TST), especially in populations vaccinated with BCG or those unlikely to return for TST reading.</p>', '<p>-          ,        ,                           -        -  - (IFN-)     ,            -        </p><p>         ,     -                 ,          IFN-  ,               ,                      ,       ,     -       </p><p>-    ,         ,                              (TST)        </p>', '2024-07-27 19:55:47', '2024-07-27 19:55:47', NULL, 0),
(217, NULL, 'Troponin T - Qualitative', 'EXP0217', '1899', '995', 'Same Day', 'Overnight fasting for 9-12 hours', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'A troponin T qualitative test measures the presence of troponin T proteins in the blood, indicating heart muscle damage. Troponin T is released into the bloodstream when the heart muscle is injured, such as during a heart attack. The qualitative test doesn\'t quantify the amount but confirms if troponin T is detectable, helping diagnose acute coronary syndromes and other heart conditions. It\'s a crucial early indicator in emergency settings for evaluating patients with chest pain.', NULL, '<p>Troponin T is a protein found in cardiac muscle fibers that plays a crucial role in muscle contraction. It is part of the troponin complex, which includes troponin I and troponin C, and is essential for regulating the interaction between actin and myosin, the proteins responsible for muscle contraction. When the heart muscle is damaged, as occurs during a heart attack or other forms of cardiac injury, troponin T is released into the bloodstream.</p><p>The measurement of troponin T levels in the blood is a key diagnostic tool for detecting myocardial infarction (heart attack) and other heart-related conditions. Elevated troponin T levels indicate cardiac muscle damage and can help differentiate between cardiac and non-cardiac causes of chest pain. The presence of troponin T in the blood is highly specific to heart injury, making it a valuable marker for clinicians in diagnosing and managing acute coronary syndromes and other heart conditions.</p>', '<p>                            ,   I   C  ,              ,                 ,             ,        </p><p>          (  )                                       -                        ,                     </p>', '2024-07-28 18:01:02', '2024-07-28 18:01:02', NULL, 0),
(218, NULL, 'BNP B- TYPE NATRIURETIC PEPTIDE', 'EXP0218', '3200', '2269', 'Same Day', 'Overnight fasting for 9-12 hours', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'B-type natriuretic peptide (BNP) measures the level of BNP in the blood, a hormone produced by the heart\'s ventricles. BNP levels increase when the heart is under stress and struggling to pump blood effectively, such as in heart failure. Measuring BNP helps diagnose and assess the severity of heart failure, differentiate cardiac from non-cardiac causes of symptoms like shortness of breath, and guide treatment decisions. Elevated BNP levels indicate worsening heart function and fluid overload.', NULL, '<p>B-type natriuretic peptide (BNP) is a hormone produced primarily by the ventricles of the heart in response to excessive stretching of heart muscle cells. BNP plays a critical role in cardiovascular homeostasis by promoting vasodilation, reducing blood volume, and decreasing the workload on the heart. When the heart is under stress, such as in cases of heart failure, BNP is released into the bloodstream to counteract the increased pressure and volume load.</p><p>Measuring BNP levels in the blood is a valuable diagnostic tool for assessing heart failure and other cardiac conditions. Elevated BNP levels indicate that the heart is struggling to pump blood effectively, which can help differentiate heart failure from other conditions that cause similar symptoms, such as shortness of breath or edema. BNP testing is also useful for monitoring the severity of heart failure, guiding treatment decisions, and predicting patient outcomes, making it an essential marker in cardiovascular care.</p>', '<p>-   (BNP)                         BNP       ,     ,      ,               ,      , BNP                   </p><p>  BNP                        BNP                  ,                   ,       BNP       ,    ,            ,            </p>', '2024-07-28 18:06:35', '2024-07-28 18:06:35', NULL, NULL),
(219, NULL, 'Widal and Thypi Dot IgG & IgM Rapid - Salmonella Typhi', 'EXP0219', '850', '499', 'Same Day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'The Widal test and Typhi Dot rapid test measure antibodies in the blood to detect infection with *Salmonella typhi*, the bacteria causing typhoid fever. The Widal test measures agglutinating antibodies against O and H antigens of *S. typhi*, indicating an active or recent infection. The Typhi Dot test detects IgM and IgG antibodies, providing a quicker diagnosis. Both tests help identify typhoid fever but vary in accuracy and are often used alongside clinical evaluation and other diagnostic methods.', NULL, '<p>The Widal test and Typhi Dot rapid test are diagnostic tools used to detect typhoid fever, caused by *Salmonella typhi*.</p><p>The Widal test measures agglutinating antibodies (O and H) against *S. typhi* in the patient\'s serum, indicating an active or recent infection. It requires interpreting rising antibody titers over time, making it more accurate when paired with clinical symptoms and history.</p><p>The Typhi Dot test is a rapid serological test that detects IgM and IgG antibodies against *S. typhi*. It provides quicker results compared to the Widal test and is useful for early diagnosis. However, both tests have limitations in sensitivity and specificity and should be used alongside other clinical and laboratory findings for accurate diagnosis.</p>', NULL, '2024-07-28 18:11:50', '2024-07-28 18:11:50', NULL, 0),
(220, NULL, 'Serum IgE- Total serum IgE ( Immunoglobulin IgE )', 'EXP0220', '995', '499', 'Same Day', 'Fasting is not Manda', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'A serum IgE test measures the level of immunoglobulin E (IgE) antibodies in the blood. IgE is primarily associated with allergic reactions and responses to parasitic infections. Elevated IgE levels can indicate allergic conditions such as asthma, hay fever, eczema, and food allergies. It can also signal parasitic infections or certain immunological disorders. The test helps diagnose and manage allergic diseases by identifying heightened immune responses to specific allergens, guiding treatment plans, and monitoring the effectiveness of interventions like allergen avoidance or immunotherapy.', NULL, '<p>Serum IgE is a laboratory test that measures the concentration of immunoglobulin E (IgE) antibodies in the blood. IgE is a type of antibody produced by the immune system, primarily involved in allergic reactions and defense against parasitic infections. When the immune system encounters allergenssuch as pollen, pet dander, or certain foodsit produces IgE antibodies specific to those substances. These antibodies bind to allergens and trigger the release of histamines and other chemicals from mast cells and basophils, leading to allergic symptoms like itching, swelling, and difficulty breathing.</p><p>Elevated serum IgE levels can indicate a range of allergic conditions, including asthma, hay fever, eczema, and food allergies. High IgE levels can also suggest parasitic infections or certain immune system disorders, such as hyper-IgE syndrome. Measuring serum IgE helps healthcare providers diagnose and manage allergic diseases, identify specific allergens causing reactions, and monitor the effectiveness of treatments like allergen avoidance, medications, or immunotherapy.</p>', NULL, '2024-07-28 18:17:47', '2024-07-28 18:17:47', NULL, 0);
