(221, NULL, 'Triglycerides', 'EXP0221', '360', '140', 'Same Day', 'Overnight fasting for 9-12 hours', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'A triglycerides test measures the level of triglycerides in the blood, which are a type of fat (lipid). Elevated triglyceride levels can indicate an increased risk of cardiovascular disease, pancreatitis, and metabolic disorders. High levels often result from excess calorie consumption, obesity, uncontrolled diabetes, excessive alcohol intake, or genetic conditions. Monitoring triglycerides helps assess heart health and guide lifestyle or medical interventions to reduce the risk of heart disease and other related conditions.', NULL, '<p>Triglycerides are a type of fat (lipid) found in the blood. They are composed of three fatty acids attached to a glycerol backbone. Triglycerides are the main form of stored fat in the body and are derived from the food we eat, particularly fats and carbohydrates. After eating, any calories not immediately used for energy are converted into triglycerides and stored in fat cells. Later, hormones release these triglycerides for energy between meals.</p><p>A triglycerides test measures the level of triglycerides in the blood. High levels of triglycerides, known as hypertriglyceridemia, can increase the risk of cardiovascular disease, pancreatitis, and other metabolic disorders. Elevated triglyceride levels can result from factors such as obesity, uncontrolled diabetes, excessive alcohol consumption, a high-calorie diet, and genetic predispositions. Regular monitoring and management of triglyceride levels are important for maintaining heart health and reducing the risk of associated diseases through lifestyle changes and, if necessary, medication.</p>', '<p>     ()                                         ,             ,             ,                 ,              </p><p>            ,     ,  , ,              ,  ,    ,   ,                                 ,                </p>', '2024-07-29 13:37:16', '2024-07-29 13:37:16', NULL, 0),
(222, NULL, 'TTG IgA - Tissue Transglutaminase - IgA', 'EXP0222', '699', '1590', 'Next Day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'A tissue transglutaminase IgA (tTG-IgA) test measures the level of IgA antibodies against tissue transglutaminase in the blood. Elevated levels indicate an immune response to gluten, commonly seen in celiac disease. The test helps diagnose celiac disease by identifying this specific immune reaction, which leads to damage in the small intestine\'s lining. It is often used alongside other diagnostic methods, such as a biopsy, to confirm the presence of celiac disease and guide appropriate treatment.', NULL, '<p>The tissue transglutaminase IgA (tTG-IgA) test is a blood test used to diagnose celiac disease, an autoimmune disorder where ingestion of gluten leads to damage in the small intestine. This test measures the level of IgA antibodies against tissue transglutaminase, an enzyme found in the intestines. When individuals with celiac disease consume gluten, their immune system mistakenly targets this enzyme, leading to an inflammatory response and intestinal damage.</p><p>Elevated levels of tTG-IgA antibodies in the blood suggest that the body is mounting an immune response against gluten, indicating celiac disease. The tTG-IgA test is highly sensitive and specific for celiac disease, making it a valuable tool in the diagnostic process. It is often used in conjunction with other tests, such as an endoscopic biopsy of the small intestine, to confirm the diagnosis. Monitoring tTG-IgA levels can also help assess the effectiveness of a gluten-free diet in managing the disease.</p>', NULL, '2024-07-29 13:43:36', '2024-07-29 13:43:36', NULL, 0),
(223, NULL, 'Unconjugated Estriol-  uE3', 'EXP0223', '2380', '899', 'Same Day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Unconjugated estriol (uE3) is measured in maternal blood during pregnancy to assess fetal health and development. It is a form of estrogen produced by the placenta and fetal liver. Low levels of uE3 can indicate potential chromosomal abnormalities such as Down syndrome or Edwards syndrome, as well as fetal adrenal gland or liver issues. The test is often part of the second-trimester maternal serum screening (quad screen) to evaluate the risk of certain genetic conditions and developmental problems.', NULL, '<p>Unconjugated estriol (uE3) is a form of estrogen produced primarily by the placenta and the fetal liver during pregnancy. It is a key hormone involved in maintaining pregnancy and supporting fetal development. Unlike other forms of estriol, uE3 is not bound to proteins, allowing it to be measured directly in maternal blood. The measurement of uE3 levels is an important component of prenatal screening tests, such as the second-trimester maternal serum screening (quad screen), which typically includes measurements of alpha-fetoprotein (AFP), human chorionic gonadotropin (hCG), and inhibin-A, in addition to uE3.</p><p>Low levels of unconjugated estriol can indicate potential issues such as chromosomal abnormalities, including Down syndrome (trisomy 21) and Edwards syndrome (trisomy 18). Abnormally low levels can also suggest problems with the fetal adrenal glands or liver, or placental insufficiency. Conversely, normal levels of uE3 generally indicate healthy fetal development. This makes uE3 a valuable marker for assessing fetal health and guiding further diagnostic testing if needed.</p>', '<p>  (uE3)                                               , uE3      ,           uE3           ,        ( ),    - (AFP),    (hCG),  -A   uE3     </p><p>          ,    ,    ( 21)    ( 18)             ,              ,  uE3            uE3                    </p>', '2024-07-29 13:49:26', '2024-07-29 13:49:26', NULL, 0),
(224, NULL, 'Microalbumin- Urine spot', 'EXP0224', '999', '399', 'Same Day', 'Overnight fasting for 9-12 hours', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'A microalbumin urine spot test measures the amount of albumin, a protein, in a small urine sample. Elevated levels of albumin in the urine, known as microalbuminuria, can indicate early kidney damage, often associated with conditions like diabetes and hypertension. Detecting microalbuminuria helps in the early identification and management of kidney disease, enabling timely intervention to prevent progression to more severe kidney damage or chronic kidney disease. Regular monitoring is crucial for patients at risk of kidney issues.', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2024-07-29 13:52:53', '2024-07-29 13:52:53', NULL, 0),
(225, NULL, 'Valproic Acid -  ( Valproate-Valparin-Epilex )', 'EXP0225', '1480', '630', 'Within 4 Days', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'A valproic acid test measures the concentration of valproic acid or its salts (valproate, Valparin, Epilex) in the blood. These medications are used primarily to treat epilepsy, bipolar disorder, and migraines. Monitoring blood levels ensures that the drug is within the therapeutic range, which is crucial for maximizing efficacy and minimizing side effects. Abnormally low levels may suggest inadequate treatment, while high levels can indicate potential toxicity. Regular testing helps in adjusting dosages to effectively manage these conditions.', NULL, '<p>Valproic acid, valproate, Valparin, and Epilex are names for the same medication used primarily to manage epilepsy, bipolar disorder, and migraines. Valproic acid is the active ingredient, while valproate refers to its salt forms. Valparin and Epilex are brand names for medications containing valproic acid or valproate.</p><p>Valproic acid works by stabilizing electrical activity in the brain, which helps to prevent seizures, mood swings, and migraines. It is often prescribed for various types of seizures, including generalized and focal seizures. Monitoring blood levels of valproic acid is crucial to ensure it remains within the therapeutic range, as both low and high levels can lead to ineffective treatment or adverse effects, respectively. The medication can cause side effects such as gastrointestinal issues, weight gain, and liver problems. Regular blood tests help adjust dosages and manage side effects effectively, ensuring optimal treatment outcomes.</p>', NULL, '2024-07-29 14:01:43', '2024-07-29 14:01:43', NULL, NULL),
(226, NULL, 'VDRL- RPR for Syphilis', 'EXP0226', '350', '150', 'Same Day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'The VDRL (Venereal Disease Research Laboratory) and RPR (Rapid Plasma Reagin) tests are non-treponemal blood tests used to screen for syphilis. They measure antibodies produced in response to substances released during tissue damage caused by the syphilis bacteria. Both tests detect these non-specific antibodies, which may be elevated in syphilis infections. Positive results indicate a potential syphilis infection, but confirmatory treponemal tests are required for accurate diagnosis, as non-treponemal tests can also yield false positives.', NULL, '<p>The VDRL (Venereal Disease Research Laboratory) and RPR (Rapid Plasma Reagin) tests are non-treponemal serological tests used for screening syphilis. These tests detect the presence of non-specific antibodies, known as reagin antibodies, which are produced in response to lipids released from damaged tissues due to the syphilis bacteria, *Treponema pallidum*. Both tests are used to identify potential syphilis infections by measuring these antibodies in the blood.</p><p>While VDRL and RPR are useful for initial screening, they are not specific to syphilis and can yield false-positive results due to other conditions such as autoimmune diseases, pregnancy, or recent infections. A positive result usually requires confirmation with more specific treponemal tests, such as the FTA-ABS (Fluorescent Treponemal Antibody Absorption) test, which directly detects antibodies against *Treponema pallidum*. This confirmation is crucial for accurate diagnosis and appropriate treatment.</p>', NULL, '2024-07-29 14:08:07', '2024-07-29 14:08:07', NULL, 0),
(227, NULL, 'ABO Group and RH Type - Blood Group', 'EXP0227', '250', '149', 'Same Day', 'Fasting is not Manda', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'ABO and Rh typing are essential blood tests for determining blood group compatibility. \r\n\r\n- **ABO Typing** identifies one of four blood typesA, B, AB, or Obased on the presence or absence of A and B antigens on red blood cells. Blood type A has A antigens, type B has B antigens, type AB has both, and type O has neither. \r\n\r\n- **Rh Typing** determines the presence or absence of the Rh factor, a specific antigen on the surface of red blood cells. If the Rh factor is present, the blood type is Rh-positive (+); if absent, it is Rh-negative (). \r\n\r\nTogether, ABO and Rh typing ensure compatibility for blood transfusions, organ transplants, and help manage pregnancy-related conditions to prevent immune reactions and complications.', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2024-07-29 14:10:27', '2024-07-29 14:10:27', NULL, 0),
(228, NULL, 'Cardiolipin Antibody -ACL - IgA', 'EXP0228', '1190', '690', 'Next Day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'A cardiolipin antibody IgA test measures the level of IgA antibodies against cardiolipin, a type of lipid found in cell membranes. Elevated levels of these antibodies can indicate an increased risk of autoimmune conditions, particularly antiphospholipid syndrome (APS), which can lead to blood clotting disorders and complications during pregnancy. The test is often used to assess the presence of APS, especially when combined with other antiphospholipid antibodies tests, to evaluate thrombotic risk and guide treatment.', NULL, '<p>The cardiolipin antibody IgA test measures the level of immunoglobulin A (IgA) antibodies against cardiolipin, a lipid found in the membranes of cells. Cardiolipin antibodies are part of the antiphospholipid antibody group, which can interfere with normal blood clotting processes. Elevated levels of cardiolipin IgA can suggest the presence of antiphospholipid syndrome (APS), an autoimmune disorder that increases the risk of abnormal blood clotting, leading to complications such as deep vein thrombosis, pulmonary embolism, or recurrent miscarriages.</p><p>The test is used to assess the likelihood of APS and evaluate thrombotic risk. It is often ordered alongside other tests for antiphospholipid antibodies, such as cardiolipin IgG and IgM, and lupus anticoagulant tests, for a comprehensive assessment. Monitoring cardiolipin IgA levels helps in diagnosing APS and guiding treatment strategies to manage and reduce the risk of clotting-related complications.</p>', '<p>  IgA    (IgA)            ,                    ,              IgA      (APS)       ,   -            ,     ,   ,  -      </p><p>  APS                       ,   IgG  IgM,         ,         IgA    APS                             </p>', '2024-07-29 14:18:15', '2024-07-29 14:18:15', NULL, 0),
(229, NULL, 'Cardiolipin Antibody - ACL - IgM', 'EXP0229', '1190', '690', 'Next Day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'A cardiolipin antibodies IgM test measures the level of immunoglobulin M (IgM) antibodies against cardiolipin, a lipid found in cell membranes. Elevated IgM levels can indicate antiphospholipid syndrome (APS), an autoimmune condition that increases the risk of abnormal blood clotting, leading to issues like deep vein thrombosis, stroke, or recurrent miscarriages. The test is used to assess the likelihood of APS and guide further diagnostic and treatment decisions, often alongside other antiphospholipid antibody tests.', NULL, '<p>The cardiolipin antibody IgM test measures the level of immunoglobulin M (IgM) antibodies against cardiolipin, a lipid found in cell membranes. These antibodies are part of the antiphospholipid antibody group, which can interfere with normal blood clotting. Elevated levels of cardiolipin IgM can indicate the presence of antiphospholipid syndrome (APS), an autoimmune disorder that increases the risk of abnormal blood clotting, leading to complications such as deep vein thrombosis, pulmonary embolism, or recurrent miscarriages.</p><p>The IgM form of these antibodies is typically associated with recent or acute immune responses. This test is used to help diagnose APS and evaluate the risk of clotting disorders. It is often performed alongside other antiphospholipid antibody tests, such as cardiolipin IgG, and lupus anticoagulant tests, to provide a comprehensive assessment. Monitoring cardiolipin IgM levels aids in diagnosing APS and guiding appropriate treatment to manage and reduce clotting-related complications.</p>', '<p>  IgM   M (IgM)            ,                    ,              IgM      (APS)       ,   -            ,     ,   ,  -      </p><p>IgM               APS                        ,   IgG         ,         IgM    APS             ,              </p>', '2024-07-29 14:21:47', '2024-07-29 14:21:47', NULL, NULL),
(230, NULL, 'E2- Estradiol/ Estrogen', 'EXP0230', '950', '490', 'Same Day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'The E2 test, often referring to estradiol (E2), measures the level of estradiol, a form of estrogen hormone, in the blood. Estradiol is the most potent estrogen and plays a crucial role in regulating the menstrual cycle, reproductive system, and maintaining bone density. It is also involved in various functions throughout the body.\r\n\r\nThe E2 test is used to evaluate estrogen levels for diagnosing and monitoring conditions related to reproductive health, such as irregular menstrual cycles, menopause, or hormone therapy. It can also be used to assess ovarian function, fertility, and certain types of hormone-sensitive cancers.', NULL, '<p>Estradiol (E2) is a major form of estrogen, a key hormone in the regulation of the female reproductive system and secondary sexual characteristics. It is produced primarily in the ovaries in women, but also in smaller amounts by the adrenal glands and, during pregnancy, by the placenta. Estradiol plays a crucial role in the menstrual cycle, including the development and maintenance of the uterine lining, and it regulates the growth and function of reproductive organs.</p><p>In addition to its reproductive functions, estradiol is important for maintaining bone density, cardiovascular health, and cognitive function. The E2 test measures estradiol levels in the blood and is used to evaluate various conditions related to hormonal balance, such as menstrual irregularities, menopause, and hormone replacement therapy. It can also aid in assessing ovarian function and fertility, and monitoring hormone-sensitive cancers, like certain types of breast cancer.</p>', '<p> (E2)      ,                          ,                           ,           ,            </p><p>    ,    ,    ,            E2                         ,     , ,                - ,              </p>', '2024-07-29 14:28:35', '2024-07-29 14:28:35', NULL, 0),
(231, NULL, 'HIV 1 & 2  Rapid Test -  ( Human Immunodeficiency Virus )', 'EXP0231', '640', '380', 'Same Day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'An HIV rapid test measures the presence of antibodies to the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) or HIV antigens in the blood, saliva, or urine. This test is designed to quickly screen for HIV infection and provide results within minutes. There are two main types of rapid tests:\r\n\r\n1. **Antibody Tests:** Detect antibodies produced by the immune system in response to HIV infection.\r\n2. **Antigen/Antibody Tests:** Detect both HIV antibodies and the HIV p24 antigen, which is a protein associated with the virus.\r\n\r\nRapid HIV tests are used for early detection of HIV infection, often in clinical settings, community health programs, or at home. Positive results from a rapid test typically require confirmation with more comprehensive tests, such as a nucleic acid test (NAT) or an enzyme immunoassay (EIA), to ensure accurate diagnosis.', NULL, '<p>HIV (Human Immunodeficiency Virus) is a virus that attacks and weakens the immune system, specifically targeting CD4 cells (T cells), which are crucial for immune response. By damaging these cells, HIV impairs the body\'s ability to fight off infections and diseases. If left untreated, HIV can lead to acquired immunodeficiency syndrome (AIDS), the final and most severe stage of HIV infection, characterized by a significantly weakened immune system and an increased susceptibility to opportunistic infections and certain cancers.</p><p>HIV is transmitted through contact with certain body fluids from an infected person, including blood, semen, vaginal fluids, and breast milk. Common modes of transmission include unprotected sexual contact, sharing needles, and from mother to child during childbirth or breastfeeding. There is currently no cure for HIV, but antiretroviral therapy (ART) can manage the virus effectively, allowing individuals to live longer and healthier lives while reducing the risk of transmission.</p>', '<p>HIV (  )             ,    CD4  (T )    ,             , HIV               HIV     ,      (AIDS)     ,  HIV        ,                      </p><p>HIV        ,  , ,       ,              ,    ,                HIV     ,    (ART)         ,                      </p>', '2024-07-29 17:08:06', '2024-07-29 17:08:53', NULL, 2),
(232, NULL, 'Viral Marker -3H /STD Detection Panel -1 ,Triple Infection -HIV HBsAg HCV Rapid', 'EXP0232', '2250', '999', 'Same Day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'The HIV, HBsAg, and HCV rapid tests are diagnostic tools used to screen for different infectious diseases:\r\n\r\n1. **HIV Rapid Test:** Detects the presence of antibodies to HIV or the HIV antigen in blood, saliva, or urine. This test helps identify HIV infection, allowing for early diagnosis and prompt treatment.\r\n\r\n2. **HBsAg Rapid Test:** Measures the presence of hepatitis B surface antigen (HBsAg) in the blood. A positive result indicates an active hepatitis B virus infection, which can be acute or chronic.\r\n\r\n3. **HCV Rapid Test:** Detects antibodies to the hepatitis C virus (HCV) in the blood. A positive result suggests exposure to HCV, and further testing is needed to confirm a current infection and determine the appropriate treatment.\r\n\r\nAll three tests are designed for quick results, usually within minutes, and are often used in health screening programs and point-of-care settings. Positive results typically require confirmation with more detailed laboratory tests.', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2024-07-29 17:13:55', '2024-07-29 17:13:55', NULL, 4),
(233, NULL, 'Platelet Count -P/C', 'EXP0233', '299', '140', 'Same Day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'A platelet count measures the number of platelets (thrombocytes) in a given volume of blood. Platelets are small, disc-shaped cell fragments that play a crucial role in blood clotting and wound healing. They help prevent excessive bleeding by aggregating at sites of blood vessel injury and forming a clot.\r\n\r\nThe platelet count is a standard part of a complete blood count (CBC) test and is used to evaluate various conditions related to blood clotting. Abnormal platelet counts can indicate a range of medical issues:\r\n- **Low Platelet Count (Thrombocytopenia):** Can be caused by conditions such as bleeding disorders, certain infections, or bone marrow disorders.\r\n- **High Platelet Count (Thrombocytosis):** May be associated with inflammation, infection, or bone marrow disorders.\r\n\r\nMonitoring platelet count helps diagnose and manage these conditions and assess overall blood health.', NULL, '<p>Platelets, also known as thrombocytes, are small, disc-shaped cell fragments found in the blood. They are crucial for blood clotting and wound healing. Produced in the bone marrow from large cells called megakaryocytes, platelets help prevent excessive bleeding by clumping together at sites of blood vessel injury and forming a blood clot. This process involves the release of clotting factors and the formation of a plug to seal the wound.</p><p>Normal platelet levels are essential for maintaining hemostasis, the balance between bleeding and clotting. Abnormal platelet counts can lead to various health issues: low platelet counts (thrombocytopenia) can result in excessive bleeding or bruising, while high counts (thrombocytosis) can increase the risk of clotting disorders. Regular monitoring of platelet levels is important for diagnosing and managing these conditions.</p>', '<p>,      ,      ,                              , ,                     ,                               </p><p>                          :   ()         ,    ()                          </p>', '2024-07-29 17:19:33', '2024-07-29 17:19:33', NULL, NULL),
(234, NULL, 'ALP-Alkaline Phosphatase', 'EXP0234', '380', '150', 'Same Day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Alkaline phosphatase (ALP) is an enzyme found in various tissues throughout the body, with high concentrations in the liver, bile ducts, bones, and placenta. The ALP test measures the level of this enzyme in the blood. Elevated or decreased levels of ALP can indicate various health conditions.\r\n\r\n1. **Elevated ALP Levels:**\r\n   - **Liver Disease:** Conditions such as hepatitis, cirrhosis, liver cancer, or bile duct obstruction can cause high ALP levels.\r\n   - **Bone Disorders:** Diseases like Paget\'s disease, osteomalacia, or bone tumors can lead to increased ALP levels.\r\n   - **Other Conditions:** Pregnancy, hyperparathyroidism, and certain infections can also raise ALP levels.\r\n\r\n2. **Decreased ALP Levels:**\r\n   - **Nutritional Deficiencies:** Conditions like malnutrition or certain vitamin deficiencies can result in low ALP levels.\r\n   - **Genetic Disorders:** Rare inherited conditions can lead to decreased ALP production.\r\n\r\nThe ALP test helps diagnose and monitor these conditions, guiding appropriate treatment strategies.', NULL, '<p>Alkaline phosphatase (ALP) is an enzyme found throughout the body, with the highest concentrations in the liver, bile ducts, bones, and placenta. It plays a crucial role in various biochemical processes, including the breakdown of proteins and the transfer of phosphate groups in many types of molecules. The ALP test measures the level of this enzyme in the blood, providing important diagnostic information.</p><p>Elevated ALP levels can indicate liver diseases such as hepatitis, cirrhosis, or bile duct obstruction, as well as bone disorders like Paget\'s disease, osteomalacia, or bone tumors. Other conditions, such as pregnancy, hyperparathyroidism, and certain infections, can also raise ALP levels. Conversely, decreased ALP levels can be seen in cases of malnutrition, vitamin deficiencies, or rare genetic disorders.</p><p>The ALP test is commonly used in conjunction with other tests to diagnose and monitor conditions affecting the liver and bones. It helps guide treatment decisions and assess the effectiveness of ongoing therapies.</p>', '<p>  (ALP)          ,    ,  ,                ,                 ALP          ,       </p><p> ALP     , ,       -     , ,           ,  , ,     ALP      ,  ALP  ,   ,           </p><p>ALP                                               </p>', '2024-07-29 18:39:18', '2024-07-29 18:39:18', NULL, NULL),
(235, NULL, 'Albumin Serum', 'EXP0235', '390', '160', 'Same Day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'A serum albumin test measures the amount of albumin in the blood. Albumin is the most abundant protein in human blood plasma and plays a vital role in maintaining oncotic pressure, which helps keep fluid within the blood vessels. It also functions in transporting hormones, vitamins, drugs, and ions like calcium throughout the body.\r\n\r\nA serum albumin test is used to:\r\n- **Assess Liver Function:** Low levels can indicate liver disease, as albumin is produced in the liver.\r\n- **Evaluate Kidney Function:** Low levels may suggest kidney disease, where albumin is lost in the urine.\r\n- **Check Nutritional Status:** Low levels can result from malnutrition or conditions causing poor protein absorption.\r\n- **Monitor Chronic Conditions:** It helps in the ongoing assessment of diseases that can affect protein levels in the blood.\r\n\r\nBy measuring serum albumin, healthcare providers can gain insights into a patients overall health and identify potential underlying health issues.', NULL, '<p>Serum albumin is the most abundant protein in human blood plasma, produced primarily by the liver. It plays a crucial role in maintaining oncotic pressure, which helps keep fluid within blood vessels and prevents it from leaking into tissues. Additionally, serum albumin functions as a transport protein, carrying hormones, vitamins, drugs, and ions like calcium throughout the body.</p><p>A serum albumin test measures the level of albumin in the blood and is used to assess overall health. Low serum albumin levels can indicate liver diseases such as cirrhosis or hepatitis, kidney diseases where albumin is lost in the urine, and conditions related to malnutrition or poor protein absorption. High levels are less common but can occur in dehydration or certain genetic conditions.</p><p>Monitoring serum albumin levels helps diagnose and manage various medical conditions, evaluate nutritional status, and guide treatment decisions, providing valuable insights into a patient\'s health status.</p>', '<p>              ,                     ,                     ,           ,  , , ,          </p><p>                                ,          ,                    ,          </p><p>            ,               ,            </p>', '2024-07-29 18:43:45', '2024-07-29 18:43:45', NULL, NULL),
(236, NULL, 'ASA - Anti Sperm Antibodies', 'EXP0236', '1890', '990', 'Within 3 Days', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'The anti-sperm antibodies (ASA) test measures the presence of antibodies that target and bind to sperm. These antibodies can be produced by either the male or female immune system and may interfere with the sperm\'s ability to move and fertilize an egg.\r\n\r\nIn males, the immune system may mistakenly identify sperm as harmful invaders and produce antibodies against them, often due to injury, surgery, infection, or a breakdown of the blood-testis barrier. In females, anti-sperm antibodies can develop in response to exposure to sperm, possibly affecting fertility by inhibiting sperm movement through the cervical mucus or attacking sperm before it reaches the egg.\r\n\r\nThe ASA test is used in the evaluation of infertility, particularly when no other cause is identified. Elevated levels of anti-sperm antibodies can indicate an immune response that may contribute to difficulties in conceiving, guiding appropriate treatment options to improve the chances of successful fertilization.', NULL, '<p>Anti-sperm antibodies (ASA) are immune system proteins that mistakenly target and attach to sperm cells. These antibodies can be produced by either men or women and can interfere with sperm function, movement, and the ability to fertilize an egg. In men, ASAs can develop due to injury, infection, surgery, or other factors that disrupt the normal barriers separating sperm from the immune system. In women, ASAs can form in response to exposure to sperm.</p><p>The presence of ASAs is significant in the context of infertility, as they can hinder the sperm\'s capacity to travel through the female reproductive tract or to penetrate the egg, thus reducing the likelihood of successful conception. Testing for ASAs is often part of a comprehensive evaluation when couples face unexplained infertility, and detecting these antibodies can help guide appropriate treatment strategies, such as immunosuppressive therapy or assisted reproductive techniques, to improve fertility outcomes.</p>', '<p>-  (ASA)                                 ,               , , ,       ASAs                     , ASAs         </p><p>    ASAs    ,                        ,                 ,  ASAs          ,                  ,       ,        </p>', '2024-07-29 18:48:05', '2024-07-29 18:48:05', NULL, NULL),
(237, NULL, 'BUN - blood Urea Nitrogen', 'EXP0237', '195', '99', 'Same Day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'A blood urea nitrogen (BUN) test measures the amount of urea nitrogen in the blood. Urea nitrogen is a waste product formed in the liver when the body breaks down proteins, and it is excreted by the kidneys. The BUN test is commonly used to assess kidney function and to diagnose or monitor kidney disease or dysfunction.\r\n\r\nKey points about the BUN test:\r\n\r\n- **Kidney Function:** Elevated BUN levels can indicate impaired kidney function or kidney disease, as the kidneys are less able to remove urea from the blood.\r\n- **Liver Function:** The liver produces urea; therefore, BUN levels can also reflect liver function.\r\n- **Hydration Status:** High BUN levels can be a sign of dehydration, while low levels might indicate overhydration.\r\n- **Diet and Nutrition:** High-protein diets or significant protein breakdown in the body can increase BUN levels.\r\n\r\nThe BUN test is often performed alongside other tests, such as creatinine, to get a more comprehensive picture of kidney health.', NULL, '<p>Blood urea nitrogen (BUN) is a measure of the amount of urea nitrogen in the blood. Urea nitrogen is a waste product formed from the breakdown of proteins in the liver. Once produced, urea is transported to the kidneys, where it is filtered out of the blood and excreted in the urine. The BUN test is used primarily to evaluate kidney function, as elevated levels can indicate that the kidneys are not effectively filtering urea from the blood, which may suggest kidney disease or dysfunction.</p><p>In addition to assessing kidney health, BUN levels can reflect liver function since the liver is responsible for urea production. Factors such as dehydration, a high-protein diet, or conditions affecting protein metabolism can also influence BUN levels. The BUN test is commonly performed alongside other kidney function tests, such as serum creatinine, to provide a more comprehensive evaluation of renal health.</p>', '<p>   (BUN)                             ,        ,              BUN                ,                    ,          </p><p>       , BUN        ,         ,   ,          BUN       BUN       ,        ,            </p>', '2024-07-29 18:54:03', '2024-07-29 18:54:03', NULL, NULL),
(238, NULL, 'ANCA - Anti Neutrophil Cytoplasmic Antibodies by IFA Meathod', 'EXP0238', '2980', '1690', 'Within 4 Days', 'Overnight fasting for 9-12 hours', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'ANCA (Anti-Neutrophil Cytoplasmic Antibodies) is a test that measures the presence of specific antibodies in the blood that target proteins in neutrophils, a type of white blood cell. The ANCA test is primarily used to help diagnose and manage autoimmune diseases, particularly those that involve systemic vasculitis, which is inflammation of blood vessels.\r\n\r\nKey points about the ANCA test:\r\n\r\n- **Types:** There are two main types of ANCA, based on the staining pattern observed in the test: c-ANCA (cytoplasmic ANCA) and p-ANCA (perinuclear ANCA). These types correspond to different autoimmune conditions.\r\n- **Conditions:** Elevated levels of ANCA are associated with various autoimmune diseases, including Wegener\'s granulomatosis (now called granulomatosis with polyangiitis), microscopic polyangiitis, and Churg-Strauss syndrome.\r\n- **Diagnostic Use:** The test helps in diagnosing these conditions, assessing disease activity, and monitoring response to treatment. \r\n\r\nOverall, the ANCA test is a valuable tool in the evaluation of autoimmune disorders and related inflammatory conditions.', NULL, '<p>Anti-neutrophil cytoplasmic antibodies (ANCA) are antibodies directed against proteins in the cytoplasm of neutrophils, a type of white blood cell involved in the body\'s immune response. The ANCA test measures the presence and levels of these antibodies in the blood and is used primarily to diagnose and manage certain autoimmune diseases, particularly those characterized by inflammation of blood vessels, known as vasculitis.</p><p>The test can reveal two main types of ANCA based on staining patterns: c-ANCA (cytoplasmic ANCA), which is often associated with granulomatosis with polyangiitis (formerly Wegener\'s granulomatosis), and p-ANCA (perinuclear ANCA), which is commonly linked to microscopic polyangiitis and Churg-Strauss syndrome. Elevated ANCA levels can indicate ongoing inflammatory processes and help assess disease activity and response to treatment. The ANCA test is valuable in diagnosing autoimmune disorders and monitoring the progression and management of these conditions.</p>', '<p>-   (ANCA)                                   ANCA                           ,                ,    </p><p>      ANCA    : c-ANCA ( ANCA),      (    )    ,  p-ANCA ( ANCA),      -       ANCA                          ANCA                  </p>', '2024-07-29 19:14:43', '2024-07-29 19:14:43', NULL, NULL),
(239, NULL, 'AEC - Absolute Eosinophil Count', 'EXP0239', '290', '150', 'Same Day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'The Absolute Eosinophil Count (AEC) measures the number of eosinophils, a type of white blood cell, present in a specific volume of blood. Eosinophils are involved in the body\'s immune response, particularly in combating parasitic infections and in allergic reactions.\r\n\r\nHeres what the AEC can indicate:\r\n\r\n- **Elevated Levels:** High eosinophil counts may suggest allergic reactions (such as asthma or eczema), parasitic infections, autoimmune diseases, or certain types of cancers like leukemia.\r\n- **Low Levels:** Reduced eosinophil counts are less common but can occur in conditions such as Cushing\'s syndrome or as a result of certain medications.\r\n\r\nThe AEC is used to help diagnose and monitor conditions related to immune system dysfunction and to evaluate the effectiveness of treatments for such conditions.', NULL, '<p>The Absolute Eosinophil Count (AEC) is a laboratory test that measures the number of eosinophils, a type of white blood cell, in a specific volume of blood. Eosinophils are key components of the immune system, playing a significant role in combating parasitic infections and mediating allergic responses. Elevated eosinophil levels can indicate various conditions such as allergic diseases (e.g., asthma, eczema), parasitic infections (e.g., roundworms, hookworms), and certain autoimmune disorders or cancers like eosinophilic leukemia.</p><p>Conversely, low eosinophil counts are less common but can be associated with conditions such as Cushing\'s syndrome or the effects of certain medications. The AEC test helps diagnose and monitor these conditions by providing insight into the body\'s immune response. It is often used in conjunction with other tests to assess the overall health status and guide treatment strategies for diseases involving eosinophils.</p>', '<p>   (AEC)           ,      ,                          </p><p>              ( , ),   ( , ),         </p><p> ,                     AEC            ,         ,            </p>', '2024-07-29 19:18:55', '2024-07-29 19:18:55', NULL, NULL);
