(240, NULL, 'Sodium Serum', 'EXP0240', '250', '140', 'Same Day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'The sodium serum test measures the concentration of sodium in the blood. Sodium is an essential electrolyte that helps regulate water balance, blood pressure, and the normal function of nerves and muscles. Maintaining proper sodium levels is crucial for overall health.\r\n\r\nAbnormal sodium levels can indicate various health issues:\r\n- **Hyponatremia (low sodium levels):** Can be caused by conditions such as kidney disease, heart failure, liver disease, dehydration, or excessive fluid intake.\r\n- **Hypernatremia (high sodium levels):** Often results from dehydration, certain medications, or conditions that cause excessive loss of water, such as diabetes insipidus.\r\n\r\nThe sodium serum test is commonly used to evaluate electrolyte balance, diagnose underlying medical conditions, and monitor the effectiveness of treatments for disorders affecting sodium levels. It is an important tool in assessing a patients overall fluid and electrolyte status.', NULL, '<p>Sodium serum, also known as serum sodium, is a measurement of the concentration of sodium ions in the blood. Sodium is a vital electrolyte that helps regulate water balance, nerve function, and muscle contraction. It is essential for maintaining blood pressure and ensuring proper fluid distribution within and outside cells.</p><p>The sodium serum test is commonly performed to assess electrolyte and fluid balance in the body. Normal sodium levels typically range from 135 to 145 milliequivalents per liter (mEq/L). Abnormal sodium levels can indicate various health conditions. Hyponatremia, or low sodium levels, can result from kidney disease, heart failure, liver disease, or excessive fluid intake. Hypernatremia, or high sodium levels, is often caused by dehydration, certain medications, or conditions leading to significant water loss, such as diabetes insipidus.</p><p>Regular monitoring of serum sodium levels helps diagnose and manage conditions affecting electrolyte balance and guides appropriate treatment strategies to restore and maintain optimal health.</p>', '<p> ,       ,                 ,                                </p><p>                              ,    ,   ,  ,  ,          ,    ,  ,  ,             </p><p>                                       </p>', '2024-07-30 14:02:58', '2024-07-30 14:02:58', NULL, NULL),
(241, NULL, 'Serum Creatinine', 'EXP0241', '390', '140', 'Same Day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Creatinine is a waste product generated from the normal breakdown of muscle tissue. The kidneys filter creatinine out of the blood, and it is excreted in urine. The creatinine test measures the level of creatinine in the blood or urine and is commonly used to assess kidney function.\r\n\r\nThe test is useful for diagnosing and monitoring kidney diseases, as elevated creatinine levels can indicate impaired kidney function or kidney damage. The normal range for blood creatinine levels varies depending on age, gender, and muscle mass\r\n\r\nIn addition to blood creatinine tests, the creatinine clearance test can measure how effectively the kidneys are filtering creatinine by comparing creatinine levels in blood and urine over a 24-hour period. This provides a more comprehensive evaluation of kidney function and helps in diagnosing and managing kidney-related health issues.', NULL, '<p>Creatinine is a waste product formed by the normal breakdown of muscle tissue. It is produced from creatine, a molecule essential for energy production in muscles. Once formed, creatinine is released into the bloodstream and transported to the kidneys, where it is filtered out and excreted in urine.</p><p>The level of creatinine in the blood is a key indicator of kidney function. Normally, the kidneys efficiently remove creatinine from the blood. However, when kidney function is impaired, creatinine levels in the blood can rise. Measuring blood creatinine levels is a common method for assessing kidney health. The normal range for creatinine in blood typically varies from 0.6 to 1.2 milligrams per deciliter (mg/dL) for adults, though it can differ based on age, gender, and muscle mass.</p><p>Creatinine tests, including blood creatinine and creatinine clearance tests, are essential for diagnosing and monitoring kidney diseases, ensuring timely and appropriate medical intervention.</p>', '<p>                 ,                ,               ,          </p><p>               ,           ,      ,                         &nbsp;</p><p> ,         ,            ,          </p>', '2024-07-30 14:09:18', '2024-07-30 14:09:18', NULL, NULL),
(242, NULL, 'Chloride', 'EXP0242', '390', '140', 'Same Day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'The chloride test measures the concentration of chloride ions in the blood. Chloride is an essential electrolyte that helps maintain proper fluid balance, acid-base balance, and overall electrical neutrality in the body. It works closely with other electrolytes such as sodium, potassium, and bicarbonate. Chloride is primarily ingested through diet and absorbed in the intestines.\r\n\r\nAbnormal chloride levels can indicate various health issues. Elevated chloride levels, or hyperchloremia, can result from dehydration, kidney dysfunction, or excessive intake of saline solutions. Low chloride levels, or hypochloremia, can occur due to conditions like prolonged vomiting, diarrhea, or certain hormonal imbalances. Regular monitoring of chloride levels is crucial for diagnosing and managing conditions affecting electrolyte balance and overall health.', NULL, '<p>Chloride is an essential electrolyte found in the body, primarily in bodily fluids such as blood, urine, and sweat. It plays a crucial role in maintaining fluid balance, electrolyte balance, and acid-base balance within the body. Chloride ions work closely with sodium and potassium ions to regulate osmotic pressure and ensure the proper distribution of fluids in and out of cells. This balance is vital for normal cellular function, nerve transmission, and muscle contraction.</p><p>Chloride is typically ingested through dietary sources, particularly table salt (sodium chloride), and is absorbed in the intestines. The kidneys play a key role in regulating chloride levels by filtering and reabsorbing it as needed. Abnormal chloride levels can indicate various health conditions. Elevated chloride levels (hyperchloremia) can result from dehydration, kidney dysfunction, or excessive intake of saline solutions. Low chloride levels (hypochloremia) can be due to conditions like prolonged vomiting, diarrhea, or certain hormonal imbalances. Monitoring chloride levels helps diagnose and manage conditions affecting electrolyte balance and overall health.<br>&nbsp;</p>', '<p>           ,                ,    -                                           ,         </p><p>    ,      ( )                         ,     :                  () ,                 ()    ,                                    </p>', '2024-07-30 14:13:11', '2024-07-30 14:13:11', NULL, NULL),
(243, NULL, 'Calcium Serum', 'EXP0243', '350', '150', 'Same Day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'A calcium measurement typically refers to the amount of calcium in the blood. Calcium is vital for various bodily functions, including bone health, muscle contraction, and nerve signaling. Blood calcium levels can be measured through a test that includes both total calcium (which measures both free and bound calcium) and ionized calcium (which measures the free, active form). Abnormal levels can indicate various conditions, such as parathyroid issues, kidney disease, or vitamin D deficiencies.', NULL, '<p>Calcium is a mineral essential for numerous physiological functions in the human body. It plays a crucial role in maintaining bone and teeth health, as it is a primary component of bone tissue. Calcium is also vital for muscle contraction, nerve transmission, and blood clotting. The mineral helps regulate heart rhythms and supports proper hormone secretion. In the body, calcium is found predominantly in bones and teeth, with smaller amounts in the blood and other tissues. Blood calcium levels are tightly regulated by hormones, including parathyroid hormone and calcitonin. A deficiency or excess of calcium can lead to various health issues, such as osteoporosis, muscle cramps, or abnormal heart rhythms. Dietary sources of calcium include dairy products, leafy greens, and fortified foods. Calcium supplements are also used to ensure adequate intake, especially in individuals at risk of deficiency.</p>', '<p>                            ,              ,                                        ,               ,     ,               ,                    ,                 ,           </p>', '2024-07-30 14:17:19', '2024-07-30 14:17:19', NULL, NULL),
(244, NULL, 'Total Cholesterol', 'EXP0244', '140', '350', 'Same Day', 'Overnight Fasting for 9-12 hours', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Total cholesterol measures the overall amount of cholesterol in the blood, including low-density lipoprotein (LDL), high-density lipoprotein (HDL), and very low-density lipoprotein (VLDL). LDL is often termed \"bad\" cholesterol as it can lead to plaque buildup in arteries, while HDL is considered \"good\" cholesterol because it helps remove LDL from the bloodstream. VLDL is another type of cholesterol linked to triglycerides. Monitoring total cholesterol helps assess cardiovascular health and the risk of heart disease.', NULL, '<p>Total cholesterol is a measure of the overall amount of cholesterol present in the blood. It encompasses three main components: low-density lipoprotein (LDL), high-density lipoprotein (HDL), and very low-density lipoprotein (VLDL). LDL, often referred to as \"bad\" cholesterol, can contribute to the buildup of plaque in the arteries, increasing the risk of atherosclerosis and heart disease. HDL, known as \"good\" cholesterol, helps to remove LDL from the bloodstream and transports it to the liver for processing. VLDL, another type of \"bad\" cholesterol, carries triglycerides, a type of fat, through the bloodstream. A total cholesterol test provides a comprehensive view of these components, which helps evaluate cardiovascular health and assess the risk of heart disease. Regular monitoring of total cholesterol levels is important for managing and preventing conditions related to high cholesterol, such as coronary artery disease and stroke.</p>', '<p>                  : -  (LDL), -  (HDL),   -  (VLDL) LDL,  \"\"    ,          ,           HDL,  \"\"    , LDL                   VLDL,     \"\" ,   ,    ,              ,                        ,      ,                </p>', '2024-07-30 14:20:25', '2024-07-30 14:20:25', NULL, NULL),
(245, NULL, 'RA Factor -Rheumatoid Factor Quantitative', 'EXP0245', '590', '350', 'Same Day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'The RA (Rheumatoid Arthritis) factor test measures the level of rheumatoid factor (RF) antibodies in the blood. Elevated RF levels can suggest the presence of rheumatoid arthritis, an autoimmune condition that affects the joints. However, RF can also be elevated in other autoimmune disorders and chronic infections. Thus, while a high RA factor can be indicative of rheumatoid arthritis, it is not a definitive diagnosis and should be considered alongside other clinical findings and tests.', NULL, '<p>Rheumatoid factor (RA factor) is an autoantibody commonly associated with rheumatoid arthritis (RA), an autoimmune disease characterized by joint inflammation and damage. RA factor is produced by the immune system and targets the bodys own tissues, particularly affecting the joints. The RA factor test measures the concentration of these antibodies in the blood. Elevated levels of RA factor can suggest the presence of rheumatoid arthritis, but they are not exclusive to it; high levels can also be found in other autoimmune disorders, such as lupus or Sjgren\'s syndrome, and in chronic infections. Additionally, some individuals with rheumatoid arthritis may have normal RA factor levels. Therefore, while RA factor levels can provide clues about autoimmune activity, a diagnosis of rheumatoid arthritis is based on a combination of clinical symptoms, physical examination, and other diagnostic tests.</p>', '<p>  (RA )     :   (RA)    ,                RA              ,       RA            RA             ,        ;     ,     ,           ,       RA        ,  RA            ,      ,            </p>', '2024-07-30 14:32:19', '2024-07-30 14:32:19', NULL, NULL),
(246, NULL, 'Adenosine Deaminase Serum - ADA', 'EXP0246', '950', '495', 'Next Day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Adenosine deaminase (ADA) measures the activity of the enzyme adenosine deaminase in the blood or tissues. ADA plays a crucial role in purine metabolism by converting adenosine into inosine. Elevated levels of ADA can indicate various conditions, such as tuberculosis, certain cancers, and autoimmune disorders like rheumatoid arthritis. It is particularly useful in diagnosing and monitoring tuberculosis, especially when testing fluid samples from areas like the pleural cavity. Low levels may be seen in conditions such as severe combined immunodeficiency (SCID).', NULL, '<p>Adenosine deaminase (ADA) is an enzyme that catalyzes the deamination of adenosine, converting it into inosine as part of purine metabolism. This process is essential for maintaining the balance of nucleotides and nucleic acids within cells. ADA activity is particularly important in the immune system, where it helps regulate lymphocyte proliferation and function. Abnormal levels of ADA can be indicative of various health conditions. Elevated ADA levels are often associated with tuberculosis, especially in pleural fluid, and can also be seen in certain cancers and autoimmune disorders. Conversely, low ADA levels may suggest conditions like severe combined immunodeficiency (SCID), a rare genetic disorder affecting immune system function. ADA testing is utilized in diagnosing and monitoring these conditions, offering insights into metabolic and immune system health.</p>', '<p>  (ADA)           katalyze  ,         ,                       ADA          ,              ADA            ADA      (TB)    ,    ,              ,  ADA     (SCID)       ,               ADA           ,            </p>', '2024-07-30 14:36:30', '2024-07-30 14:36:30', NULL, NULL),
(247, NULL, 'HSV-1 IgG Antibodies', 'EXP0247', '780', '425', 'Next Day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'HSV-1 IgG antibodies measure the presence of immunoglobulin G (IgG) antibodies specific to the herpes simplex virus type 1 (HSV-1) in the blood. These antibodies indicate a past or current infection with HSV-1, which commonly causes oral herpes. A positive IgG result suggests that a person has been exposed to HSV-1 at some point, even if they are not currently experiencing symptoms. This test helps in diagnosing previous HSV-1 infections and understanding immune response.', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2024-07-30 14:44:46', '2024-07-30 14:44:46', NULL, NULL),
(248, NULL, 'HSV-II IgG Antibodies', 'EXP0248', '780', '425', 'Next Day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'HSV-2 IgG antibodies measure the presence of immunoglobulin G (IgG) antibodies specific to the herpes simplex virus type 2 (HSV-2) in the blood. These antibodies indicate a past or current infection with HSV-2, which commonly causes genital herpes. A positive IgG result suggests that a person has been exposed to HSV-2 at some point, even if they are not currently experiencing symptoms. This test helps in diagnosing previous HSV-2 infections, understanding immune response, and differentiating between HSV-1 and HSV-2 infections.', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2024-07-30 15:30:51', '2024-07-30 15:30:51', NULL, NULL),
(249, NULL, 'DHEAS - Dehydroepiandrosterone Sulphate', 'EXP0249', '1480', '690', 'Same Day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Dehydroepiandrosterone sulfate (DHEAS) measures the level of DHEAS in the blood. DHEAS is a steroid hormone produced primarily by the adrenal glands, with smaller amounts produced by the gonads and brain. It serves as a precursor to androgens and estrogens, the male and female sex hormones. Measuring DHEAS levels helps evaluate adrenal gland function and can aid in diagnosing conditions related to hormone imbalances, such as adrenal tumors, adrenal insufficiency, polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS), and certain types of congenital adrenal hyperplasia (CAH). Elevated or decreased levels can indicate various health issues.', NULL, '<p>Dehydroepiandrosterone sulfate (DHEAS) is a steroid hormone primarily produced by the adrenal glands, with smaller amounts produced by the gonads and brain. It is the sulfated form of dehydroepiandrosterone (DHEA) and serves as a precursor to sex hormones, including androgens and estrogens. DHEAS levels in the blood provide insights into adrenal gland function and overall hormonal balance. Elevated DHEAS levels can indicate conditions such as adrenal tumors, polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS), and certain types of congenital adrenal hyperplasia (CAH). Conversely, low DHEAS levels may suggest adrenal insufficiency or other endocrine disorders. Measuring DHEAS is useful in diagnosing and monitoring these conditions, as well as assessing the cause of symptoms like excessive hair growth, acne, and irregular menstrual cycles. It plays a crucial role in evaluating hormonal health and guiding appropriate treatment strategies.</p>', '<p>  (DHEAS)              ,                 (DHEA)                  DHEAS                  DHEAS   ,    (PCOS),        (CAH)         ,  DHEAS             DHEAS           ,     , ,                                  </p>', '2024-07-30 15:37:18', '2024-07-30 15:37:18', NULL, NULL),
(250, NULL, 'Progesterone', 'EXP0250', '660', '390', 'Same Day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'A progesterone measurement determines the level of progesterone, a steroid hormone, in the blood. Progesterone is primarily produced by the ovaries after ovulation and by the placenta during pregnancy. It plays a crucial role in regulating the menstrual cycle, supporting early stages of pregnancy, and preparing the endometrium (uterine lining) for implantation of a fertilized egg. In men and non-pregnant women, the adrenal glands produce small amounts of progesterone. Measuring progesterone levels helps assess ovulation, diagnose infertility issues, monitor the health of a pregnancy, and evaluate menstrual irregularities. Abnormal levels can indicate conditions such as ectopic pregnancy, ovarian cysts, or adrenal gland disorders.', NULL, '<p>Progesterone is a steroid hormone essential for regulating the menstrual cycle and supporting pregnancy. In women, it is primarily produced by the ovaries after ovulation and by the placenta during pregnancy. Progesterone prepares the endometrium (uterine lining) for the implantation of a fertilized egg and helps maintain a pregnancy by preventing uterine contractions that could cause the body to reject the developing embryo. It also plays a role in the development of mammary glands for milk production. In men and non-pregnant women, the adrenal glands produce small amounts of progesterone. Measuring progesterone levels can provide valuable insights into ovulation, fertility, and menstrual health. Abnormal progesterone levels can indicate various conditions, such as ectopic pregnancy, ovarian cysts, or adrenal gland disorders. This hormone is crucial for reproductive health and the successful continuation of pregnancy.</p>', '<p>                      ,                     (  )                        ,                              -  ,                ,                   ,   ,  ,                      </p>', '2024-07-30 15:42:06', '2024-07-30 15:42:06', NULL, NULL),
(251, NULL, 'Anti Phospholipid Antibody /APL- IgM', 'EXP0251', '1200', '590', 'Next Day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Anti-phospholipid antibodies (IgM) measure the presence of immunoglobulin M (IgM) antibodies that target phospholipids, which are essential components of cell membranes. These antibodies can interfere with normal blood clotting processes. Elevated levels of anti-phospholipid IgM antibodies are associated with antiphospholipid syndrome (APS), an autoimmune disorder that increases the risk of blood clots, pregnancy complications (such as recurrent miscarriages), and other vascular issues. The test helps diagnose APS and evaluate the risk of clotting disorders, especially in individuals with unexplained thrombotic events or recurrent pregnancy loss.', NULL, '<p>Anti-phospholipid antibodies (IgM) are immunoglobulin M (IgM) antibodies that target phospholipids, critical components of cell membranes involved in blood clotting. The presence of these antibodies can disrupt normal clotting processes, leading to an increased risk of developing blood clots. Elevated levels of anti-phospholipid IgM antibodies are associated with antiphospholipid syndrome (APS), an autoimmune disorder characterized by recurrent blood clots, pregnancy complications (such as recurrent miscarriages or stillbirths), and other vascular issues. The anti-phospholipid IgM test is used to diagnose APS and assess the risk of clotting disorders, especially in individuals with unexplained thrombotic events, recurrent pregnancy loss, or a history of autoimmune diseases. This test helps in identifying the underlying cause of these conditions and guiding appropriate treatment to prevent further complications. Monitoring these antibodies is crucial for managing and mitigating the risks associated with APS.</p>', '<p>-  (IgM)  M (IgM)        ,                              ,           - IgM       (APS)    ,          ,    (     ),        - IgM    APS               ,           ,   ,                                       APS           </p>', '2024-07-30 15:47:32', '2024-07-30 15:47:32', NULL, NULL),
(252, NULL, 'Total Protein- Protein', 'EXP0252', '350', '145', 'Same Day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'A protein measurement typically assesses the total amount of protein in the blood or a specific type of protein within the blood. This can provide insights into overall health and various bodily functions. \r\n\r\n1. **Total Protein**: This measures the combined levels of all proteins in the blood, including albumin and globulins. It helps evaluate liver and kidney function, nutritional status, and the presence of conditions such as liver disease, kidney disease, and malnutrition.\r\n\r\n2. **Specific Proteins**: Tests can measure specific proteins like albumin, which maintains blood volume and pressure, or specific antibodies or enzymes to diagnose particular conditions.\r\n\r\n3. **Protein Electrophoresis**: This technique separates proteins based on their size and charge to detect abnormalities in protein levels or types, which can help diagnose conditions like multiple myeloma or other immune disorders.', NULL, '<p>Proteins are essential biomolecules composed of long chains of amino acids linked by peptide bonds. They perform a vast array of functions in the body, including catalyzing biochemical reactions (enzymes), providing structural support (collagen and keratin), transporting molecules (hemoglobin), and regulating bodily processes (hormones and antibodies). Proteins are critical for growth, repair, and maintenance of tissues. They are involved in almost every cellular function and play a role in immune response, muscle contraction, and cellular signaling. Proteins are synthesized based on genetic instructions and can be found in all living organisms. In clinical settings, measuring protein levels in the blood can provide insights into nutritional status, liver and kidney function, and the presence of various diseases or conditions. Abnormal protein levels or types can indicate a range of health issues, including metabolic disorders, infections, or malignancies.</p>', '<p>           ,                 ,       (),     (  ),     (),       (  )  , ,                    ,   ,                             ,          ,     ,                             ,   , ,    </p>', '2024-07-30 16:00:26', '2024-07-30 16:00:26', NULL, NULL),
(253, NULL, 'Anti Phospholipid Antibody /  APL - IgG', 'EXP0253', '1480', '590', 'Next Day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Anti-phospholipid antibodies (IgG) measure the presence of immunoglobulin G (IgG) antibodies that target phospholipids, which are crucial components of cell membranes involved in blood clotting. Elevated levels of anti-phospholipid IgG antibodies are associated with antiphospholipid syndrome (APS), an autoimmune disorder that increases the risk of abnormal blood clotting, pregnancy complications (such as recurrent miscarriages or stillbirths), and other vascular issues. The presence of these antibodies can disrupt normal blood clotting processes. The test helps diagnose APS, assess the risk of clotting disorders, and guide treatment, especially in individuals with unexplained thrombotic events or recurrent pregnancy loss.', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2024-07-30 16:03:42', '2024-07-30 16:04:14', NULL, NULL),
(254, NULL, 'Aspartate Aminotransferase - SGOT-AST', 'EXP0254', '350', '145', 'Same Day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'SGOT, or serum glutamate-oxaloacetate transaminase (also known as aspartate aminotransferase or AST), measures the level of this enzyme in the blood. SGOT is found in various tissues, including the liver, heart, muscles, and kidneys. Elevated levels of SGOT in the blood can indicate damage to these tissues, particularly the liver. High SGOT levels are commonly associated with liver conditions such as hepatitis, cirrhosis, or liver damage from drugs or alcohol. It can also indicate heart conditions like myocardial infarction or muscle disorders. Measuring SGOT levels helps diagnose and monitor these conditions and assess overall organ health.', NULL, '<p>SGOT, or serum glutamate-oxaloacetate transaminase (also known as aspartate aminotransferase or AST), is an enzyme found primarily in the liver, heart, muscle, and kidneys. It plays a crucial role in amino acid metabolism by facilitating the transfer of amino groups between molecules. Elevated levels of SGOT in the blood can indicate tissue damage or disease, as the enzyme is released into the bloodstream when cells are damaged. High SGOT levels are commonly associated with liver conditions such as hepatitis, cirrhosis, and liver damage from toxins or alcohol. Elevated SGOT can also be seen in heart conditions, including myocardial infarction (heart attack), and in muscle disorders. Conversely, low levels of SGOT are usually less concerning but may indicate other health issues. Measuring SGOT levels helps in diagnosing and monitoring liver and heart diseases, assessing the extent of tissue damage, and guiding appropriate treatment.</p>', '<p>SGOT,   -  (    AST       ),        , , ,                ,               SGOT             ,               SGOT        , ,              SGOT   ,    ()            , SGOT    :                SGOT           ,       ,        </p>', '2024-07-30 16:08:55', '2024-07-30 16:08:55', NULL, NULL),
(255, NULL, 'Potassium', 'EXP0255', '360', '240', 'Same Day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'A potassium measurement determines the level of potassium, an essential electrolyte, in the blood. Potassium is crucial for maintaining proper cell function, including regulating fluid balance, nerve signal transmission, and muscle contractions. It also plays a key role in maintaining heart rhythm. Abnormal potassium levels can indicate various health issues. High potassium levels (hyperkalemia) may be due to kidney dysfunction, dehydration, or certain medications. Low potassium levels (hypokalemia) can result from conditions such as prolonged vomiting, diarrhea, or excessive use of diuretics. Measuring potassium levels helps in diagnosing and managing these conditions and ensuring overall electrolyte balance and proper functioning of the heart and muscles.', NULL, '<p>Potassium is a vital electrolyte and mineral that plays a key role in maintaining various physiological functions in the body. It is essential for regulating fluid balance, nerve signal transmission, and muscle contraction, including the contraction of the heart muscle. Potassium helps maintain normal blood pressure and is involved in acid-base balance within cells. It operates by creating electrical gradients across cell membranes, which are crucial for nerve and muscle function. The body primarily obtains potassium from dietary sources such as fruits, vegetables, and legumes. Proper potassium levels are necessary for maintaining overall health, as imbalances can lead to serious health issues. High potassium levels (hyperkalemia) may result from kidney dysfunction, dehydration, or certain medications, while low levels (hypokalemia) can be caused by conditions such as prolonged vomiting, diarrhea, or excessive use of diuretics. Monitoring potassium levels is crucial for diagnosing and managing related health conditions.</p>', '<p>                       ,   ,    ,         ,                     -                  ,               , ,                 ,              ()   , ,        ,    ()    , ,                        </p>', '2024-07-30 16:10:57', '2024-07-30 16:10:57', NULL, NULL),
(256, NULL, 'Anti dsDNA - Anti Double Standard DNA Elisa', 'EXP0256', '1400', '830', 'Next Day', 'Overnight fasting for 9-12 hours', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Anti-dsDNA (anti-double-stranded DNA) antibodies measure the presence of antibodies directed against double-stranded DNA, a key component of the cell nucleus. Elevated levels of these antibodies are commonly associated with systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE), an autoimmune disease where the immune system mistakenly attacks the body\'s own tissues. Anti-dsDNA antibodies are often used to help diagnose SLE, monitor disease activity, and evaluate the effectiveness of treatment. While elevated anti-dsDNA levels are highly indicative of SLE, they can also be found in other autoimmune disorders, though less commonly. The test is particularly useful for assessing the severity of kidney involvement in lupus, as these antibodies often correlate with renal disease in SLE.', NULL, '<p>Anti-dsDNA (anti-double-stranded DNA) antibodies are autoantibodies that target double-stranded DNA, a major component of the cell\'s genetic material. The presence of these antibodies is most commonly associated with systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE), an autoimmune disease where the immune system erroneously attacks the bodys own tissues. Elevated levels of anti-dsDNA antibodies are indicative of active disease and are often used to help diagnose SLE and assess disease activity, particularly in monitoring kidney involvement, as these antibodies frequently correlate with lupus nephritis. The test for anti-dsDNA antibodies is valuable for evaluating the severity of SLE and guiding treatment decisions. Although high levels of these antibodies are strongly associated with SLE, they can also be found in other autoimmune disorders, but this is less common. Overall, the presence and levels of anti-dsDNA antibodies provide crucial insights into autoimmune disease management and monitoring.</p>', NULL, '2024-07-30 17:01:37', '2024-07-30 17:01:37', NULL, NULL),
(257, NULL, 'Thyphi Dot IgG Rapid- Thyphoid', 'EXP0257', '490', '295', 'Same Day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'The Typhi Dot IgG test measures the presence of IgG antibodies specific to *Salmonella typhi*, the bacterium responsible for typhoid fever. Elevated levels of IgG antibodies indicate a past infection or long-term exposure to *S. typhi*. This test is used to diagnose typhoid fever, particularly when there is a need to determine if a person has had a previous infection or to confirm a chronic carrier state. The presence of IgG antibodies suggests that the immune system has been exposed to *S. typhi* at some point, either through a past infection or possibly through vaccination.', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2024-07-30 17:17:33', '2024-07-30 17:21:05', NULL, NULL),
(258, NULL, 'Thypi Dot IgM Rapid-Thyphoid', 'EXP0258', '490', '295', 'Same Day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'The Typhi Dot IgM test measures the presence of IgM antibodies specific to *Salmonella typhi*, the bacterium that causes typhoid fever. Elevated IgM levels typically indicate a recent or acute infection with *S. typhi*. This test helps diagnose typhoid fever, especially in the early stages of the disease, as IgM antibodies appear shortly after infection and are a marker of the body\'s initial response to the pathogen. The presence of IgM antibodies suggests that the infection is recent or ongoing.', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2024-07-30 17:20:18', '2024-07-30 17:20:18', NULL, NULL),
(259, NULL, 'Bilirubin Total', 'EXP0259', '300', '150', 'Same Day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'The total bilirubin test measures the overall level of bilirubin in the blood. Bilirubin is a yellowish substance produced during the breakdown of red blood cells. It is processed by the liver, where it is converted into a form that can be excreted in bile. The test measures both direct (conjugated) and indirect (unconjugated) bilirubin.\r\n\r\n- **Direct (conjugated) bilirubin** is water-soluble and is excreted in bile. Elevated levels can indicate liver dysfunction or bile duct obstruction.\r\n- **Indirect (unconjugated) bilirubin** is not water-soluble and is transported to the liver for processing. High levels may suggest hemolysis (rapid breakdown of red blood cells) or issues with bilirubin processing in the liver.\r\n\r\nMeasuring total bilirubin helps diagnose and monitor conditions like jaundice, liver diseases, and certain blood disorders.', NULL, '<p>Total bilirubin is a blood test that measures the combined levels of direct (conjugated) and indirect (unconjugated) bilirubin in the bloodstream. Bilirubin is a yellow pigment produced from the breakdown of hemoglobin in red blood cells. Direct bilirubin is processed by the liver and excreted in bile, making it water-soluble. Indirect bilirubin is not water-soluble and is transported to the liver for conversion into direct bilirubin. Elevated total bilirubin levels can indicate liver dysfunction, such as hepatitis or cirrhosis, bile duct obstruction, or excessive red blood cell breakdown (hemolysis). Increased direct bilirubin often points to liver or bile duct issues, while high indirect bilirubin levels can suggest problems with red blood cell breakdown or liver processing. The total bilirubin test is crucial for diagnosing and monitoring conditions that affect liver function, bile production, and overall metabolic health.</p>', '<p>          ()   ()                                         ,                               ,    ,    ,        ()         :          ,                          ,  ,               </p>', '2024-07-30 17:27:52', '2024-07-30 17:27:52', NULL, NULL),
(260, NULL, 'TIBC Total - Iron Binding Capay', 'EXP0260', '400', '210', 'Same Day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Total Iron-Binding Capacity (TIBC) measures the blood\'s ability to bind and transport iron. It assesses how much iron can be carried by transferrin, a protein that binds iron in the bloodstream. TIBC is useful for diagnosing and managing iron-related conditions:\r\n\r\n- **High TIBC levels** can indicate iron deficiency anemia, where there\'s a shortage of iron available for binding.\r\n- **Low TIBC levels** can suggest iron overload conditions such as hemochromatosis or anemia of chronic disease, where the body has more iron than normal or the iron-binding capacity is reduced due to chronic illness.\r\n\r\nThe TIBC test helps evaluate overall iron metabolism and is often used alongside other tests, such as serum iron and ferritin, to provide a comprehensive view of iron status and related health conditions.', NULL, '<p>Total Iron-Binding Capacity (TIBC) is a blood test that measures the maximum amount of iron that can be bound by proteins in the bloodstream, primarily transferrin. Transferrin is the main protein responsible for transporting iron throughout the body. The TIBC test is used to assess iron metabolism and diagnose iron-related disorders. Elevated TIBC levels are often associated with iron deficiency anemia, as the body increases transferrin production to maximize iron transport when iron stores are low. Conversely, low TIBC levels can indicate conditions such as iron overload (hemochromatosis), chronic disease anemia, or malnutrition, where transferrin production is reduced or iron binding capacity is altered. The TIBC test is typically used in conjunction with other iron tests, such as serum iron and ferritin, to evaluate the overall status of iron in the body and to aid in the diagnosis and management of anemia and other iron-related conditions.</p>', '<p> -  (TIBC)                    ,                 TIBC                       TIBC           ,                     ,  TIBC     (ochromatosis),    ,         ,               TIBC      ,           ,                            </p>', '2024-07-30 17:31:58', '2024-07-30 17:31:58', NULL, NULL);
