(261, NULL, 'Thyroglobulin -TG', 'EXP0261', '960', '495', 'Same Day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Thyroglobulin (TG) is a protein produced by the thyroid gland and is a key component in the production of thyroid hormones. The Thyroglobulin (TG) test measures the level of this protein in the blood. \r\n\r\n- **Elevated levels of TG** can indicate thyroid gland abnormalities, such as thyroid cancer, especially in patients who have had thyroid cancer treatment or surgery. It can be used to monitor disease recurrence or progression.\r\n- **Low or normal levels of TG** are generally considered normal and can be used to assess the effectiveness of thyroid cancer treatment or surgery.\r\n\r\nThe TG test is particularly useful for tracking changes in patients with a history of thyroid cancer or certain thyroid disorders, helping to evaluate treatment response and disease status.', NULL, '<p>Thyroglobulin (TG) is a protein synthesized and secreted by the thyroid gland, essential for the production and storage of thyroid hormones (thyroxine and triiodothyronine). It serves as a precursor for these hormones, which are critical for regulating metabolism, growth, and development. The Thyroglobulin test measures the level of this protein in the blood and is often used in the management of thyroid conditions. Elevated TG levels can indicate thyroid disorders such as thyroid cancer, particularly in patients who have had thyroid cancer treatment or surgery, as it helps monitor for recurrence or progression of the disease. In patients without thyroid disease, normal TG levels are expected. The test is particularly useful in tracking changes in thyroid cancer patients post-treatment and assessing the effectiveness of ongoing therapy. Regular monitoring helps guide treatment decisions and evaluate the overall status of thyroid health.</p>', '<p> (TG)                 (  )                   ,  ,                                TG   ,    ,     ,               ,                     TG                        ongoing                              </p>', '2024-07-30 17:36:44', '2024-07-30 17:36:44', NULL, NULL),
(262, NULL, 'Human Growth Harmone -HGH', 'EXP0262', '1290', '660', 'Next Day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'A human growth hormone (HGH) test measures the concentration of growth hormone in the blood. Produced by the pituitary gland, HGH is vital for growth, cell repair, and metabolism. Elevated levels can indicate conditions like acromegaly or gigantism, while low levels may point to growth hormone deficiency. This test helps diagnose and manage growth disorders and monitor the effectiveness of related treatments.', NULL, '<p>The Human Growth Hormone (HGH) test measures the level of growth hormone in the blood, produced by the pituitary gland. HGH is essential for growth, metabolism, and cell repair. This test is used to diagnose conditions related to abnormal HGH levels, including growth hormone deficiency and excess. In children, low HGH levels can lead to growth delays and short stature, while high levels may cause gigantism. In adults, a deficiency can result in fatigue, decreased muscle mass, and increased body fat, while excess HGH can lead to acromegaly, characterized by enlarged bones and tissues. The HGH test typically involves blood sampling, and results are often evaluated alongside other tests, such as insulin-like growth factor 1 (IGF-1) levels, to provide a comprehensive view of growth hormone function. This test helps guide treatment decisions and monitor the effectiveness of therapy for related conditions.</p>', '<p>   (HGH)          ,         HGH ,           HGH    ,        ,           ,  HGH           ,      (gigantism)     ,   ,   ,         ,   HGH   (acromegaly)   ,         HGH        ,       ,   -   1 (IGF-1)      ,                               </p>', '2024-07-30 17:44:34', '2024-07-30 17:44:34', NULL, NULL),
(263, NULL, 'HDL Cholesterol -', 'EXP0263', '390', '180', 'Same Day', 'Overnight fasting for 9-12 hours', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'High-Density Lipoprotein (HDL) cholesterol measures the level of HDL in the blood. HDL is often referred to as \"good\" cholesterol because it helps remove excess cholesterol from the bloodstream and transports it to the liver for excretion. Higher HDL levels are associated with a lower risk of cardiovascular disease, as it aids in preventing the buildup of plaque in the arteries. Monitoring HDL cholesterol levels helps assess cardiovascular health and guide prevention strategies.', NULL, '<p>High-Density Lipoprotein (HDL) cholesterol is a type of cholesterol carried in the blood by HDL particles, often referred to as \"good\" cholesterol. HDL helps to remove excess cholesterol from the bloodstream and transport it to the liver for excretion. This process reduces the risk of cholesterol buildup in the arteries, which can lead to cardiovascular diseases like heart attack and stroke. Higher HDL levels are associated with a lower risk of heart disease, as HDL plays a protective role in maintaining vascular health. HDL cholesterol levels are typically measured through a blood test, and maintaining healthy levels through diet, exercise, and lifestyle changes is crucial for overall cardiovascular health.</p>', '<p>-  (HDL)          HDL      ,   \"\"     HDL                              ,               HDL           ,  HDL              HDL            ,  , ,                  </p>', '2024-07-30 17:48:10', '2024-07-30 17:48:10', NULL, NULL),
(264, NULL, 'Asca IgA &IgG', 'EXP0264', '4000', '2500', 'Within 3 Days', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'ASCA (Anti-Saccharomyces cerevisiae antibodies) IgG and IgA tests measure the levels of antibodies against Saccharomyces cerevisiae, a yeast used in baking and brewing. Elevated ASCA IgG and IgA levels are often associated with Crohn\'s disease, an inflammatory bowel condition. ASCA IgG and IgA tests help in diagnosing Crohn\'s disease and differentiating it from other inflammatory bowel diseases like ulcerative colitis. These tests are used alongside other diagnostic methods to assess and manage gastrointestinal conditions.', NULL, '<p>ASCA (Anti-Saccharomyces cerevisiae antibodies) IgG and IgA are specific antibodies produced by the immune system against Saccharomyces cerevisiae, a type of yeast commonly used in baking and brewing. The ASCA IgG and IgA tests measure the levels of these antibodies in the blood. Elevated levels of ASCA IgG and/or IgA are often associated with Crohn\'s disease, an inflammatory bowel disease that affects the digestive tract. ASCA testing helps in differentiating Crohn\'s disease from other inflammatory bowel conditions, such as ulcerative colitis, which typically does not show elevated ASCA levels. The presence of ASCA antibodies can aid in diagnosing Crohn\'s disease, particularly in the context of other clinical findings and diagnostic tests. However, ASCA is not exclusive to Crohn\'s disease and can be found in some healthy individuals and other conditions. Therefore, it is used in conjunction with other diagnostic methods for a comprehensive assessment.</p>', '<p>ASCA (-  ) IgG  IgA         ,             ,       ASCA IgG  IgA              ASCA IgG / IgA         ,               ASCA          ,    ,       ,    ASCA       ASCA              ,            , ASCA                      ,               </p>', '2024-07-30 17:51:48', '2024-07-30 17:51:48', NULL, NULL),
(265, NULL, 'GGT- Gamma Glutamyl Transferase', 'EXP0265', '490', '230', 'Same Day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Gamma-glutamyl transferase (GGT) measures the level of the GGT enzyme in the blood. GGT is involved in the metabolism of glutathione, a key antioxidant, and is primarily found in the liver. Elevated GGT levels can indicate liver dysfunction, bile duct obstruction, or excessive alcohol consumption. It is often used to assess liver health and diagnose conditions like hepatitis, cirrhosis, and liver damage. The test can also help evaluate the effectiveness of treatment for liver-related issues.', NULL, '<p>Gamma-glutamyl transferase (GGT) is an enzyme found predominantly in the liver, as well as in the kidneys, pancreas, and spleen. It plays a crucial role in the metabolism of glutathione, a powerful antioxidant that helps protect cells from oxidative stress. GGT facilitates the transfer of amino acids and peptides across cellular membranes, which is essential for various metabolic processes.</p><p>A GGT blood test measures the level of this enzyme in the blood. Elevated GGT levels can indicate liver-related issues, such as liver disease, hepatitis, or cirrhosis, and may also reflect bile duct obstruction or alcohol-related liver damage. High GGT levels can be associated with excessive alcohol consumption, certain medications, and metabolic conditions. The GGT test is often used to evaluate liver function, diagnose liver disorders, and monitor the effectiveness of treatment. It is typically ordered alongside other liver function tests for a comprehensive assessment of liver health.</p>', '<p>-  (GGT)          ,   , ,             ,              GGT              ,        </p><p>GGT             GGT          ,    , ,  ,                    GGT    ,  ,         GGT        ,      ,                                   </p>', '2024-07-30 17:54:44', '2024-07-30 17:54:44', NULL, NULL),
(266, NULL, 'SHBG- Sex Hormone Binding Globulin', 'EXP0266', '3900', '1590', 'Next Day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Sex Hormone-Binding Globulin (SHBG) measures the level of a protein in the blood that binds to sex hormones, including testosterone and estrogen. SHBG regulates the availability and activity of these hormones by binding them in a way that makes them less active. Elevated or decreased SHBG levels can indicate hormonal imbalances or underlying conditions such as liver disease, polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS), or thyroid disorders. The SHBG test is used to assess and diagnose these hormonal issues.', NULL, '<p>Sex Hormone-Binding Globulin (SHBG) is a protein produced by the liver that binds to sex hormones, primarily testosterone and estrogen, in the blood. By binding to these hormones, SHBG regulates their availability and activity. When hormones are bound to SHBG, they are rendered inactive and less available to tissues. SHBG plays a crucial role in maintaining hormonal balance and is involved in regulating reproductive and sexual function.</p><p>Abnormal SHBG levels can indicate various health conditions. Elevated SHBG levels can be associated with liver disease, hyperthyroidism, or conditions such as anorexia. Low SHBG levels may suggest conditions like polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS), hypothyroidism, or metabolic syndrome. The SHBG test is used to evaluate hormonal imbalances, assist in diagnosing endocrine disorders, and monitor treatment effects. It is often performed alongside other hormone tests to provide a comprehensive understanding of an individuals hormonal health.</p>', '<p> -  (SHBG)                              , SHBG           SHBG    ,               SHBG                    </p><p> SHBG           SHBG    , ,           SHBG     (PCOS), ,           SHBG      ,     ,                                   </p>', '2024-07-30 17:58:21', '2024-07-30 17:58:21', NULL, NULL),
(267, NULL, 'Hepatitis B core - IgM Antibodies- Anti HBc', 'EXP0267', '1500', '760', 'Same Day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Hepatitis B core antibodies (anti-HBc IgM) measure the presence of IgM antibodies against the core antigen of the hepatitis B virus (HBV) in the blood. These antibodies are typically produced during the acute phase of a hepatitis B infection. A positive anti-HBc IgM result often indicates a recent or acute hepatitis B infection. It can also help distinguish between acute hepatitis B and chronic infection, as well as identify individuals in the early stages of infection. This test is used to diagnose and monitor hepatitis B infection.', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2024-07-30 18:03:50', '2024-07-30 18:03:50', NULL, NULL),
(268, NULL, 'Immunoglobulin-IgG', 'EXP0268', '800', '480', 'Next Day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Immunoglobulin IgG measures the level of IgG antibodies in the blood. IgG is the most abundant type of antibody and plays a crucial role in the immune response by identifying and neutralizing pathogens like bacteria and viruses. Elevated IgG levels can indicate a past or chronic infection, while low levels may suggest an immune deficiency or inadequate immune response. The IgG test is often used to diagnose infections, monitor immune system health, and evaluate vaccine responses.', NULL, '<p>Immunoglobulin IgG is a type of antibody found in the blood and extracellular fluid, making up about 75% of the total immunoglobulins in the body. It plays a critical role in the immune response by identifying and neutralizing pathogens such as bacteria, viruses, and toxins. IgG antibodies are produced by B cells and are crucial for long-term protection against infections, as they provide immunity by recognizing and remembering previously encountered pathogens. Elevated IgG levels can indicate chronic or past infections, while low levels may suggest an immune deficiency or compromised immune system. The IgG test is used to diagnose and monitor various conditions, including infections, autoimmune diseases, and to assess vaccine effectiveness. It helps in understanding the bodys immune status and guiding appropriate treatment or preventive measures.</p>', '<p> IgG              ,        75%           ,   , ,         IgG  B              ,    Encounter              IgG          ,               IgG   ,  ,  ,                                </p>', '2024-07-30 18:07:13', '2024-07-30 18:07:13', NULL, NULL),
(269, NULL, 'Immunoglobulin IgA', 'EXP0269', '800', '480', 'Next Day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'The Immunoglobulin IgA test measures the level of IgA antibodies in the blood or other bodily fluids. IgA is a type of antibody primarily found in mucosal areas, such as the respiratory and gastrointestinal tracts, as well as in secretions like saliva, tears, and breast milk. This test helps evaluate immune function by assessing the body\'s ability to produce IgA, which plays a crucial role in defending against infections at mucosal surfaces. Abnormal IgA levels can indicate conditions such as immune deficiencies, chronic infections, or autoimmune disorders.', NULL, '<p>Immunoglobulin IgA is a type of antibody primarily found in mucosal areas of the body, including the respiratory and gastrointestinal tracts, as well as in secretions such as saliva, tears, and breast milk. It constitutes about 15% of the total immunoglobulins in the blood and is the main antibody present in mucosal secretions. IgA plays a crucial role in mucosal immunity by preventing pathogens from adhering to and penetrating epithelial surfaces. It helps neutralize and eliminate bacteria, viruses, and toxins that enter through mucosal surfaces, thus providing an essential line of defense against infections. The IgA test measures the level of this antibody in the blood or other bodily fluids and is used to diagnose and monitor conditions like immunodeficiencies, chronic infections, and autoimmune disorders. Abnormal IgA levels can indicate various health issues, including immune system disorders or inflammatory conditions.</p>', '<p> IgA                 ,      ,       , ,                 15%           IgA       ,                , ,            ,             IgA                ,  ,                  IgA         ,          </p>', '2024-07-30 18:10:13', '2024-07-30 18:10:13', NULL, NULL),
(270, NULL, 'Immunoglobulin panel', 'EXP0270', '2800', '1290', 'Next Day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Immunoglobulins, also known as antibodies, are proteins produced by the immune system to identify and neutralize pathogens. There are several types, each with specific roles:\r\n\r\n1. **IgA (Immunoglobulin A)**: Found mainly in mucosal areas such as the respiratory and gastrointestinal tracts, and in secretions like saliva and tears. IgA helps protect mucosal surfaces by preventing pathogens from adhering and penetrating epithelial cells.\r\n\r\n2. **IgG (Immunoglobulin G)**: The most abundant antibody in the blood, constituting about 75% of total immunoglobulins. IgG provides long-term protection by recognizing and neutralizing pathogens and toxins, and it plays a crucial role in fighting bacterial and viral infections.\r\n\r\n3. **IgM (Immunoglobulin M)**: The first antibody produced in response to an infection. It is mainly found in the blood and lymphatic fluid and is effective in forming complexes with pathogens, initiating their removal.\r\n\r\nThese antibodies are critical for a well-functioning immune system and are measured to diagnose and monitor various immune-related conditions.', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2024-07-30 18:13:21', '2024-07-30 18:13:21', NULL, NULL),
(271, NULL, 'Dengue IgG & IgM', 'EXP0271', '1500', '640', 'Same day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Dengue IgG and IgM tests are blood tests used to diagnose and monitor dengue fever, a viral illness transmitted by mosquitoes. \r\n\r\n**Dengue IgM** antibodies are produced early in the course of dengue infection, typically detectable within 4-5 days after the onset of symptoms. Their presence indicates a recent or acute dengue infection.\r\n\r\n**Dengue IgG** antibodies are produced later, usually within 7-10 days after the onset of symptoms and can remain detectable for months or even years. The presence of IgG antibodies indicates either a past infection or a more recent infection if paired with IgM antibodies.\r\n\r\nThe IgM and IgG tests help determine the timing of infection, distinguish between primary and secondary dengue infections, and assess the stage of the disease. These tests are crucial for diagnosing dengue fever, particularly in areas where the disease is endemic, and for differentiating dengue from other febrile illnesses.', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2024-07-30 18:15:11', '2024-07-30 18:15:11', NULL, NULL),
(272, NULL, 'Carbamazepine Tegretol,Mazetol', 'EXP0272', '1120', '690', 'Within 3 Days', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, 'Recommended specimen :- Jist before the next dose is due at steady state', NULL, NULL, 'Carbamazepine, also known by brand names such as Tegretol and Mazetol, is a medication primarily used to treat epilepsy, bipolar disorder, and certain types of nerve pain. The test for carbamazepine measures the level of this drug in the blood to ensure it is within a therapeutic range and to avoid toxicity. \r\n\r\nMaintaining appropriate levels is important for effectiveness and safety, as too little may not control symptoms, while too much can cause adverse effects like dizziness, nausea, or severe reactions. Regular monitoring of carbamazepine levels helps in adjusting dosages and managing potential side effects, ensuring optimal treatment outcomes for conditions being treated with this medication.', NULL, '<p>Carbamazepine, available under brand names such as Tegretol and Mazetol, is an anticonvulsant and mood-stabilizing medication used to treat various neurological and psychiatric conditions. It is primarily prescribed for managing epilepsy, including partial and generalized seizures, and for controlling bipolar disorder, particularly manic and mixed episodes. Carbamazepine is also used to alleviate certain types of neuropathic pain, such as trigeminal neuralgia.</p><p>The medication works by stabilizing electrical activity in the brain, thereby reducing the frequency and severity of seizures and mood swings. It achieves this by affecting neurotransmitter activity and ion channels in nerve cells. Regular monitoring of carbamazepine levels in the blood is crucial to ensure therapeutic efficacy and to avoid potential side effects, such as dizziness, drowsiness, or more severe reactions. Carbamazepine can interact with other medications and has potential side effects, so careful dosage adjustments and monitoring are essential for optimal treatment outcomes.</p>', NULL, '2024-07-30 18:20:17', '2024-07-30 18:20:17', NULL, NULL),
(273, NULL, 'Chikungunya IgM-ELISA', 'EXP0273', '690', '495', 'Next Day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Chikungunya IgM is an antibody test used to diagnose chikungunya virus infection, a mosquito-borne virus that causes chikungunya fever. This test detects the presence of immunoglobulin M (IgM) antibodies, which are produced by the immune system in response to a recent infection with the chikungunya virus. IgM antibodies generally appear in the blood within a few days to weeks after the onset of symptoms, such as fever, joint pain, rash, and headache. The presence of IgM antibodies indicates a recent or acute chikungunya infection. This test is valuable for diagnosing chikungunya fever, particularly in the early stages of the disease when other diagnostic methods might be less effective. It helps differentiate chikungunya from other febrile illnesses and is crucial for guiding treatment and managing outbreaks. Accurate interpretation of IgM test results, along with clinical symptoms and history, aids in confirming the diagnosis of chikungunya virus infection.', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2024-07-30 18:23:53', '2024-07-30 18:23:53', NULL, NULL),
(274, NULL, 'Serum Copper', 'EXP0274', '2400', '1180', 'Next Day', 'Fasting is not Manda', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'A copper test measures the amount of copper in the blood, which is essential for various bodily functions. Copper is involved in forming red blood cells, maintaining nerve cells, and supporting the immune system. Abnormal copper levels can indicate health issues: high levels may suggest Wilson\'s disease or liver problems, while low levels can point to deficiencies or disorders like Menkes disease. This test helps diagnose and monitor conditions related to copper metabolism and balance.', NULL, '<p>Copper is an essential trace mineral crucial for several bodily functions. It plays a key role in forming red blood cells, maintaining nerve cells, and supporting the immune system. Copper is involved in the synthesis of collagen, a protein important for connective tissue health, and in the production of energy through its role in various enzymatic processes. It also acts as an antioxidant, helping to protect cells from oxidative damage. The body obtains copper from dietary sources such as shellfish, nuts, seeds, and whole grains. Proper copper levels are vital for maintaining overall health. Abnormal copper levels can lead to health issues: excessive copper accumulation can cause conditions like Wilson\'s disease, while copper deficiency can lead to anemia, weakened immune function, and bone abnormalities. Regular copper testing helps diagnose and manage these conditions, ensuring that copper balance is maintained for optimal health.</p>', '<p>                   ,     ,                   ,        ,                         ,                 , , ,                            :           ,      ,   ,                     ,                 </p>', '2024-07-30 18:29:04', '2024-07-30 18:29:04', NULL, NULL),
(275, NULL, 'Serum Zinc', 'EXP0275', '2500', '1390', 'Next Day', 'Overnight fasting for 9-12 hours', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'A zinc test measures the level of zinc in the blood. Zinc is an essential trace element crucial for numerous bodily functions, including enzyme activity, immune function, protein synthesis, and cell growth. It plays a role in wound healing, DNA synthesis, and maintaining a healthy sense of taste and smell. Abnormal zinc levels can indicate deficiencies or excesses, which may lead to various health issues such as immune dysfunction, growth retardation, or impaired cognitive function.', NULL, '<p>Zinc is an essential trace mineral crucial for a variety of biological functions. It plays a pivotal role in enzyme function, protein synthesis, wound healing, and cell division. Zinc is integral to the functioning of the immune system, supporting immune cell development and activity. It also contributes to DNA synthesis, growth, and development during pregnancy, infancy, and childhood. Additionally, zinc helps maintain skin health, senses of taste and smell, and supports cognitive function. The body obtains zinc through dietary sources such as meat, shellfish, dairy products, nuts, and seeds. Zinc deficiency can lead to symptoms like impaired immune response, stunted growth, hair loss, and delayed wound healing. Conversely, excessive zinc intake can cause nausea, vomiting, and interfere with the absorption of other essential minerals. Regular monitoring of zinc levels is important for diagnosing deficiencies or excesses and managing related health conditions.</p>', '<p>                ,  ,                    ,             , ,  ,              ,    ,                              , ,  ,           ,   ,                  ,                                   </p>', '2024-07-30 18:31:51', '2024-07-30 18:31:51', NULL, NULL),
(276, NULL, 'C- Peptide - Post Prandial /PP', 'EXP0276', '1200', '670', 'Next Day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'A C-peptide postprandial test measures the level of C-peptide in the blood after eating. C-peptide is a byproduct of insulin production, released from the pancreas alongside insulin. This test helps assess the pancreas\'s ability to produce insulin in response to food intake. Elevated C-peptide levels can indicate insulin resistance or excess insulin production, while low levels may suggest insufficient insulin production, such as in type 1 diabetes. It aids in evaluating and managing diabetes and related conditions.', NULL, '<p>C-peptide is a protein fragment produced when proinsulin is split into insulin and C-peptide in the pancreas. It serves as a marker of insulin production since it is released in equal amounts to insulin but does not act on insulin receptors. Measuring C-peptide levels provides insights into the function of the pancreas and the amount of insulin being produced.</p><p>In clinical settings, C-peptide tests are useful for differentiating between type 1 and type 2 diabetes, as type 1 diabetes typically shows low C-peptide levels due to autoimmune destruction of insulin-producing cells, while type 2 diabetes may have normal or elevated levels due to insulin resistance. C-peptide tests also help evaluate insulin production in people receiving insulin therapy and diagnose conditions related to abnormal insulin secretion. Monitoring C-peptide levels assists in managing diabetes and understanding pancreatic health.</p>', '<p>C-peptide               C-peptide                                  C-peptide                    </p><p>  , C-peptide   1   2         ,   1     C-peptide   ,  -        ,   2      C-peptide    ,        C-peptide                             C-peptide                 </p>', '2024-07-30 18:38:32', '2024-07-30 18:38:32', NULL, NULL),
(277, NULL, 'Serum Bicarbonate', 'EXP0277', '900', '490', 'Within 3 Days', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Bicarbonate (HCO) is a key component of the body\'s buffering system that helps maintain the pH balance in the blood. Measuring bicarbonate levels provides insight into the bodys acid-base balance and can help diagnose conditions related to metabolic acidosis or alkalosis. Low bicarbonate levels may indicate conditions like kidney disease or lactic acidosis, while high levels can be associated with metabolic alkalosis or chronic respiratory issues. This test is crucial for assessing overall metabolic health and managing electrolyte imbalances.', NULL, '<p>Bicarbonate (HCO) is a crucial electrolyte in the blood that plays a significant role in maintaining the body\'s acid-base balance. It acts as a buffer, helping to neutralize excess acids and bases to keep the blood\'s pH within a narrow, optimal range. Bicarbonate is produced primarily by the kidneys and participates in several physiological processes, including the regulation of blood pH and the removal of carbon dioxide, a metabolic byproduct.</p><p>Measuring bicarbonate levels helps evaluate the bodys metabolic and respiratory function. Abnormal bicarbonate levels can indicate various health issues: low levels may suggest metabolic acidosis due to conditions like kidney disease, diabetes, or lactic acidosis, while high levels can point to metabolic alkalosis, often related to chronic respiratory conditions or excessive loss of stomach acid. Regular bicarbonate testing is essential for diagnosing and managing disorders affecting acid-base balance and overall metabolic health.</p>', '<p> (HCO)          -                  ,               pH                     pH      ,   ,          </p><p>                            :             ,     , ,          ,          ,                     -                   </p>', '2024-07-30 18:41:40', '2024-07-30 18:41:40', NULL, NULL),
(278, NULL, 'SS-A Antibodies Ro-  Anti , RO Antibody', 'EXP0278', '2090', '1180', 'Within 3 Days', 'Fasting is not Manda', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'SS-A antibodies, also known as anti-Ro antibodies, are autoantibodies that target the SS-A antigen, a protein commonly found in the nucleus of cells. The presence of SS-A antibodies is associated with autoimmune conditions such as Sjgren\'s syndrome and systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE). Measuring SS-A antibodies helps in diagnosing these conditions, particularly in distinguishing them from other autoimmune disorders. Elevated levels can indicate disease activity and are useful in guiding treatment and monitoring disease progression.', NULL, '<p>SS-A antibodies, also known as anti-Ro antibodies, are autoantibodies that target proteins found in the nucleus of cells. These antibodies are commonly associated with autoimmune diseases such as Sjgren\'s syndrome and systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE). In Sjgren\'s syndrome, SS-A antibodies are linked with symptoms like dry mouth and eyes, while in SLE, they can be associated with various systemic symptoms, including skin rashes and joint pain.</p><p>The SS-A antibody test measures the presence of these autoantibodies in the blood, aiding in the diagnosis and management of autoimmune conditions. Elevated SS-A antibody levels are useful for confirming these diagnoses, particularly when clinical symptoms align with autoimmune disease profiles. However, the presence of SS-A antibodies alone is not definitive for diagnosis, as they can also be found in some healthy individuals and other diseases. Therefore, SS-A testing is often used in conjunction with other diagnostic tools for a comprehensive evaluation.</p>', '<p>SS-A ,  -     ,                               (SLE)       , SS-A           ,  SLE                   </p><p>SS-A           ,             SS-A           ,            , SS-A           ,               , SS-A                </p>', '2024-07-30 18:47:00', '2024-07-30 18:47:00', NULL, NULL),
(279, NULL, 'SS-B Antibodies La-Anti La, La Antibody', 'EXP0279', '2090', '1180', 'Within 3 Days', 'Overnight fasting for 9-12 hours', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'SS-B antibodies, also known as anti-La antibodies, measure the presence of autoantibodies against the La protein found in the nucleus of cells. These antibodies are primarily associated with autoimmune conditions like Sjgren\'s syndrome and systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE). Elevated SS-B antibody levels help in diagnosing these diseases and assessing disease activity. While their presence supports the diagnosis, they are not exclusive to these conditions and may be found in some healthy individuals or other disorders.', NULL, '<p>SS-B antibodies, also known as anti-La antibodies, are autoantibodies that target the La protein found in the nucleus of cells. These antibodies are most commonly associated with autoimmune diseases, particularly Sjgren\'s syndrome and systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE). In Sjgren\'s syndrome, the presence of SS-B antibodies is linked to symptoms such as dry eyes and mouth, as well as other systemic manifestations. In SLE, SS-B antibodies can contribute to various symptoms, including joint pain, skin rashes, and organ involvement.</p><p>The detection of SS-B antibodies in the blood is an important diagnostic tool for these autoimmune conditions. Elevated levels of SS-B antibodies help confirm the diagnosis and can also provide insight into the severity and progression of the disease. However, it is important to note that SS-B antibodies are not exclusively found in these diseases; they may also appear in some healthy individuals and other autoimmune disorders. Therefore, the SS-B antibody test is typically used alongside other clinical evaluations and diagnostic tests for a comprehensive assessment.</p>', '<p>- ,  -     ,                         ,          ()       , -           -         , -        ,    ,   ,       </p><p>  -               -                            ,       -         ;               , -                    </p>', '2024-07-30 18:51:03', '2024-07-30 18:51:03', NULL, NULL),
(280, NULL, 'eGFR', 'EXP0280', '400', '295', 'Same Day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Estimated Glomerular Filtration Rate (eGFR) measures how well the kidneys filter waste from the blood. It is calculated using blood creatinine levels, age, gender, and sometimes race. eGFR is a key indicator of kidney function, helping to diagnose and stage chronic kidney disease (CKD). Higher eGFR values indicate better kidney function, while lower values suggest impaired kidney function. Regular eGFR testing is crucial for monitoring kidney health and guiding treatment decisions for patients with kidney disease.', NULL, '<p>Estimated Glomerular Filtration Rate (eGFR) is a crucial measure of kidney function, estimating how effectively the kidneys filter waste and excess fluids from the blood. It is derived from the levels of creatinine in the blood, along with factors such as age, sex, and body size. eGFR is expressed in milliliters per minute per 1.73 meters squared (mL/min/1.73 m) and helps identify and monitor kidney health.</p><p>An eGFR of 90 mL/min/1.73 m or higher is typically considered normal, while lower values indicate varying degrees of kidney dysfunction. eGFR is essential for diagnosing and staging chronic kidney disease (CKD), with stages ranging from mild (stage 1) to kidney failure (stage 5). This measure guides treatment decisions, helps in managing conditions like diabetes and hypertension that affect kidney health, and informs about the potential need for dialysis or kidney transplantation. Regular eGFR testing is vital for early detection and effective management of kidney-related conditions.</p>', NULL, '2024-07-30 18:54:00', '2024-07-30 18:54:00', NULL, NULL),
(281, NULL, 'Urine Protein Creatinine Ratio', 'EXP0281', '680', '395', 'Next Day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'The urine protein-creatinine ratio (UPCR) measures the amount of protein in the urine relative to the amount of creatinine. This test is used to assess kidney function and detect kidney damage. Elevated UPCR levels indicate increased protein in the urine, a sign of kidney disease or damage, which can result from conditions like diabetes, hypertension, or glomerulonephritis. The UPCR provides a convenient and accurate assessment of proteinuria, helping guide diagnosis and treatment decisions for kidney-related conditions.', NULL, '<p>The urine protein-creatinine ratio (UPCR) is a diagnostic test that measures the amount of protein in the urine relative to the amount of creatinine. Creatinine is a waste product of muscle metabolism, excreted at a relatively constant rate, making it a useful reference for assessing protein levels. The UPCR is used to evaluate kidney function and detect proteinuria, which is an abnormal amount of protein in the urine.</p><p>Elevated levels of protein in the urine can indicate kidney damage or disease, often resulting from conditions such as diabetes, hypertension, or glomerulonephritis. The UPCR test is particularly useful because it eliminates the need for a 24-hour urine collection, providing a convenient and accurate assessment from a single urine sample. It helps in diagnosing and monitoring kidney disorders, guiding treatment decisions, and assessing the effectiveness of therapeutic interventions. Regular monitoring of UPCR is essential for early detection and management of kidney-related health issues.</p>', '<p> -  (UPCR)                           ,         ,                UPCR                  ,         </p><p>               ,   ,           UPCR         24          ,                       ,      ,                       UPCR     </p>', '2024-07-30 18:57:32', '2024-07-30 18:57:32', NULL, NULL);
