(328, NULL, 'Fever Package 2', 'EXP0328', '1780', '850', 'Same Day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'A **fever package** including CBC, ESR, MP, Widal (Typhi Dot), and urine tests provides a comprehensive assessment to identify the cause of fever:\r\n\r\n- **CBC (Complete Blood Count):** Assesses overall health, detects infections, anemia, and other blood disorders.\r\n- **ESR (Erythrocyte Sedimentation Rate):** Measures inflammation levels, helping to identify inflammatory or infectious conditions.\r\n- **MP (Malaria Parasite):** Detects the presence of malaria parasites in the blood, indicating malaria infection.\r\n- **Widal Test (Typhi Dot):** Identifies typhoid fever by detecting antibodies against Salmonella typhi and Salmonella paratyphi.\r\n- **Urine Analysis:** Evaluates for urinary tract infections and other abnormalities.\r\n\r\nThis package aids in diagnosing various infectious or inflammatory conditions responsible for fever, guiding appropriate treatment.', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2024-08-01 12:15:05', '2024-08-01 12:15:05', NULL, NULL),
(329, NULL, 'Fever package 3', 'EXP0329', '1900', '999', 'Same Day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'A **fever package** including CBC, urine analysis, ESR, malaria antigen, and Typhi Dot test measures the following:\r\n\r\n- **CBC (Complete Blood Count):** Evaluates overall health and identifies infections, anemia, and blood disorders.\r\n- **Urine Analysis:** Detects urinary tract infections, kidney issues, and other abnormalities.\r\n- **ESR (Erythrocyte Sedimentation Rate):** Indicates inflammation levels in the body, which can be due to infections or chronic diseases.\r\n- **Malaria Antigen Test:** Detects specific antigens produced by malaria parasites in the blood, confirming malaria infection.\r\n- **Typhi Dot Test:** Identifies typhoid fever by detecting antibodies against Salmonella typhi and Salmonella paratyphi.\r\n\r\nThis package helps in diagnosing and managing various infectious and inflammatory conditions that cause fever.', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2024-08-01 12:22:59', '2024-08-01 12:22:59', NULL, NULL),
(330, NULL, 'PP-Post Prandial Blood Sugar', 'EXP0330', '300', '190', 'Same Day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '**Postprandial blood sugar** refers to the measurement of blood glucose levels after eating a meal. This test is typically conducted 1-2 hours after eating to evaluate how well the body processes glucose following food intake. It helps assess insulin function and is crucial for diagnosing and managing diabetes and other glucose metabolism disorders.\r\n\r\n**Key Points:**\r\n\r\n- **Purpose:** To measure the body\'s response to glucose after a meal and evaluate postprandial glucose control.\r\n- **Clinical Relevance:** Helps diagnose diabetes, monitor glucose levels in diabetic patients, and adjust treatment plans.\r\n- **Interpretation:** Elevated postprandial blood sugar levels may indicate insulin resistance or poor glycemic control. \r\n\r\nMaintaining normal postprandial glucose levels is essential for effective diabetes management and overall metabolic health.', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2024-08-01 12:26:44', '2024-08-01 12:26:44', NULL, NULL),
(331, NULL, 'Vitamin A Retinol', 'EXP0331', '6000', '3395', 'Within 7 Days', 'Overnight fasting for 9-12 hours', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '**Vitamin A (Retinol)** levels in the blood measure the concentration of retinol, a form of vitamin A that is crucial for various bodily functions. Retinol is essential for vision, immune function, skin health, and cellular growth.\r\n\r\n**Key Points:**\r\n\r\n- **Function:** Retinol supports vision by maintaining the health of the retina, enhances immune function, promotes skin health, and is involved in cell differentiation.\r\n- **Measurement:** The serum retinol test measures the level of retinol in the blood, providing insight into vitamin A status.\r\n- **Clinical Relevance:** Low levels can indicate vitamin A deficiency, which can lead to vision problems, immune deficiencies, and skin issues. High levels might suggest excess intake or supplementation.\r\n\r\nTesting vitamin A levels helps assess nutritional status and guide dietary or supplemental interventions to maintain optimal health.', NULL, '<p>**Vitamin A (retinol)** is a fat-soluble vitamin essential for several key physiological functions. It exists in two primary forms: preformed vitamin A (retinol) found in animal products and provitamin A carotenoids, such as beta-carotene, found in plant-based foods.</p><p>**Key Points:**</p><p>- **Function:** Retinol plays a crucial role in maintaining healthy vision, particularly in low-light conditions, by contributing to the formation of rhodopsin, a visual pigment. It also supports immune function, promotes cell growth and differentiation, and helps maintain healthy skin and mucous membranes.<br>- **Measurement:** Serum retinol levels are measured to assess vitamin A status and diagnose deficiencies or excess. Low levels indicate a deficiency, which can lead to night blindness, immune system impairment, and skin problems. Excessive levels, often due to high-dose supplements, can cause toxicity and adverse effects.<br>- **Sources:** Rich sources of retinol include liver, dairy products, and fish, while carotenoids are abundant in carrots, sweet potatoes, and leafy greens.</p><p>Monitoring retinol levels ensures adequate vitamin A for overall health and function.</p>', '<p>** A ()**                       : -  A ()         A ,   -,         </p><p>** :**</p><p>- **:**          ,    -   ,                 ,        ,             <br>- **:**      A                       ,   ,    ,           ,          ,        <br>- **:**      ,  ,    ,   , ,          </p><p>     A      ,         </p>', '2024-08-01 12:31:06', '2024-08-01 12:31:06', NULL, NULL),
(332, NULL, 'Phospholipase A2 Receptor Antibody - PLA2R Qualitative', 'EXP0332', '8900', '4800', 'Within 5 Days', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '**PLA2R (Phospholipase A2 Receptor)** is a test that measures antibodies against the PLA2R protein, which is found on the surface of podocytes in the kidneys. These antibodies are associated with **primary membranous nephropathy**, a kidney disorder characterized by the thickening of the membranes in the kidneys filtering units (glomeruli).\r\n\r\n**Key Points:**\r\n\r\n- **Purpose:** The PLA2R test helps in diagnosing primary membranous nephropathy by detecting the presence of anti-PLA2R antibodies in the blood. This condition can cause nephrotic syndrome, which includes symptoms like proteinuria (excess protein in urine), edema (swelling), and hypertension (high blood pressure).\r\n  \r\n- **Clinical Relevance:** Elevated levels of anti-PLA2R antibodies indicate an autoimmune reaction against the kidneys filtration system, contributing to disease progression. The test is used to confirm the diagnosis and monitor disease activity.\r\n\r\n- **Diagnostic Use:** PLA2R testing is typically used alongside kidney biopsy and other laboratory tests to provide a comprehensive evaluation of kidney function and autoimmune activity.\r\n\r\nMeasuring PLA2R helps in the accurate diagnosis and effective management of primary membranous nephropathy.', NULL, '<p>**PLA2R (Phospholipase A2 Receptor)** is a protein present on the surface of podocytes, which are specialized cells in the kidneys\' glomeruli. The PLA2R test measures the presence of antibodies against this receptor, which are linked to **primary membranous nephropathy**. This kidney disorder is characterized by the thickening of the glomerular basement membrane due to an autoimmune response.</p><p>**Key Points:**</p><p>- **Function:** PLA2R is involved in cellular signaling and membrane remodeling. When targeted by autoantibodies, it can lead to immune complex deposition in the kidneys, causing inflammation and damage.</p><p>- **Clinical Relevance:** Elevated anti-PLA2R antibodies are a marker for primary membranous nephropathy and are used to confirm the diagnosis of this condition. The test helps differentiate primary membranous nephropathy from secondary causes of nephrotic syndrome.</p><p>- **Diagnostic Use:** The PLA2R test is used in conjunction with kidney biopsy and other tests to monitor disease activity, guide treatment, and assess prognosis.</p><p>Monitoring PLA2R levels is crucial for diagnosing and managing primary membranous nephropathy effectively.</p>', '<p>**PLA2R (Phospholipase A2 Receptor)**                 PLA2R           ,  **  **                ,        </p><p>** :**</p><p>- **:** PLA2R                ,             ,      </p><p>- ** :**    -PLA2R                                      </p><p>- ** :** PLA2R               ,              </p><p>PLA2R               </p>', '2024-08-01 12:54:16', '2024-08-01 12:54:16', NULL, NULL),
(333, NULL, 'Fertility panel 1', 'EXP0333', '2000', '890', 'Same Day', 'Overnight fasting for 9-12 hours', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '**LH (Luteinizing Hormone), FSH (Follicle-Stimulating Hormone), PRL (Prolactin), and TSH (Thyroid-Stimulating Hormone)** are key hormones measured to assess reproductive and endocrine health.\r\n\r\n- **LH (Luteinizing Hormone):** Produced by the pituitary gland, LH regulates the menstrual cycle and ovulation in women and testosterone production in men. Elevated or decreased levels can indicate issues with reproductive function.\r\n\r\n- **FSH (Follicle-Stimulating Hormone):** Also produced by the pituitary gland, FSH stimulates ovarian follicle development in women and sperm production in men. Abnormal levels can indicate problems with fertility or gonadal function.\r\n\r\n- **PRL (Prolactin):** This hormone, produced by the pituitary gland, stimulates breast milk production. Elevated levels can cause irregular menstrual cycles, infertility, and may indicate pituitary disorders.\r\n\r\n- **TSH (Thyroid-Stimulating Hormone):** Secreted by the pituitary gland, TSH regulates thyroid function. Abnormal TSH levels can indicate thyroid disorders such as hypothyroidism or hyperthyroidism.\r\n\r\nTesting these hormones helps diagnose and manage various reproductive and endocrine disorders.', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2024-08-01 13:33:56', '2024-08-01 13:33:56', NULL, NULL),
(334, NULL, 'ENA/ANA Quantitative Profile-Extractable Nuclear Antigens  / Anti Nuclear Antibodies Quantitative profile', 'EXP0334', '10000', '4990', 'Within 3 Days', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '**ENA (Extractable Nuclear Antigens) and ANA (Antinuclear Antibodies)** are tests used to detect autoantibodies in the blood. ANA tests screen for antibodies against nuclear components, often indicating autoimmune disorders like lupus. ENA tests identify specific autoantibodies related to conditions such as Sjgren\'s syndrome, scleroderma, and polymyositis. High levels of these antibodies suggest an autoimmune response, helping diagnose and differentiate various autoimmune diseases.', NULL, '<p>**ANA (Antinuclear Antibodies)** and **ENA (Extractable Nuclear Antigens)** are blood tests used to detect autoantibodies that target components within the cell nucleus.</p><p>**ANA Test:** This test screens for the presence of antibodies against nuclear antigens, which can indicate autoimmune disorders. Elevated ANA levels are commonly associated with conditions such as systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE), rheumatoid arthritis, and Sjgren\'s syndrome. While a positive ANA test is not specific, it is a key initial screening tool.</p><p>**ENA Test:** This test further identifies specific autoantibodies against extractable nuclear antigens, including antibodies to Ro (SSA), La (SSB), Sm, RNP, Scl-70, and Jo-1. The ENA panel helps diagnose and differentiate between various autoimmune diseases, such as SLE, Sjgren\'s syndrome, and scleroderma, by pinpointing specific autoantibodies.</p><p>Together, ANA and ENA tests provide a comprehensive view of the autoimmune process, aiding in diagnosis and management of autoimmune diseases.</p>', '<p>**ANA (- )**  **ENA (  )**                   </p><p>**ANA :**             ,          ANA       (SLE),              ANA    ,       </p><p>**ENA :**      Ro (SSA), La (SSB), Sm, RNP, Scl-70,  Jo-1         ENA    ,  SLE,    ,         </p><p>ANA  ENA           ,        </p>', '2024-08-01 13:39:40', '2024-08-01 13:39:40', NULL, NULL),
(335, NULL, 'TheXpertlab Thalassemia Profile', 'EXP0335', '2200', '1190', 'Next Day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'A **thalassemia profile** measures various indicators to diagnose and assess thalassemia, a genetic blood disorder affecting hemoglobin production. It typically includes:\r\n\r\n- **Complete Blood Count (CBC):** Assesses red blood cell count, hemoglobin levels, and mean corpuscular volume (MCV), often showing microcytic anemia.\r\n- **Hemoglobin Electrophoresis:** Identifies abnormal hemoglobin types specific to thalassemia.\r\n- **Iron Studies:** Differentiates thalassemia from iron deficiency anemia by measuring serum iron and ferritin levels.\r\n- **Genetic Testing:** Detects mutations in genes responsible for thalassemia, confirming diagnosis and determining the disorders type and severity.', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2024-08-01 13:44:57', '2024-08-01 13:44:57', NULL, NULL),
(336, NULL, 'Phospholipid Syndrome Panel', 'EXP0336', '5200', '2995', 'Same Day', 'Overnight fasting for 9-12 hours', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '**Phospholipid syndrome** measures antibodies against phospholipids, which are fats that interact with proteins in the blood, potentially causing blood clotting issues. Key tests include:\r\n\r\n- **Anticardiolipin Antibodies (aCL):** Measures antibodies against cardiolipin, a type of phospholipid.\r\n- **Lupus Anticoagulant (LA):** Assesses the presence of antibodies that interfere with blood clotting.\r\n- **Anti-2-Glycoprotein I Antibodies (a2GPI):** Detects antibodies against 2-glycoprotein I, another phospholipid-binding protein.\r\n\r\nElevated levels indicate antiphospholipid syndrome, which can lead to increased risk of thrombosis and pregnancy complications.', NULL, '<p>**Phospholipid syndrome**, also known as antiphospholipid syndrome (APS), is an autoimmune disorder characterized by the presence of antibodies against phospholipids or phospholipid-binding proteins. Phospholipids are essential components of cell membranes and play a role in blood coagulation. APS can lead to an increased risk of abnormal blood clotting, which can cause complications such as deep vein thrombosis, pulmonary embolism, stroke, or recurrent miscarriages.</p><p>**Key Points:**</p><p>- **Autoantibodies:** The condition is associated with antibodies such as anticardiolipin antibodies (aCL), lupus anticoagulant (LA), and anti-2-glycoprotein I antibodies (a2GPI).<br>- **Symptoms:** Symptoms may include unexplained blood clots, pregnancy complications (e.g., recurrent miscarriages), or other thrombotic events.<br>- **Diagnosis:** Diagnosis is made based on clinical criteria (e.g., thrombosis, pregnancy losses) and laboratory tests for specific antibodies.<br>- **Management:** Treatment typically involves anticoagulants to prevent clot formation and manage associated risks.</p><p>Understanding and managing phospholipid syndrome is crucial for preventing serious complications and improving patient outcomes.</p>', '<p>** **,    (APS)    ,        -                          APS           ,     ,   , ,  -      </p><p>** :**</p><p>- **:**         (aCL),   (LA),  -2- I  (a2GPI)  <br>- **:**     ,    (, - ),        <br>- **:**    (, , )             <br>- **:**                       </p><p>                     </p>', '2024-08-01 13:48:59', '2024-08-01 13:48:59', NULL, NULL),
(337, NULL, 'Chikungunya Virus-RTPCR Qualitative', 'EXP0337', '2600', '1530', 'Within 3 Days', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '**Chikungunya virus RT-PCR** is a diagnostic test used to detect the presence of chikungunya virus RNA in blood samples. Chikungunya is a viral disease transmitted by mosquitoes, primarily Aedes aegypti and Aedes albopictus. The RT-PCR (Reverse Transcription Polymerase Chain Reaction) test is highly sensitive and specific, making it a reliable method for identifying the virus, especially during the acute phase of infection when viral RNA is present in high concentrations.\r\n\r\n**Key Points:**\r\n\r\n- **Purpose:** This test detects chikungunya virus RNA, confirming an active infection. It is crucial for diagnosing the disease and distinguishing it from other similar infections, such as dengue or Zika virus.\r\n  \r\n- **Procedure:** Blood samples are collected and processed to extract RNA, which is then reverse-transcribed into complementary DNA (cDNA) and amplified to detect the presence of the virus.\r\n\r\n- **Clinical Relevance:** Accurate diagnosis helps in managing the infection, providing appropriate treatment, and implementing control measures to prevent outbreaks.\r\n\r\nChikungunya virus RT-PCR is essential for timely diagnosis and effective management of chikungunya virus infections.', NULL, '<p>**  RT-PCR**            RNA                             RT-PCR (    )       ,             ,         RNA     </p><p>** :**</p><p>- **:**     RNA    ,                    </p><p>- **:**       , RNA   ,  -   DNA (cDNA)                 </p><p>- ** :**      ,                   </p><p>  RT-PCR            </p>', NULL, '2024-08-01 14:01:34', '2024-08-01 14:01:34', NULL, NULL),
(338, NULL, 'Osmolality Serum', 'EXP0338', '1360', '600', 'Within 3 Days', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '**Osmolality** measures the concentration of solute particles in a solution, typically blood, urine, or other body fluids. It indicates the body\'s water balance and solute concentration, providing crucial information about hydration status and kidney function.\r\n\r\n**Key Points:**\r\n\r\n- **Purpose:** Assesses the concentration of dissolved particles (like sodium, glucose, and urea) in fluids.\r\n- **Clinical Relevance:** Helps diagnose conditions such as dehydration, overhydration, hyponatremia, kidney dysfunction, and metabolic disorders.\r\n- **Interpretation:** High osmolality indicates high solute concentration, while low osmolality suggests dilution. \r\n\r\nMonitoring osmolality is vital for understanding fluid and electrolyte balance in the body.', NULL, '<p>**Serum osmolality** is a test that measures the concentration of solutes, such as electrolytes, glucose, and urea, in the serum (the liquid part of the blood). This measurement is crucial for evaluating the body\'s water-electrolyte balance and assessing various health conditions.</p><p>**Key Points:**</p><p>- **Function:** Serum osmolality indicates the osmotic pressure exerted by solutes in the blood. It reflects the bodys hydration status and the kidney\'s ability to concentrate or dilute urine.<br>- **Clinical Relevance:** This test helps diagnose and monitor conditions like dehydration, overhydration, hyponatremia (low sodium levels), hypernatremia (high sodium levels), diabetes insipidus, and certain metabolic disorders.<br>- **Interpretation:** Normal serum osmolality ranges from 275 to 295 mOsm/kg. High serum osmolality may indicate dehydration, hypernatremia, or hyperglycemia, while low serum osmolality may suggest overhydration, hyponatremia, or SIADH (Syndrome of Inappropriate Antidiuretic Hormone Secretion).<br>- **Procedure:** Blood is drawn and analyzed in a laboratory to determine the osmolality, providing essential insights into the patient\'s fluid and electrolyte status.</p><p>Serum osmolality is a valuable diagnostic tool for assessing and managing various medical conditions related to fluid and electrolyte imbalances.</p>', '<p>** **      (   )    ,  ,             -            </p><p>** :**</p><p>- **:**                                 <br>- ** :**   , -,  (  ),  (  ),                 <br>- **:**    275  295 mOsm/kg        , ,       ,     -, ,  SIADH (     )     <br>- **:**                  ,              </p><p>                      </p>', '2024-08-01 18:03:59', '2024-08-01 18:03:59', NULL, NULL),
(339, NULL, 'Osmolality Urine', 'EXP0339', '1300', '600', 'Within 3 Days', 'Overnight fasting for 9-12 hours', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '**Urine osmolality** measures the concentration of solutes, such as electrolytes, urea, and glucose, in the urine. This test helps evaluate the kidney\'s ability to concentrate or dilute urine, providing insights into the body\'s water-electrolyte balance and kidney function.\r\n\r\n**Key Points:**\r\n\r\n- **Function:** Urine osmolality reflects how effectively the kidneys can concentrate or dilute urine. It indicates the amount of water being excreted or conserved by the kidneys.\r\n- **Clinical Relevance:** This test is used to diagnose and monitor conditions like dehydration, overhydration, kidney disorders, diabetes insipidus, and syndrome of inappropriate antidiuretic hormone secretion (SIADH).\r\n- **Interpretation:** High urine osmolality indicates concentrated urine, which may be due to dehydration, high solute intake, or SIADH. Low urine osmolality indicates dilute urine, which can result from overhydration, diabetes insipidus, or certain kidney disorders.\r\n- **Procedure:** A urine sample is collected and analyzed in a laboratory to measure osmolality, typically expressed in milliosmoles per kilogram (mOsm/kg).\r\n\r\nUrine osmolality is a valuable diagnostic tool for assessing kidney function and the bodys fluid and electrolyte status.', NULL, '<p>**Urine osmolality** measures the concentration of solutes such as electrolytes, urea, and glucose in the urine. This test evaluates the kidney\'s ability to concentrate or dilute urine, providing insights into the bodys water-electrolyte balance and renal function.</p><p>**Key Points:**</p><p>- **Function:** Urine osmolality indicates the osmoregulatory capacity of the kidneys, reflecting how well they can adjust urine concentration in response to hydration status and solute load.<br>- **Clinical Relevance:** This test helps diagnose and monitor conditions like dehydration, overhydration, kidney disorders, diabetes insipidus, and syndrome of inappropriate antidiuretic hormone secretion (SIADH). It can also be used to assess the effects of certain medications on kidney function.<br>- **Interpretation:** Normal urine osmolality varies but typically ranges from 300 to 900 mOsm/kg. High urine osmolality indicates concentrated urine, often due to dehydration or SIADH. Low urine osmolality suggests dilute urine, which can be caused by overhydration or diabetes insipidus.<br>- **Procedure:** A urine sample is collected and analyzed in a laboratory to determine its osmolality, which provides essential information for diagnosing and managing various medical conditions.</p><p>Urine osmolality is a crucial diagnostic tool for assessing kidney function and the body\'s fluid and electrolyte balance.</p>', '<p>** **   ,                            ,    -         </p><p>** :**</p><p>- **:**          ,                          <br>- ** :**   ,  ,   ,  ,       (SIADH)                             <br>- **:**           300  900 mOsm/kg            ,     SIADH             ,           <br>- **:**                      ,                </p><p>                    </p>', '2024-08-01 18:07:54', '2024-08-01 18:07:54', NULL, NULL),
(340, NULL, 'D- Dimer Quantitative', 'EXP0340', '1900', '890', 'Same Day', 'Overnight fasting for 9-12 hours', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'The **D-dimer test** measures the level of D-dimer, a protein fragment produced when a blood clot dissolves. Elevated D-dimer levels indicate significant clot formation and breakdown in the body. It is used to help diagnose conditions like deep vein thrombosis (DVT), pulmonary embolism (PE), and disseminated intravascular coagulation (DIC). A negative D-dimer test can help rule out these conditions, while a positive test may require further diagnostic imaging to confirm the presence of a clot.', NULL, '<p>**D-dimer** is a small protein fragment present in the blood after a blood clot dissolves through fibrinolysis. It is a byproduct of the degradation of cross-linked fibrin, which occurs when the body breaks down blood clots.</p><p>**Key Points:**</p><p>- **Function:** The presence of D-dimer indicates active clot formation and subsequent breakdown in the body.<br>- **Clinical Relevance:** Elevated D-dimer levels are associated with conditions involving excessive clotting and fibrinolysis, such as deep vein thrombosis (DVT), pulmonary embolism (PE), disseminated intravascular coagulation (DIC), and some cases of thrombophilia.&nbsp;<br>- **Diagnostic Use:** The D-dimer test is a valuable tool in diagnosing thrombotic disorders. A negative D-dimer test can effectively rule out conditions like DVT and PE in low-risk patients, whereas a positive test suggests the need for further imaging studies to confirm the diagnosis.<br>- **Interpretation:** While high D-dimer levels indicate clotting activity, they are not specific to one condition and can be elevated in inflammation, infection, liver disease, pregnancy, and post-surgical states.</p><p>The D-dimer test is a critical component in assessing clot-related conditions, aiding in timely diagnosis and appropriate treatment.</p>', '<p>**D-dimer**                        -      ,            </p><p>** :**</p><p>- **:** D-dimer               <br>- ** :**  D-dimer             (DVT),   (PE),    (DIC)          <br>- ** :** D-dimer             D-dimer       DVT  PE          ,                   <br>- **:**  D-dimer        ,           , ,  , ,            </p><p>D-dimer             ,           </p>', '2024-08-01 18:11:26', '2024-08-01 18:11:26', NULL, NULL),
(341, NULL, 'Basic Allergy Screening', 'EXP0341', '1900', '750', 'Same Day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '**Allergy Screening Basic**, often including tests like CBC (Complete Blood Count), AEC (Absolute Eosinophil Count), and IgE (Immunoglobulin E), helps evaluate allergic reactions and related conditions.\r\n\r\n- **CBC (Complete Blood Count):** Provides a broad overview of blood cell health, including white blood cells, red blood cells, and platelets. It helps detect general health issues, including potential signs of infection or inflammation that may accompany allergies.\r\n\r\n- **AEC (Absolute Eosinophil Count):** Measures the number of eosinophils, a type of white blood cell involved in allergic responses and asthma. Elevated eosinophil levels can indicate allergic conditions or parasitic infections.\r\n\r\n- **IgE (Immunoglobulin E):** This test measures the level of IgE antibodies in the blood. Elevated IgE levels are commonly associated with allergic reactions, such as asthma, hay fever, and food allergies.\r\n\r\nTogether, these tests help diagnose and monitor allergic conditions, identify specific allergens, and guide appropriate treatment strategies.', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2024-08-01 18:16:19', '2024-08-01 18:16:19', NULL, NULL),
(342, NULL, 'Milk allergy', 'EXP0342', '2800', '1290', 'Within 5 Days', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'A milk allergy test measures the body\'s immune response to proteins found in milk, typically through specific IgE antibody testing or skin prick testing.\r\n\r\n**Key Points:**\r\n\r\n- **Specific IgE Testing:** Measures the level of IgE antibodies in the blood specific to milk proteins, such as casein and whey. Elevated IgE levels indicate an allergic reaction to milk.\r\n  \r\n- **Skin Prick Test:** Involves exposing the skin to milk proteins to see if an allergic reaction occurs, such as redness or swelling.\r\n\r\n- **Clinical Relevance:** Helps diagnose milk allergy, distinguish it from lactose intolerance (which is not an immune response), and guide dietary modifications to avoid allergic reactions.\r\n\r\nThese tests are crucial for identifying milk allergies, managing symptoms, and preventing adverse reactions.', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2024-08-01 18:18:21', '2024-08-01 18:18:21', NULL, NULL),
(343, NULL, 'Allergy Panel 1 - Vegetarian + Non vegetarian/ Inhalants Drugs', 'EXP0343', '10000', '4990', 'Within 5 Days', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'An **allergy panel** is a diagnostic test used to identify specific allergens that may be causing allergic reactions. These panels can be categorized based on the type of allergens included, such as vegetarian or non-vegetarian allergens.\r\n\r\n**Vegetarian Allergy Panel:**\r\n- **Definition:** Tests for allergies to plant-based substances. This panel typically includes allergens from fruits, vegetables, nuts, seeds, grains, and pollen from plants.\r\n- **Purpose:** Identifies reactions to common vegetarian allergens, helping individuals manage symptoms related to foods or environmental factors of plant origin.\r\n\r\n**Non-Vegetarian Allergy Panel:**\r\n- **Definition:** Tests for allergies to animal-based substances. This panel usually includes allergens from meats, fish, shellfish, eggs, and dairy products.\r\n- **Purpose:** Detects sensitivities or allergies to common animal-derived foods and proteins, aiding in the management of allergic reactions to animal products.\r\n\r\nBoth panels use blood tests or skin prick tests to measure specific IgE antibodies or immune responses to the included allergens, helping diagnose and manage allergies effectively.', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2024-08-01 18:23:43', '2024-08-01 18:23:43', NULL, NULL),
(344, NULL, 'Allergy Specific IgG - Aspergillus Fumigatus', 'EXP0344', '2600', '1995', 'Within 7 Days', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '**Allergy-specific IgG** is a blood test that measures the presence of immunoglobulin G (IgG) antibodies against specific allergens. Unlike IgE antibodies, which are associated with immediate allergic reactions, IgG antibodies are generally linked to delayed-type hypersensitivity responses.\r\n\r\n**Key Points:**\r\n\r\n- **Function:** IgG antibodies bind to allergens and can indicate exposure or sensitivity to specific substances. Elevated levels of IgG against certain allergens may suggest chronic or delayed allergic reactions.\r\n- **Clinical Relevance:** This test is used to identify potential food intolerances or sensitivities, though its role in diagnosing classic allergies is limited. It may provide insights into underlying sensitivities or chronic conditions.\r\n- **Diagnostic Use:** It helps in understanding immune responses to specific allergens, guiding dietary or lifestyle adjustments. However, it is less commonly used than IgE testing for diagnosing immediate allergic reactions.\r\n\r\nThe allergy-specific IgG test is part of a broader approach to allergy testing, focusing on identifying potential delayed hypersensitivity reactions.', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2024-08-01 18:27:35', '2024-08-01 18:27:35', NULL, NULL),
(345, NULL, 'HOMA- IR - Insulin Resistance Index', 'EXP0345', '1700', '895', 'Same Day', 'Overnight fasting for 9-12 hours', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '**HOMA-IR (Homeostasis Model Assessment of Insulin Resistance)** is a method used to estimate insulin resistance, which is a condition where the body\'s cells do not respond effectively to insulin, leading to elevated blood glucose levels.\r\n\r\n**Key Points:**\r\n\r\n- **Calculation:** HOMA-IR is calculated using fasting plasma glucose and fasting insulin levels. The formula is: \\[ \\text{HOMA-IR} = \\frac{(\\text{Fasting Insulin} \\, (\\mu U/mL) \\times \\text{Fasting Glucose} \\, (mg/dL))}{405} \\]\r\n  \r\n- **Function:** It provides an estimate of how well the body is managing glucose metabolism and insulin sensitivity. Higher values indicate increased insulin resistance.\r\n\r\n- **Clinical Relevance:** HOMA-IR is used to assess metabolic conditions such as type 2 diabetes, metabolic syndrome, and prediabetes. It helps in evaluating the effectiveness of interventions aimed at improving insulin sensitivity.\r\n\r\n- **Interpretation:** Normal values vary, but elevated HOMA-IR suggests significant insulin resistance, requiring further investigation and management strategies to improve metabolic health.\r\n\r\nThe HOMA-IR index is a valuable tool for assessing and managing insulin resistance and related metabolic disorders.', NULL, '<p>**HOMA-IR (Homeostasis Model Assessment of Insulin Resistance)**       (insulin resistance)         ,             ,       </p><p>** :**</p><p>- **:** HOMA-IR                     : \\[ \\text{HOMA-IR} = \\frac{(\\text{ } \\, (\\mu U/mL) \\times \\text{ } \\, (mg/dL))}{405} \\]</p><p>- **:**                            </p><p>- ** :** HOMA-IR    2 ,  ,                                </p><p>- **:**      ,   HOMA-IR       ,           </p><p>HOMA-IR                 </p>', NULL, '2024-08-01 18:31:12', '2024-08-01 18:31:12', NULL, NULL),
(346, NULL, 'Cystatin C', 'EXP0346', '2100', '1380', 'Within 5 Days', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '**Cystatin C** is a protein produced by all nucleated cells and is filtered by the kidneys. It is measured in the blood to evaluate kidney function, particularly to assess glomerular filtration rate (GFR), which indicates how well the kidneys are filtering waste from the blood.\r\n\r\n**Key Points:**\r\n\r\n- **Function:** Cystatin C levels in the blood reflect kidney function. Unlike creatinine, which can be affected by muscle mass and other factors, cystatin C levels are less influenced by age, gender, or muscle mass.\r\n\r\n- **Clinical Relevance:** Elevated cystatin C levels can indicate impaired kidney function or reduced GFR, helping diagnose and monitor conditions such as chronic kidney disease (CKD) or acute kidney injury (AKI).\r\n\r\n- **Diagnostic Use:** The cystatin C test is often used in conjunction with other tests, such as serum creatinine and urine tests, to provide a more accurate assessment of kidney health.\r\n\r\n- **Interpretation:** Increased levels suggest decreased kidney function and can prompt further investigation and management to address underlying kidney issues.\r\n\r\nCystatin C is a valuable biomarker for assessing kidney function and diagnosing renal conditions.', NULL, '<p>**Cystatin C** is a protein used to assess kidney function. It is produced by all nucleated cells and filtered out of the blood by the kidneys. Measuring cystatin C levels provides an indication of the glomerular filtration rate (GFR), which reflects how effectively the kidneys are filtering waste.</p><p>**Key Points:**</p><p>- **Function:** Cystatin C levels in the blood are used to evaluate kidney function. It is less influenced by factors like muscle mass, age, and gender compared to creatinine, another common kidney function marker.<br>&nbsp;<br>- **Clinical Relevance:** Elevated cystatin C levels can signal impaired kidney function or decreased GFR, which is crucial for diagnosing and monitoring chronic kidney disease (CKD) and acute kidney injury (AKI).</p><p>- **Diagnostic Use:** The test is useful in providing a more accurate assessment of kidney health, especially in cases where creatinine levels may be misleading.</p><p>Cystatin C measurement is a valuable tool for evaluating and managing kidney function.</p>', '<p>** **                                            (GFR)    ,            </p><p>** :**</p><p>- **:**                           ,        ,     ,    <br>&nbsp;<br>- ** :**           GFR       ,     (CKD)     (AKI)        </p><p>- ** :**              ,           </p><p>                </p>', '2024-08-01 18:35:46', '2024-08-01 18:36:38', NULL, NULL),
(347, NULL, 'Stool Hanging Drop', 'EXP0347', '350', '180', 'Same Day', 'Overnight fasting for 9-12 hours', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '**Stool hanging drop** is a diagnostic test used to detect motile parasites in stool samples, such as Giardia lamblia and Entamoeba histolytica. A small amount of stool is mixed with a saline solution and placed on a glass slide under a coverslip, which is then examined under a microscope. The test allows for the observation of live parasites\' movement, aiding in the diagnosis of parasitic infections causing gastrointestinal symptoms.', NULL, '<p>**Stool hanging drop** is a laboratory technique used to identify motile parasites in stool samples. This test is particularly useful for diagnosing parasitic infections that cause gastrointestinal symptoms, such as Giardia lamblia, Entamoeba histolytica, and other protozoa.</p><p>**Key Points:**</p><p>- **Procedure:** A small amount of stool is mixed with a saline solution and placed on a microscope slide. A coverslip is carefully placed over the sample to create a \"hanging drop\" effect, where the sample forms a thin layer between the slide and the coverslip. This setup allows for observation of live, motile parasites under a microscope.<br>&nbsp;<br>- **Function:** The test helps in identifying parasites based on their movement and morphology, which is crucial for accurate diagnosis and treatment planning.</p><p>- **Clinical Relevance:** Stool hanging drop is used in parasitology to detect active infections by observing the movement of parasites, aiding in the diagnosis of infections like giardiasis and amoebiasis.</p><p>The stool hanging drop method is a valuable tool in diagnosing and managing parasitic infections.</p>', '<p>**  **                                       ,  Giardia lamblia, Entamoeba histolytica,   </p><p>** :**</p><p>- **:**                ,          </p><p>- ** :**                 ,             </p><p>              </p>', '2024-08-01 18:49:28', '2024-08-01 18:49:28', NULL, NULL),
(348, NULL, 'Hepatitis A Total', 'EXP0348', '1500', '695', 'Same Day', 'Fasting is not mandatory', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '**Hepatitis A total** measures the total antibodies (both IgM and IgG) against the hepatitis A virus (HAV) in the blood. This test assesses:\r\n\r\n- **Exposure:** Indicates if a person has been exposed to HAV at any time.\r\n- **Immunity:** Determines if a person has immunity from past infection or vaccination.\r\n\r\nA positive result shows past exposure or vaccination, while a negative result indicates no previous exposure or immunity.', NULL, '<p>**Hepatitis A** is a viral infection of the liver caused by the hepatitis A virus (HAV). It is typically transmitted through the ingestion of contaminated food or water. The infection causes inflammation of the liver, leading to symptoms such as jaundice, fatigue, abdominal pain, and nausea.</p><p>**Key Points:**</p><p>- **Transmission:** Spread primarily through fecal-oral route, often via contaminated food or water, or close contact with an infected person.<br>- **Symptoms:** Symptoms include jaundice, dark urine, pale stools, fever, and abdominal discomfort. Some people may be asymptomatic.<br>- **Diagnosis:** Diagnosed through blood tests that detect HAV antibodies (IgM and IgG) or the virus itself.<br>- **Prevention:** Prevented by vaccination and practicing good hygiene.</p><p>The infection usually resolves on its own without long-term consequences, but it can cause significant illness and discomfort.</p>', '<p>**Hepatitis A**         (HAV)      :                  ,  , ,         </p><p>** :**</p><p>- **:**     -    ,               <br>- **:**   ,    ,    , ,               <br>- **:**         ,  HAV  (IgM  IgG)      <br>- **:**             </p><p>             ,           </p>', '2024-08-01 18:56:21', '2024-08-01 18:56:21', NULL, NULL);
